WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:08.300 --> 00:00:15.859
In the year 1858, the French novelist

00:00:12.300 --> 00:00:18.660
Gustave Flaubert arrived in North Africa

00:00:15.859 --> 00:00:20.939
hoping to find inspiration for his

00:00:18.660 --> 00:00:24.180
latest book.

00:00:20.939 --> 00:00:26.580
Flaubert was a seasoned traveler, and a

00:00:24.180 --> 00:00:29.279
decade or so earlier had embarked on a

00:00:26.580 --> 00:00:31.980
grand tour of Cairo, Constantinople,

00:00:29.279 --> 00:00:34.500
Greece, and Italy.

00:00:31.980 --> 00:00:36.960
But the writer, who now departed on this

00:00:34.500 --> 00:00:38.100
new set of travels, was like a different

00:00:36.960 --> 00:00:41.100
man.

00:00:38.100 --> 00:00:44.040
Although only 37 years old, he was

00:00:41.100 --> 00:00:45.360
plagued by sickness and prone to fits of

00:00:44.040 --> 00:00:47.460
depression,

00:00:45.360 --> 00:00:49.620
and the novel he had been working on for

00:00:47.460 --> 00:00:51.780
the last year was threatening to drive

00:00:49.620 --> 00:00:53.879
him mad.

00:00:51.780 --> 00:00:56.940
The publication of his most famous work

00:00:53.879 --> 00:01:00.059
two years before, the novel Madame Bovary,

00:00:56.940 --> 00:01:01.800
had brought him fame and wealth. But now

00:01:00.059 --> 00:01:03.960
he was attempting to write a piece of

00:01:01.800 --> 00:01:05.339
fiction quite unlike anything he had

00:01:03.960 --> 00:01:07.500
ever attempted.

00:01:05.339 --> 00:01:10.020
It would be a story from classical

00:01:07.500 --> 00:01:12.720
history that took place in an empire

00:01:10.020 --> 00:01:15.000
that had once flourished in the north of

00:01:12.720 --> 00:01:17.700
Africa, had become the most powerful

00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:21.119
society in the ancient world, and then

00:01:17.700 --> 00:01:24.000
had vanished in its entirety more than

00:01:21.119 --> 00:01:26.280
2,000 years ago, an empire that had been

00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:28.619
largely forgotten beside the more

00:01:26.280 --> 00:01:30.600
well-studied societies of Classical

00:01:28.619 --> 00:01:34.619
Greece and Rome.

00:01:30.600 --> 00:01:36.659
This was the empire of Carthage.

00:01:34.619 --> 00:01:39.479
He had spent the last months locked up

00:01:36.659 --> 00:01:42.180
in his study like a hermit, surrounded by

00:01:39.479 --> 00:01:44.579
the work of ancient historians, trying to

00:01:42.180 --> 00:01:45.840
bring the lost city of Carthage back to

00:01:44.579 --> 00:01:48.840
life.

00:01:45.840 --> 00:01:50.280
But the writing just wouldn't come, as he

00:01:48.840 --> 00:01:52.259
wrote to his friend,

00:01:50.280 --> 00:01:56.159
Ernest Feydeau.

00:01:52.259 --> 00:01:59.100
I'm done for, my friend, done for!

00:01:56.159 --> 00:02:02.759
The past month, I found it impossible to

00:01:59.100 --> 00:02:04.979
write. I can't find a single word.

00:02:02.759 --> 00:02:07.619
Just think of what I've let myself in

00:02:04.979 --> 00:02:10.560
for, to resuscitate an entire

00:02:07.619 --> 00:02:12.540
civilization with nothing whatsoever to

00:02:10.560 --> 00:02:14.280
go on.

00:02:12.540 --> 00:02:16.500
Flaubert made the decision that

00:02:14.280 --> 00:02:18.780
something would have to change.

00:02:16.500 --> 00:02:22.560
He wrote of his intentions to his friend,

00:02:18.780 --> 00:02:25.739
Mademoiselle Leroyer de Chantepie.

00:02:22.560 --> 00:02:28.680
I absolutely must take a trip to Africa;

00:02:25.739 --> 00:02:30.420
so, toward the end of March, I'll return

00:02:28.680 --> 00:02:33.780
to the land of dates.

00:02:30.420 --> 00:02:35.160
Once again, Iíll live on horseback and sleep

00:02:33.780 --> 00:02:38.760
under a tent.

00:02:35.160 --> 00:02:41.459
I need only to go to El Kef and explore

00:02:38.760 --> 00:02:43.379
the environs of Carthage in order to

00:02:41.459 --> 00:02:46.940
acquaint myself thoroughly with the

00:02:43.379 --> 00:02:46.940
landscapes I'll be describing.

00:02:47.099 --> 00:02:52.620
When he arrived in the French colony of Tunisia,

00:02:50.280 --> 00:02:55.140
Flaubert jotted down hurried impressions in his

00:02:52.620 --> 00:02:58.019
notebooks as he explored the ruins of

00:02:55.140 --> 00:03:00.959
the ancient cities of Utica and Carthage,

00:02:58.019 --> 00:03:05.000
now all but buried beneath the modern

00:03:00.959 --> 00:03:05.000
Tunisian capital of Tunis.

00:03:05.640 --> 00:03:11.159
In the green wheat full of flowering

00:03:07.920 --> 00:03:13.739
poppies, the road climbs a little, sloping

00:03:11.159 --> 00:03:17.220
to the left, and arrives at a valley;

00:03:13.739 --> 00:03:20.760
flat plains in the middle, at a league's

00:03:17.220 --> 00:03:24.000
distance, ruins like palm trees, and here

00:03:20.760 --> 00:03:27.840
and there, blocks of masonry. We are

00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:30.659
walking on the remains of a Roman road.

00:03:27.840 --> 00:03:33.420
As he walked among the ruined walls of

00:03:30.659 --> 00:03:36.120
this ancient city, Flaubert felt himself

00:03:33.420 --> 00:03:37.980
connected to the ancient people he had

00:03:36.120 --> 00:03:40.620
been trying to write about,

00:03:37.980 --> 00:03:43.080
and saw ways of life that must have

00:03:40.620 --> 00:03:45.180
remained almost unchanged since the days

00:03:43.080 --> 00:03:48.360
of Carthage.

00:03:45.180 --> 00:03:51.659
In the South; the village of Sidi-bou-Said,

00:03:48.360 --> 00:03:52.799
the sea behind like a great block of

00:03:51.659 --> 00:03:56.400
indigo.

00:03:52.799 --> 00:03:59.819
All Carthage now stretches out before me.

00:03:56.400 --> 00:04:03.239
A camel on a terrace, turning a well;

00:03:59.819 --> 00:04:05.459
flies are buzzing, weeds hang from the

00:04:03.239 --> 00:04:07.860
halls like chandeliers.

00:04:05.459 --> 00:04:11.120
A bird takes flight with the sound of a

00:04:07.860 --> 00:04:15.540
wing; another sings; very fine dust,

00:04:11.120 --> 00:04:19.880
silence, green marks on the walls, livid

00:04:15.540 --> 00:04:19.880
and thick water in some basins.

00:04:20.459 --> 00:04:24.479
By the time he had finished his

00:04:22.199 --> 00:04:27.360
wanderings among the Carthaginian ruins

00:04:24.479 --> 00:04:29.460
of Tunisia, Flaubert had decided to

00:04:27.360 --> 00:04:33.960
completely rewrite the draft of his book,

00:04:29.460 --> 00:04:37.560
as he writes to Mademoiselle de Chantepie.

00:04:33.960 --> 00:04:40.259
Everything I had done on my novel has to

00:04:37.560 --> 00:04:41.520
be done over. I was on the wrong track

00:04:40.259 --> 00:04:44.520
entirely.

00:04:41.520 --> 00:04:46.620
So, it turns out that a little over a

00:04:44.520 --> 00:04:49.740
year since I first had the idea for the

00:04:46.620 --> 00:04:52.680
book, and after working hard on it most

00:04:49.740 --> 00:04:54.860
of that time, I am still only at the

00:04:52.680 --> 00:04:54.860
beginning.

00:04:56.400 --> 00:05:01.320
Armed with his Tunisian notebooks,

00:04:59.040 --> 00:05:04.560
Flaubert finished his book four years later,

00:05:01.320 --> 00:05:06.479
and it was published under the title of

00:05:04.560 --> 00:05:09.600
Salammbo.

00:05:06.479 --> 00:05:12.840
The book was an enormous success.

00:05:09.600 --> 00:05:15.840
It inspired plays and later even silent

00:05:12.840 --> 00:05:18.660
films, and it is credited with renewing

00:05:15.840 --> 00:05:20.940
public interest in a city and a culture

00:05:18.660 --> 00:05:23.400
that had once been considered a side

00:05:20.940 --> 00:05:26.460
note of history.

00:05:23.400 --> 00:05:29.340
As Flaubert walked those ruined walls

00:05:26.460 --> 00:05:31.380
and sunken harbors, as he kicked his way

00:05:29.340 --> 00:05:34.139
through the dust and scree of the

00:05:31.380 --> 00:05:37.259
crumbling city ruins, he must have asked

00:05:34.139 --> 00:05:39.780
himself again and again; what did it feel

00:05:37.259 --> 00:05:43.320
like to walk the streets of that ancient

00:05:39.780 --> 00:05:45.539
city? What was it like to see Carthage at

00:05:43.320 --> 00:05:48.060
the height of its golden age,

00:05:45.539 --> 00:05:51.020
and what would it have felt like to see

00:05:48.060 --> 00:05:55.080
this entire city, its streets and houses,

00:05:51.020 --> 00:05:58.560
its temples and theaters, its harbors and

00:05:55.080 --> 00:06:01.080
its homes, utterly destroyed and buried

00:05:58.560 --> 00:06:04.080
in dust and ash?

00:06:33.380 --> 00:06:37.860
My name's Paul Cooper, and you're

00:06:36.060 --> 00:06:39.539
listening to the Fall of Civilizations

00:06:37.860 --> 00:06:42.240
Podcast.

00:06:39.539 --> 00:06:44.699
Each episode, I look at a civilization of

00:06:42.240 --> 00:06:47.400
the past that rose to glory and then

00:06:44.699 --> 00:06:49.560
collapsed into the ashes of history.

00:06:47.400 --> 00:06:52.319
I want to ask, what did they have in

00:06:49.560 --> 00:06:54.419
common? What led to their fall, and what

00:06:52.319 --> 00:06:57.120
did it feel like to be a person alive at

00:06:54.419 --> 00:06:58.620
the time who witnessed the end of their

00:06:57.120 --> 00:07:01.199
world?

00:06:58.620 --> 00:07:03.240
In this episode, I want to tell one of

00:07:01.199 --> 00:07:05.819
the most dramatic stories to come down

00:07:03.240 --> 00:07:09.419
to us from the ancient world, the rise

00:07:05.819 --> 00:07:12.300
and fall of the empire of Carthage.

00:07:09.419 --> 00:07:14.160
I want to show how this city rose out of

00:07:12.300 --> 00:07:16.919
the Phoenician states of the Eastern

00:07:14.160 --> 00:07:19.380
Mediterranean, and set out on voyages of

00:07:16.919 --> 00:07:22.080
discovery and settlement that put them

00:07:19.380 --> 00:07:24.300
at the center of the ancient world.

00:07:22.080 --> 00:07:26.460
I want to describe the unique culture

00:07:24.300 --> 00:07:29.520
that flourished on the shores of North

00:07:26.460 --> 00:07:31.680
Africa, and I want to tell the story of

00:07:29.520 --> 00:07:34.620
how the city of Carthage was destroyed

00:07:31.680 --> 00:07:36.800
and its memory nearly wiped from the

00:07:34.620 --> 00:07:36.800
Earth.

00:07:49.639 --> 00:07:55.919
The Mediterranean Sea is a vast body of

00:07:53.460 --> 00:07:59.039
salt water that lies between the

00:07:55.919 --> 00:08:02.039
continents of Europe and Africa.

00:07:59.039 --> 00:08:04.800
It's by far the largest inland sea on

00:08:02.039 --> 00:08:07.620
the planet, stretching around 4,000

00:08:04.800 --> 00:08:09.419
kilometers from end to end, and in the

00:08:07.620 --> 00:08:12.240
West, it's connected to the Atlantic

00:08:09.419 --> 00:08:15.199
Ocean by a thin opening of the Straits

00:08:12.240 --> 00:08:15.199
of Gibraltar. The coastline

00:08:16.199 --> 00:08:22.500
of this sea is more than 46,000

00:08:19.919 --> 00:08:25.440
kilometers long, or enough to wrap around

00:08:22.500 --> 00:08:28.020
the entire circumference of the planet,

00:08:25.440 --> 00:08:30.539
and this coastline has provided a home

00:08:28.020 --> 00:08:32.820
to countless cultures and civilizations

00:08:30.539 --> 00:08:35.219
over history.

00:08:32.820 --> 00:08:37.320
One of these cultures emerged on the

00:08:35.219 --> 00:08:40.620
easternmost corner of the Mediterranean

00:08:37.320 --> 00:08:43.740
coast, on a stony stretch of shore in

00:08:40.620 --> 00:08:46.260
what is today Lebanon, overlooked by

00:08:43.740 --> 00:08:47.459
towering mountains covered in cedar

00:08:46.260 --> 00:08:50.279
forest.

00:08:47.459 --> 00:08:52.800
Here, a series of city-states rose up

00:08:50.279 --> 00:08:54.959
more than 4,000 years ago that would

00:08:52.800 --> 00:08:58.440
give rise to a culture that would one

00:08:54.959 --> 00:09:01.080
day be called the Phoenicians.

00:08:58.440 --> 00:09:04.940
The largest of these cities were named

00:09:01.080 --> 00:09:07.440
Tyre, Sidon, and Byblos.

00:09:04.940 --> 00:09:09.720
Pinched as they were between the waves

00:09:07.440 --> 00:09:12.180
to the west and the forested mountains

00:09:09.720 --> 00:09:14.940
to the east, the territories they ruled

00:09:12.180 --> 00:09:17.700
over were never large, but this

00:09:14.940 --> 00:09:19.320
relatively isolated geography also meant

00:09:17.700 --> 00:09:21.980
that they were somewhat protected from

00:09:19.320 --> 00:09:21.980
invaders.

00:09:22.740 --> 00:09:27.180
The people we now think of as Phoenician

00:09:24.779 --> 00:09:30.120
wouldn't have ever used that word.

00:09:27.180 --> 00:09:32.760
Phoenician is a term invented later by

00:09:30.120 --> 00:09:34.920
their great rivals, the Greeks, and it's

00:09:32.760 --> 00:09:37.860
unclear if these cities ever thought of

00:09:34.920 --> 00:09:40.320
themselves as a unified people.

00:09:37.860 --> 00:09:42.839
They had a common Phoenician language

00:09:40.320 --> 00:09:45.440
and were united by the worship of

00:09:42.839 --> 00:09:49.320
certain gods, among them, Baal Hammon,

00:09:45.440 --> 00:09:52.200
a heroic god named Melqart, and his wife

00:09:49.320 --> 00:09:54.720
Astarte, but there's very little in the

00:09:52.200 --> 00:09:58.200
historical record to suggest a common

00:09:54.720 --> 00:10:00.660
identity, architecture, or literature.

00:09:58.200 --> 00:10:03.839
Even the Greek word Phoenician has a

00:10:00.660 --> 00:10:07.019
somewhat mysterious origin. In the

00:10:03.839 --> 00:10:10.019
earliest texts such as Homer's Iliad and

00:10:07.019 --> 00:10:12.779
Odyssey, the word Phoinike is used to

00:10:10.019 --> 00:10:15.779
describe a particular color of purple or

00:10:12.779 --> 00:10:18.540
crimson, and it is also used to describe

00:10:15.779 --> 00:10:21.240
a date palm, possibly due to the reddish

00:10:18.540 --> 00:10:23.940
color of its fruit when ripe.

00:10:21.240 --> 00:10:26.519
So, it's possible that the word came

00:10:23.940 --> 00:10:29.339
to be used as a result of one of the

00:10:26.519 --> 00:10:32.060
Phoenicianís earliest and most successful

00:10:29.339 --> 00:10:32.060
industries.

00:10:35.880 --> 00:10:41.100
The Phoenicians of Tyre and other cities

00:10:38.640 --> 00:10:43.980
were the first people to color their

00:10:41.100 --> 00:10:47.040
clothes with a particular kind of dye

00:10:43.980 --> 00:10:51.360
derived from the bodies of predatory sea

00:10:47.040 --> 00:10:54.300
snails known as the Murex, or rock snail.

00:10:51.360 --> 00:10:57.060
These snails produce their dye as a

00:10:54.300 --> 00:10:59.579
defense mechanism against predators, and

00:10:57.060 --> 00:11:02.399
depending on the species, can produce a

00:10:59.579 --> 00:11:04.680
vivid red or purple color quite unlike

00:11:02.399 --> 00:11:06.060
anything else available in the ancient

00:11:04.680 --> 00:11:08.220
world.

00:11:06.060 --> 00:11:11.100
From the moment these dyes were first

00:11:08.220 --> 00:11:13.680
used by Phoenicians around the 16th

00:11:11.100 --> 00:11:15.899
century BC, their colors became

00:11:13.680 --> 00:11:18.180
immediately sought after.

00:11:15.899 --> 00:11:20.940
But the process of producing these dyes

00:11:18.180 --> 00:11:23.519
was difficult and costly.

00:11:20.940 --> 00:11:25.920
It could take more than 50 kilograms of

00:11:23.519 --> 00:11:29.519
these snails to make a single gram of

00:11:25.920 --> 00:11:30.839
dye, and so, these fabrics were extremely

00:11:29.519 --> 00:11:33.360
expensive.

00:11:30.839 --> 00:11:36.420
The color purple would soon become

00:11:33.360 --> 00:11:39.120
associated with enormous wealth, and as a

00:11:36.420 --> 00:11:41.339
consequence, with royalty.

00:11:39.120 --> 00:11:44.279
This color would be known as Tyrian

00:11:41.339 --> 00:11:48.000
Purple, after the Phoenician city of Tyre,

00:11:44.279 --> 00:11:50.459
and later, Imperial Purple. It would dye

00:11:48.000 --> 00:11:54.360
the robes of the emperors of Assyria,

00:11:50.459 --> 00:11:57.360
Rome, and later, Byzantium.

00:11:54.360 --> 00:11:59.880
The first-century Roman writer, Pliny the

00:11:57.360 --> 00:12:03.300
Elder, writes about the effect this color

00:11:59.880 --> 00:12:06.540
had on anyone who saw it.

00:12:03.300 --> 00:12:09.480
For purple, the rods and axes of Rome

00:12:06.540 --> 00:12:11.880
clear a path, and it likewise marks the

00:12:09.480 --> 00:12:14.760
dignity of boyhood. It distinguishes

00:12:11.880 --> 00:12:17.459
senator from noble, and it is summoned to

00:12:14.760 --> 00:12:19.740
secure the favor of the gods. It

00:12:17.459 --> 00:12:23.040
illuminates every garment, and on the

00:12:19.740 --> 00:12:25.640
triumphal robe, it is blended with gold.

00:12:23.040 --> 00:12:28.320
But why the price?

00:12:25.640 --> 00:12:31.200
It's possible then that the term

00:12:28.320 --> 00:12:33.959
Phoinike came to be used by the Greeks

00:12:31.200 --> 00:12:36.839
to describe these traders from the rocky

00:12:33.959 --> 00:12:39.300
coast of Lebanon as the makers of purple,

00:12:36.839 --> 00:12:41.700
or the purple people.

00:12:39.300 --> 00:12:43.980
The name of the mythical creature, the

00:12:41.700 --> 00:12:46.980
phoenix, an immortal bird with red

00:12:43.980 --> 00:12:49.459
feathers, also seems to derive from the

00:12:46.980 --> 00:12:49.459
same word.

00:12:49.560 --> 00:12:54.480
With their dye industry booming, the

00:12:52.320 --> 00:12:56.519
Phoenicians began to set out on ever

00:12:54.480 --> 00:12:59.339
longer voyages out into the

00:12:56.519 --> 00:13:02.639
Mediterranean Sea, all in search of

00:12:59.339 --> 00:13:05.100
ever more of these priceless snails, and

00:13:02.639 --> 00:13:08.940
these longer voyages would require new

00:13:05.100 --> 00:13:11.279
developments in shipbuilding.

00:13:08.940 --> 00:13:13.980
Since as early as the third millennium

00:13:11.279 --> 00:13:16.860
BC, Phoenician sailors from the city of

00:13:13.980 --> 00:13:19.680
Byblos had developed ships with curved

00:13:16.860 --> 00:13:21.779
hulls perfectly suited for traveling on

00:13:19.680 --> 00:13:24.480
the waves, and they had developed

00:13:21.779 --> 00:13:28.200
techniques for waterproofing the hulls

00:13:24.480 --> 00:13:31.680
of their ships using bitumen or pitch.

00:13:28.200 --> 00:13:34.980
In the Hebrew Bible, the 6th century BC

00:13:31.680 --> 00:13:38.940
Book of Ezekiel contains one poetic

00:13:34.980 --> 00:13:41.519
description of a Phoenician ship.

00:13:38.940 --> 00:13:43.980
They made all your timbers of juniper

00:13:41.519 --> 00:13:46.920
from Senir. They took a cedar from

00:13:43.980 --> 00:13:50.399
Lebanon to make a mast for you.

00:13:46.920 --> 00:13:53.040
Of oaks from Bashan they made your oars;

00:13:50.399 --> 00:13:57.060
of cypress wood from the coasts of Cyprus

00:13:53.040 --> 00:13:59.700
they made your deck, adorned with ivory.

00:13:57.060 --> 00:14:02.700
Fine embroidered linen from Egypt was

00:13:59.700 --> 00:14:05.339
your sail and served as your banner;

00:14:02.700 --> 00:14:09.500
your awnings were of blue and purple

00:14:05.339 --> 00:14:09.500
from the coasts of Elishah.

00:14:09.839 --> 00:14:14.760
The Phoenicians were also some of the

00:14:12.120 --> 00:14:18.660
earliest people to notice the pole star,

00:14:14.760 --> 00:14:20.579
or Polaris, a star that happens to align

00:14:18.660 --> 00:14:22.920
more or less perfectly with the

00:14:20.579 --> 00:14:25.380
rotational axis of the Earth.

00:14:22.920 --> 00:14:28.019
This means that while all other stars

00:14:25.380 --> 00:14:30.899
appear to rotate in the sky throughout

00:14:28.019 --> 00:14:34.500
the night as the Earth turns, the pole

00:14:30.899 --> 00:14:37.500
star remains more or less fixed in place.

00:14:34.500 --> 00:14:40.199
This made it exceptionally useful as a

00:14:37.500 --> 00:14:41.940
navigation tool, a fixed reference point

00:14:40.199 --> 00:14:44.639
in the sky.

00:14:41.940 --> 00:14:50.420
In Greek, this star would even come to be

00:14:44.639 --> 00:14:50.420
known as Phoinike, or the Phoenician Star.

00:14:51.120 --> 00:14:55.740
The Phoenicianís early voyages around the

00:14:53.399 --> 00:14:58.620
Mediterranean led to them encountering

00:14:55.740 --> 00:15:01.320
many other peoples, and among these, they

00:14:58.620 --> 00:15:04.260
began to cultivate a reputation as

00:15:01.320 --> 00:15:06.540
uncompromising traders and shrewd

00:15:04.260 --> 00:15:10.699
businessmen, something that seems to have

00:15:06.540 --> 00:15:13.980
gained them some degree of unpopularity.

00:15:10.699 --> 00:15:17.160
Homer's Odyssey, probably written down in

00:15:13.980 --> 00:15:19.800
the 7th or 8th Century BC from even more

00:15:17.160 --> 00:15:22.860
ancient oral traditions, describes the

00:15:19.800 --> 00:15:25.800
Phoenicians as cunning and untrustworthy

00:15:22.860 --> 00:15:28.320
in contrast to the supposedly noble

00:15:25.800 --> 00:15:31.560
Greeks.

00:15:28.320 --> 00:15:34.019
Thither came Phoenicians, men famed for

00:15:31.560 --> 00:15:37.560
their ships, greedy knaves, bringing

00:15:34.019 --> 00:15:40.079
countless trinkets in their black ship.

00:15:37.560 --> 00:15:43.380
It seems the Phoenicians had become

00:15:40.079 --> 00:15:46.500
adept at metalworking, too. The following

00:15:43.380 --> 00:15:49.560
passage in Homer's Odyssey describes an

00:15:46.500 --> 00:15:52.620
ornate bowl brought by traders from the

00:15:49.560 --> 00:15:55.680
Phoenician city of Sidon.

00:15:52.620 --> 00:15:59.160
Then the son of Peleus set forth other

00:15:55.680 --> 00:16:02.339
prizes; a mixing bowl of silver, richly

00:15:59.160 --> 00:16:05.339
wrought; in beauty, far the goodliest in

00:16:02.339 --> 00:16:08.519
all the Earth, Sidonians, well skilled in

00:16:05.339 --> 00:16:10.800
deft handiwork, had watered cunningly, and

00:16:08.519 --> 00:16:14.959
men of the Phoenicians brought it over

00:16:10.800 --> 00:16:14.959
the murky deep, and landed it in harbor.

00:16:18.300 --> 00:16:22.860
As a seafaring people, the Phoenicians

00:16:21.180 --> 00:16:25.440
had a clear preference for building

00:16:22.860 --> 00:16:28.500
their cities on narrow, easily-defended

00:16:25.440 --> 00:16:30.720
peninsulas, and where possible, on islands

00:16:28.500 --> 00:16:33.540
set just offshore.

00:16:30.720 --> 00:16:36.120
Their most influential city of Tyre was

00:16:33.540 --> 00:16:39.420
a perfect example, located on a small

00:16:36.120 --> 00:16:42.420
island just off the rocky coast.

00:16:39.420 --> 00:16:45.360
In the Hebrew Bible, the prophet Ezekiel

00:16:42.420 --> 00:16:47.579
gives us a sense of the trade that the

00:16:45.360 --> 00:16:50.279
people of Tyre drove with their

00:16:47.579 --> 00:16:52.320
surrounding neighbors.

00:16:50.279 --> 00:16:54.839
Tarshish did business with you because

00:16:52.320 --> 00:16:58.019
of your great wealth of goods. They

00:16:54.839 --> 00:16:59.579
exchanged silver, iron, tin, and lead for

00:16:58.019 --> 00:17:01.920
your merchandise.

00:16:59.579 --> 00:17:04.559
Greece, Tubal, and Meshek did business

00:17:01.920 --> 00:17:07.679
with you. They traded human beings and

00:17:04.559 --> 00:17:10.140
articles of bronze for your wares. Men of

00:17:07.679 --> 00:17:13.679
Beth Togarmah exchanged chariot horses,

00:17:10.140 --> 00:17:16.500
cavalry horses, and mules. Aram exchanged

00:17:13.679 --> 00:17:20.400
turquoise, purple fabric, embroidered work,

00:17:16.500 --> 00:17:22.919
fine linen, coral, and rubies. Judah and

00:17:20.400 --> 00:17:25.740
Israel traded with you; they exchanged

00:17:22.919 --> 00:17:28.220
wheat from Minnith, honey, olive oil, and

00:17:25.740 --> 00:17:28.220
balm.

00:17:29.220 --> 00:17:34.200
While the natural defenses of their

00:17:31.919 --> 00:17:36.240
geography had kept cities like Tyre

00:17:34.200 --> 00:17:40.520
independent for much of their history,

00:17:36.240 --> 00:17:40.520
this wasn't to last forever.

00:17:42.240 --> 00:17:49.080
The first millennium BC was an age of

00:17:45.419 --> 00:17:51.480
iron and an age of empires, and soon the

00:17:49.080 --> 00:17:54.059
Phoenicians found themselves in a world

00:17:51.480 --> 00:17:55.620
of increasingly violent and aggressive

00:17:54.059 --> 00:17:58.320
neighbors.

00:17:55.620 --> 00:18:02.179
Perhaps the most terrifying of these was

00:17:58.320 --> 00:18:02.179
the power of the Assyrian Empire.

00:18:04.140 --> 00:18:09.840
From its heartlands in what is today

00:18:06.539 --> 00:18:12.480
Iraq, the Assyrian war machine would

00:18:09.840 --> 00:18:14.520
periodically stretch its power right to

00:18:12.480 --> 00:18:17.280
the coast of the Mediterranean, and

00:18:14.520 --> 00:18:20.039
threatened to engulf the Phoenicians.

00:18:17.280 --> 00:18:22.860
One inscription from the palace of an

00:18:20.039 --> 00:18:25.440
Assyrian king gives just one example of

00:18:22.860 --> 00:18:27.660
the typical fate of a city conquered by

00:18:25.440 --> 00:18:31.500
the Assyrians.

00:18:27.660 --> 00:18:34.620
That city I destroyed -- I flung my

00:18:31.500 --> 00:18:37.380
soldiers like lightning upon them.

00:18:34.620 --> 00:18:41.039
I piled up heaps of heads in front of

00:18:37.380 --> 00:18:45.360
his great gate. Bands of captive soldiers

00:18:41.039 --> 00:18:46.440
I impaled on stakes on every side of his

00:18:45.360 --> 00:18:50.340
city.

00:18:46.440 --> 00:18:54.860
His palm trees I cut down, and from the

00:18:50.340 --> 00:18:54.860
city of Amidi, I departed.

00:18:55.080 --> 00:18:58.980
The Phoenicians had every reason to be

00:18:57.840 --> 00:19:02.280
nervous.

00:18:58.980 --> 00:19:05.640
At the start of the 8th century BC, the

00:19:02.280 --> 00:19:08.340
Assyrian king Adad-Nirari III conquered

00:19:05.640 --> 00:19:12.120
the territory of Northern Syria, as he

00:19:08.340 --> 00:19:14.400
boasts in his royal palace inscriptions.

00:19:12.120 --> 00:19:17.100
Conquering from the Siluna mountain of

00:19:14.400 --> 00:19:20.820
the Rising Sun and from the banks of the

00:19:17.100 --> 00:19:23.940
Euphrates, the country of Hatti,  Amurra in

00:19:20.820 --> 00:19:27.179
its full extent, the land of Tyre, the

00:19:23.940 --> 00:19:30.840
land of Sidon, the land of Israel, the

00:19:27.179 --> 00:19:33.480
land of Edom, the land of Philistia; I

00:19:30.840 --> 00:19:35.880
made them submit to my feet, imposing

00:19:33.480 --> 00:19:38.039
upon them tribute.

00:19:35.880 --> 00:19:39.960
The Assyrians were now breathing

00:19:38.039 --> 00:19:42.600
directly down the necks of the

00:19:39.960 --> 00:19:44.880
Phoenician cities of the coast, but as

00:19:42.600 --> 00:19:47.280
time went on, the Phoenicians were able

00:19:44.880 --> 00:19:49.679
to carve out a niche for themselves that

00:19:47.280 --> 00:19:54.020
ensured they were quite simply too

00:19:49.679 --> 00:19:54.020
useful for the Assyrians to destroy.

00:19:58.740 --> 00:20:03.539
The Mediterranean Sea had long been an

00:20:01.200 --> 00:20:05.700
insurmountable challenge to many of the

00:20:03.539 --> 00:20:09.000
region's great powers.

00:20:05.700 --> 00:20:11.640
The Assyrians referred to it as Id-marrati,

00:20:09.000 --> 00:20:14.100
or the Bitter River, which they believed

00:20:11.640 --> 00:20:16.679
to flow around the whole Earth,

00:20:14.100 --> 00:20:20.760
while the Egyptians referred to it as

00:20:16.679 --> 00:20:23.940
Wadj-Wer, or the Great Green.

00:20:20.760 --> 00:20:26.460
These Empires were freshwater river

00:20:23.940 --> 00:20:29.400
cultures and navigated the waters of

00:20:26.460 --> 00:20:31.620
their rivers in flat-bottomed barges.

00:20:29.400 --> 00:20:35.820
For this reason, they had always remained

00:20:31.620 --> 00:20:38.400
wary of the rougher waters of the sea.

00:20:35.820 --> 00:20:40.679
Assyria relied heavily on many of the

00:20:38.400 --> 00:20:44.100
commodities brought into the region by

00:20:40.679 --> 00:20:47.340
Phoenician traders; incense, silver, and

00:20:44.100 --> 00:20:49.740
purple dye for their palaces, bronze and

00:20:47.340 --> 00:20:52.260
iron for their armies.

00:20:49.740 --> 00:20:55.799
So, Assyria offered the cities of

00:20:52.260 --> 00:20:57.900
Tyre and Sidon something of a deal.

00:20:55.799 --> 00:21:00.840
They would be allowed a degree of

00:20:57.900 --> 00:21:03.000
independence so long as they ensured a

00:21:00.840 --> 00:21:06.000
constant flow of metals and other

00:21:03.000 --> 00:21:08.640
resources into Assyria, and so long as

00:21:06.000 --> 00:21:11.220
they acted as a kind of navy for hire,

00:21:08.640 --> 00:21:14.039
providing their ships and sailors to

00:21:11.220 --> 00:21:17.039
Assyria in times of war.

00:21:14.039 --> 00:21:19.220
The Phoenicians had little choice but to

00:21:17.039 --> 00:21:19.220
accept,

00:21:19.260 --> 00:21:25.500
but there was one problem; the Assyrian

00:21:22.620 --> 00:21:27.900
demands for metal were truly staggering,

00:21:25.500 --> 00:21:30.600
and if they were going to be met, it

00:21:27.900 --> 00:21:33.740
would require a drastic expansion of the

00:21:30.600 --> 00:21:33.740
Phoenician trade network.

00:21:36.480 --> 00:21:41.760
At first, the Phoenicians set up simple

00:21:39.120 --> 00:21:44.159
trading posts anywhere they could find

00:21:41.760 --> 00:21:46.860
good supplies of metal.

00:21:44.159 --> 00:21:49.500
Archeology shows they set up trading

00:21:46.860 --> 00:21:52.260
communities in Cyprus to take advantage

00:21:49.500 --> 00:21:54.299
of its rich stores of copper, and in

00:21:52.260 --> 00:21:57.179
Sardinia, the Mediterranean's second-

00:21:54.299 --> 00:21:59.220
-largest island, rich in copper, iron,

00:21:57.179 --> 00:22:02.280
silver, and lead.

00:21:59.220 --> 00:22:04.260
At these sites, local people usually did

00:22:02.280 --> 00:22:06.720
all the actual mining, while the

00:22:04.260 --> 00:22:09.960
Phoenicians simply turned up to buy the

00:22:06.720 --> 00:22:12.659
goods and take them away by ship. From

00:22:09.960 --> 00:22:14.520
Cyprus and Sardinia, Phoenician sailors

00:22:12.659 --> 00:22:15.659
pushed on into the west of the

00:22:14.520 --> 00:22:18.780
Mediterranean

00:22:15.659 --> 00:22:21.360
and set up a small colony of Utica in

00:22:18.780 --> 00:22:23.880
North Africa, and even reached southern

00:22:21.360 --> 00:22:26.760
Spain, where they found that the mines

00:22:23.880 --> 00:22:28.820
practically overflowed with silver, iron,

00:22:26.760 --> 00:22:30.900
and other metals.

00:22:28.820 --> 00:22:33.000
Archaeologists have found huge

00:22:30.900 --> 00:22:35.820
Phoenician furnaces in this region,

00:22:33.000 --> 00:22:38.520
designed for smelting metal ingots for

00:22:35.820 --> 00:22:41.520
transportation on an industrial scale,

00:22:38.520 --> 00:22:44.340
all to satisfy the demands of the

00:22:41.520 --> 00:22:46.919
fearsome Assyrian kings.

00:22:44.340 --> 00:22:48.720
Before long, the Phoenicians were sailing

00:22:46.919 --> 00:22:51.299
out through the Straits of Gibraltar,

00:22:48.720 --> 00:22:54.120
then known as the Pillars of Hercules,

00:22:51.299 --> 00:22:56.820
and out into the Atlantic Ocean.

00:22:54.120 --> 00:22:59.039
They set up a colony at Lixus, on the

00:22:56.820 --> 00:23:01.440
western coast of Morocco, and pushed

00:22:59.039 --> 00:23:03.419
further down the coast to settle what is

00:23:01.440 --> 00:23:07.140
now the Moroccan port town of

00:23:03.419 --> 00:23:09.740
Essaouira, more than 4,000 kilometers from

00:23:07.140 --> 00:23:09.740
their homeland.

00:23:12.059 --> 00:23:16.020
To finance these expeditions, the

00:23:14.520 --> 00:23:18.539
Phoenicians developed innovative

00:23:16.020 --> 00:23:21.320
monetary systems that in some ways

00:23:18.539 --> 00:23:24.299
represented a form of ancient capitalism.

00:23:21.320 --> 00:23:27.179
Phoenician society was dominated by

00:23:24.299 --> 00:23:29.400
powerful trading firms usually run by a

00:23:27.179 --> 00:23:31.799
certain family, and they pioneered the

00:23:29.400 --> 00:23:34.440
use of interest-bearing loans for

00:23:31.799 --> 00:23:37.380
voyages, even developing Maritime

00:23:34.440 --> 00:23:40.140
insurance policies, which paid out if

00:23:37.380 --> 00:23:43.020
your ships were destroyed in a storm or

00:23:40.140 --> 00:23:45.000
plundered by pirates.

00:23:43.020 --> 00:23:47.100
But perhaps the greatest of their

00:23:45.000 --> 00:23:48.480
innovations was something that we use

00:23:47.100 --> 00:23:52.340
every day,

00:23:48.480 --> 00:23:52.340
and that is the alphabet.

00:23:53.580 --> 00:23:59.820
Up until that point, writing had been a

00:23:56.760 --> 00:24:02.580
cumbersome and difficult task.

00:23:59.820 --> 00:24:04.380
The cuneiform writing systems that had

00:24:02.580 --> 00:24:06.720
been developed by the Sumerians

00:24:04.380 --> 00:24:09.120
thousands of years before, and the

00:24:06.720 --> 00:24:11.280
Hieroglyphics of the Egyptians, were both

00:24:09.120 --> 00:24:13.799
difficult to learn and relied on the

00:24:11.280 --> 00:24:16.200
services of a learned class of scribes

00:24:13.799 --> 00:24:19.200
who spent years of their lives learning

00:24:16.200 --> 00:24:22.200
them. But the Phoenician alphabet was a

00:24:19.200 --> 00:24:25.200
master class in simplicity. It had only

00:24:22.200 --> 00:24:27.720
22 letters, and could be used to spell

00:24:25.200 --> 00:24:31.440
out words phonetically, leaving out any

00:24:27.720 --> 00:24:33.960
vowels. Quite ingeniously, the shapes

00:24:31.440 --> 00:24:35.700
of the letters also gave a clue as to

00:24:33.960 --> 00:24:39.179
how they were pronounced.

00:24:35.700 --> 00:24:41.720
Their letter B, for instance, was named Bet,

00:24:39.179 --> 00:24:45.120
which was the Phoenician word for house,

00:24:41.720 --> 00:24:49.020
and its symbol was drawn with a pointed

00:24:45.120 --> 00:24:51.179
roof. This simplicity drastically reduced

00:24:49.020 --> 00:24:53.520
the amount of time it took to learn, and

00:24:51.179 --> 00:24:56.100
meant that common traders and merchants

00:24:53.520 --> 00:24:59.400
may have had some ability to read and

00:24:56.100 --> 00:25:01.620
write, and to keep records essential for

00:24:59.400 --> 00:25:04.200
the complex business of buying and

00:25:01.620 --> 00:25:06.659
selling across the sea.

00:25:04.200 --> 00:25:08.520
The Phoenician alphabet was such a good

00:25:06.659 --> 00:25:11.100
idea that it was adopted almost

00:25:08.520 --> 00:25:14.580
wholesale by the Greeks, as the Greek

00:25:11.100 --> 00:25:17.460
historian Herodotus recounts.

00:25:14.580 --> 00:25:20.340
These Phoenicians who came with Cadmus

00:25:17.460 --> 00:25:24.000
brought with them to Greece, among many

00:25:20.340 --> 00:25:27.779
other kinds of learning, the alphabet.

00:25:24.000 --> 00:25:30.299
As time went on, the sound and form of

00:25:27.779 --> 00:25:32.400
the letters were changed, and after being

00:25:30.299 --> 00:25:34.559
taught the letters by the Phoenicians,

00:25:32.400 --> 00:25:38.900
the Greeks, who were settled around them,

00:25:34.559 --> 00:25:38.900
used them with a few changes of form.

00:25:40.080 --> 00:25:44.580
With the addition of some letters for vowels,

00:25:42.179 --> 00:25:46.799
what resulted was the Greek

00:25:44.580 --> 00:25:49.440
alphabet, which means that the Phoenician

00:25:46.799 --> 00:25:53.299
writing system is the foundation of all

00:25:49.440 --> 00:25:53.299
Western alphabets used today.

00:25:54.000 --> 00:25:59.820
The earliest piece of Phoenician writing

00:25:56.820 --> 00:26:02.720
was found on an inscribed tablet known

00:25:59.820 --> 00:26:05.340
as the Nora Stone, unearthed in Sardinia,

00:26:02.720 --> 00:26:07.740
apparently commemorating a Phoenician

00:26:05.340 --> 00:26:10.760
captain who may have died in conflict

00:26:07.740 --> 00:26:10.760
with the local people.

00:26:10.860 --> 00:26:15.419
He fought with the Sardinians at

00:26:12.779 --> 00:26:18.480
Tarshish, and he drove them out.

00:26:15.419 --> 00:26:22.200
Among the Sardinians, he is now at peace,

00:26:18.480 --> 00:26:27.679
and his army is at peace; Milkaton,

00:26:22.200 --> 00:26:27.679
son of Shubna, general of King Pummay.

00:26:27.840 --> 00:26:31.860
But for the most part, the Phoenicians

00:26:30.419 --> 00:26:33.779
seemed to have interacted with the

00:26:31.860 --> 00:26:38.340
people they met relatively peacefully,

00:26:33.779 --> 00:26:38.340
and most of all, profitably.

00:26:40.559 --> 00:26:46.679
Before long, the cities of Tyre, Sidon, and

00:26:43.740 --> 00:26:49.500
Byblos found themselves at the far east

00:26:46.679 --> 00:26:51.900
of a sprawling trade network.

00:26:49.500 --> 00:26:54.299
Keeping such a loose and disparate

00:26:51.900 --> 00:26:57.059
collection of colonies together was no

00:26:54.299 --> 00:27:01.640
easy task, but it seems that here, the

00:26:57.059 --> 00:27:01.640
Phoenician religion played a key role.

00:27:02.220 --> 00:27:09.360
The people of Tyre worshiped a heroic

00:27:05.340 --> 00:27:11.279
god known as Melqart, a warrior hero who

00:27:09.360 --> 00:27:12.440
the Greeks would later associate with

00:27:11.279 --> 00:27:15.419
Hercules.

00:27:12.440 --> 00:27:18.179
Temples to Melqart were set up at

00:27:15.419 --> 00:27:20.700
multiple Phoenician trading posts, and

00:27:18.179 --> 00:27:22.980
most had an olive tree, a symbol of the

00:27:20.700 --> 00:27:25.020
city of Tyre, growing in their central

00:27:22.980 --> 00:27:27.600
courtyard.

00:27:25.020 --> 00:27:29.820
The grandest of these temples was built

00:27:27.600 --> 00:27:32.820
at the furthest Phoenician colony from

00:27:29.820 --> 00:27:35.820
Tyre, then known as Gades, what is

00:27:32.820 --> 00:27:38.400
narrow the Spanish city of Cadiz.

00:27:35.820 --> 00:27:41.159
This colony sat on the Atlantic coast

00:27:38.400 --> 00:27:43.500
just outside the Straits of Gibraltar,

00:27:41.159 --> 00:27:47.940
but it made up for its extreme distance

00:27:43.500 --> 00:27:50.039
from Tyre with its immense opulence.

00:27:47.940 --> 00:27:52.679
At the center of the temple stood an

00:27:50.039 --> 00:27:55.320
olive tree, with its branches and leaves

00:27:52.679 --> 00:27:58.020
wrought out of solid gold, holding

00:27:55.320 --> 00:28:00.840
emerald fruits in its branches.

00:27:58.020 --> 00:28:03.779
Women were forbidden entry to the temple,

00:28:00.840 --> 00:28:06.960
as were pigs, and the priests of Melqart

00:28:03.779 --> 00:28:09.600
went barefoot, wearing a band of Egyptian

00:28:06.960 --> 00:28:12.480
flax over their bare heads.

00:28:09.600 --> 00:28:14.400
The Greek geographer Strabo recounts the

00:28:12.480 --> 00:28:16.919
following description of the settlement

00:28:14.400 --> 00:28:19.799
of Gades.

00:28:16.919 --> 00:28:22.980
Now, these islands are this side of what

00:28:19.799 --> 00:28:26.159
are called the Pillars of Heracles. Gades,

00:28:22.980 --> 00:28:28.200
however, is outside the pillars. Here live

00:28:26.159 --> 00:28:30.960
the men who fit out the most and largest

00:28:28.200 --> 00:28:33.840
merchant vessels, both for our sea and

00:28:30.960 --> 00:28:36.120
the outer sea. They say the Tyrians

00:28:33.840 --> 00:28:38.340
believe that the two capes which form

00:28:36.120 --> 00:28:41.039
the strait were the ends of the

00:28:38.340 --> 00:28:44.220
inhabited world.

00:28:41.039 --> 00:28:47.520
A great ceremony, known as the Egersis

00:28:44.220 --> 00:28:49.500
or Awakening, was conducted each year in

00:28:47.520 --> 00:28:52.500
the temple of Gades.

00:28:49.500 --> 00:28:54.840
During this time, all foreigners were

00:28:52.500 --> 00:28:57.779
asked to leave the city, and a great

00:28:54.840 --> 00:29:00.419
effigy of the god Melqart was set afloat

00:28:57.779 --> 00:29:03.059
on the sea and burned.

00:29:00.419 --> 00:29:05.700
Even this temple was a crucial part

00:29:03.059 --> 00:29:08.760
of the Phoenician trading system.

00:29:05.700 --> 00:29:11.159
The institution worked to guarantee the

00:29:08.760 --> 00:29:14.460
quality of metal ingots produced in

00:29:11.159 --> 00:29:16.679
Gades by giving them a special stamp,

00:29:14.460 --> 00:29:19.860
and acted as a guarantor between

00:29:16.679 --> 00:29:21.779
merchants entering into contracts, with

00:29:19.860 --> 00:29:24.720
punishments promised from Melqart

00:29:21.779 --> 00:29:26.960
himself if any dared to go back on their

00:29:24.720 --> 00:29:26.960
word.

00:29:28.880 --> 00:29:34.559
With Phoenician trade increasingly

00:29:31.860 --> 00:29:37.080
drifting westward, the center of their

00:29:34.559 --> 00:29:39.419
power would soon also shift in that

00:29:37.080 --> 00:29:41.520
direction to a place where they would

00:29:39.419 --> 00:29:44.220
finally be free of the overbearing

00:29:41.520 --> 00:29:45.360
empires constantly breathing down their

00:29:44.220 --> 00:29:48.000
necks.

00:29:45.360 --> 00:29:50.220
They would soon found a city on the

00:29:48.000 --> 00:29:52.559
shore of North Africa, right at the

00:29:50.220 --> 00:29:54.960
center of the Mediterranean world,

00:29:52.559 --> 00:29:57.779
a city that would become one of the

00:29:54.960 --> 00:30:00.720
largest and wealthiest on Earth.

00:29:57.779 --> 00:30:03.380
That city would one day be known as

00:30:00.720 --> 00:30:03.380
Carthage.

00:30:12.980 --> 00:30:18.000
Like so many aspects of our modern

00:30:15.779 --> 00:30:20.520
understanding of the Phoenicians, the

00:30:18.000 --> 00:30:23.640
name Carthage is itself a distortion,

00:30:20.520 --> 00:30:27.000
filtered through the accounts of others.

00:30:23.640 --> 00:30:30.179
In Latin, the city was known as Carthago,

00:30:27.000 --> 00:30:32.880
while the Greeks called it Karkedon. But

00:30:30.179 --> 00:30:37.919
to its inhabitants, it was known as

00:30:32.880 --> 00:30:39.960
Qart-Hadasht, or in Phoenician, the New City.

00:30:37.919 --> 00:30:42.779
Like many great cities of its time,

00:30:39.960 --> 00:30:43.860
Carthage soon developed its own founding

00:30:42.779 --> 00:30:46.440
myth.

00:30:43.860 --> 00:30:50.880
It begins with a princess of Tyre named

00:30:46.440 --> 00:30:53.159
Elissa or Elishaya. In the legend, the

00:30:50.880 --> 00:30:55.320
king of Tyre promises that upon his

00:30:53.159 --> 00:30:57.840
death, his kingdom would be split between

00:30:55.320 --> 00:31:00.179
his two children, his daughter Elishaya,

00:30:57.840 --> 00:31:02.520
and his son Pygmalion.

00:31:00.179 --> 00:31:05.220
But when the old king dies, the

00:31:02.520 --> 00:31:07.260
treacherous brother Pygmalion refuses to

00:31:05.220 --> 00:31:10.020
accept the splitting of the kingdom and

00:31:07.260 --> 00:31:12.779
moves to seize everything for himself,

00:31:10.020 --> 00:31:15.480
even killing Elishaya's husband to

00:31:12.779 --> 00:31:18.539
remove any potential rivals.

00:31:15.480 --> 00:31:21.600
Stricken with grief, Elishaya flees down

00:31:18.539 --> 00:31:24.360
to the docks, along with a ragtag band of

00:31:21.600 --> 00:31:26.700
her royal guards and temple women, and

00:31:24.360 --> 00:31:28.380
there they set sail westwards and make

00:31:26.700 --> 00:31:31.559
for Africa.

00:31:28.380 --> 00:31:34.020
The Roman writer Justinus, drawing on an

00:31:31.559 --> 00:31:35.460
earlier Greek text, writes his rendition

00:31:34.020 --> 00:31:37.799
of this story,

00:31:35.460 --> 00:31:41.580
along with a cunning deception to slow

00:31:37.799 --> 00:31:44.399
down any greedy pursuers.

00:31:41.580 --> 00:31:47.279
Elissa put the attendants, who was sent

00:31:44.399 --> 00:31:49.679
by the king to assist in her removal, on

00:31:47.279 --> 00:31:51.960
board some vessels in the early part of

00:31:49.679 --> 00:31:54.720
the evening, and sailing out into the

00:31:51.960 --> 00:31:58.080
deep, made them throw some loads of sand

00:31:54.720 --> 00:31:59.580
put up in sacks, as if it was money, into

00:31:58.080 --> 00:32:02.940
the sea.

00:31:59.580 --> 00:32:05.460
This group of refugees sail along the

00:32:02.940 --> 00:32:07.919
coast of North Africa until eventually

00:32:05.460 --> 00:32:10.860
they set ashore near the Phoenician

00:32:07.919 --> 00:32:13.919
colony of Utica. They camp on a nearby

00:32:10.860 --> 00:32:16.919
hill known as Byrsa, and the king who

00:32:13.919 --> 00:32:20.399
rules there, a man named Iarbus, takes

00:32:16.919 --> 00:32:23.100
pity on them, but not too much pity.

00:32:20.399 --> 00:32:26.340
He offers to sell them a plot of land on

00:32:23.100 --> 00:32:29.880
the hill no bigger than an ox hide.

00:32:26.340 --> 00:32:32.820
But Elishaya is cunning; she cuts the

00:32:29.880 --> 00:32:35.520
ox hide into thin strips, lining them up to

00:32:32.820 --> 00:32:38.220
enclose the entire hill, a much larger

00:32:35.520 --> 00:32:39.539
area of land than the miserly king had

00:32:38.220 --> 00:32:42.480
intended.

00:32:39.539 --> 00:32:44.460
Bound by his word, Iarbus has no choice

00:32:42.480 --> 00:32:47.960
but to give them the land he promised,

00:32:44.460 --> 00:32:50.460
and so, the city of Carthage is born.

00:32:47.960 --> 00:32:52.440
Justinus recounts the city's early

00:32:50.460 --> 00:32:55.500
flourishing.

00:32:52.440 --> 00:32:57.480
Carthage was founded, an annual tribute

00:32:55.500 --> 00:33:00.179
being fixed for the ground which it was

00:32:57.480 --> 00:33:02.640
to occupy. At the commencement of digging

00:33:00.179 --> 00:33:05.220
the foundations, an ox's head was found,

00:33:02.640 --> 00:33:08.600
which was an omen that the city would be

00:33:05.220 --> 00:33:11.880
wealthy, indeed, but laborious and always

00:33:08.600 --> 00:33:13.980
enslaved. It was therefore removed to

00:33:11.880 --> 00:33:16.799
another place, where the head of a horse

00:33:13.980 --> 00:33:18.799
was found, which, indicating that the

00:33:16.799 --> 00:33:21.419
people would be warlike and powerful,

00:33:18.799 --> 00:33:24.059
portended an auspicious sight.

00:33:21.419 --> 00:33:26.399
In a short time, as the surrounding

00:33:24.059 --> 00:33:28.919
people came together at the report, the

00:33:26.399 --> 00:33:32.460
inhabitants became numerous, and the city

00:33:28.919 --> 00:33:32.460
itself extensive. From the hilltop of Byrsa,

00:33:36.559 --> 00:33:43.559
the city grows and grows, soon eclipsing

00:33:40.440 --> 00:33:46.440
King Iarbus' town of Utica, which makes

00:33:43.559 --> 00:33:49.080
him understandably jealous. He demands

00:33:46.440 --> 00:33:51.299
that Elishaya marry him so that he can

00:33:49.080 --> 00:33:54.299
absorb her flourishing town and

00:33:51.299 --> 00:33:57.179
everything she owns into his kingdom.

00:33:54.299 --> 00:33:58.919
If she refuses, he will burn Carthage to

00:33:57.179 --> 00:34:00.539
the ground.

00:33:58.919 --> 00:34:02.940
Faced with the choice of this

00:34:00.539 --> 00:34:06.059
capitulation or the destruction of her

00:34:02.940 --> 00:34:08.460
new city, Elishaya builds a great pyre

00:34:06.059 --> 00:34:11.520
and climbs onto it, saying that she must

00:34:08.460 --> 00:34:13.980
indeed go to her husband, meaning not

00:34:11.520 --> 00:34:16.560
Iarbus, but the man her brother had killed

00:34:13.980 --> 00:34:19.320
on the other side of the sea, waiting for

00:34:16.560 --> 00:34:23.099
her in the afterlife.

00:34:19.320 --> 00:34:25.679
This tragic but noble self-sacrifice has

00:34:23.099 --> 00:34:28.859
proven irresistible to generations of

00:34:25.679 --> 00:34:32.220
poets, and the Roman poet Virgil gives

00:34:28.859 --> 00:34:34.800
one rendition of this scene.

00:34:32.220 --> 00:34:36.000
When the pyre of cut pine and oak was

00:34:34.800 --> 00:34:39.020
raised high

00:34:36.000 --> 00:34:41.879
in an innermost court open to the sky,

00:34:39.020 --> 00:34:45.599
the queen hung the place with garlands,

00:34:41.879 --> 00:34:48.720
and wreathed it with funeral foliage.

00:34:45.599 --> 00:34:52.560
She laid his sword and clothes and

00:34:48.720 --> 00:34:55.020
picture on the bed. She lingered a while,

00:34:52.560 --> 00:34:56.220
in tears and thought,

00:34:55.020 --> 00:34:59.580
then

00:34:56.220 --> 00:35:02.160
cast herself on the bed and spoke her

00:34:59.580 --> 00:35:03.599
last words; ìAccept

00:35:02.160 --> 00:35:08.119
this soul,

00:35:03.599 --> 00:35:08.119
and loose me from my sorrows.î

00:35:09.480 --> 00:35:14.940
In honor of Elishaya's sacrifice, her

00:35:12.780 --> 00:35:18.300
people gave her the title of Dido,

00:35:14.940 --> 00:35:19.920
meaning female warrior or heroine, and

00:35:18.300 --> 00:35:23.700
this is the name by which she would be

00:35:19.920 --> 00:35:26.760
known to later Roman writers.

00:35:23.700 --> 00:35:28.980
This Baroque tale of love and tragedy

00:35:26.760 --> 00:35:31.200
has all the hallmarks of ancient

00:35:28.980 --> 00:35:33.240
literature, and we can't assume that it

00:35:31.200 --> 00:35:34.380
bears any relationship to what actually

00:35:33.240 --> 00:35:36.960
happened.

00:35:34.380 --> 00:35:39.359
Some details of the tale do accord with

00:35:36.960 --> 00:35:41.820
what archeology tells us, that the

00:35:39.359 --> 00:35:44.339
Carthaginian Phoenicians drew their

00:35:41.820 --> 00:35:46.320
origins back to the city of Tyre, and

00:35:44.339 --> 00:35:48.599
that the city was founded close to the

00:35:46.320 --> 00:35:50.820
older settlement of Utica, which it soon

00:35:48.599 --> 00:35:52.920
eclipsed in size.

00:35:50.820 --> 00:35:54.960
But perhaps more important than any of

00:35:52.920 --> 00:35:56.940
this is the sense that this founding

00:35:54.960 --> 00:35:59.220
myth might give us of the way the

00:35:56.940 --> 00:36:01.920
Carthaginians thought of themselves and

00:35:59.220 --> 00:36:04.800
their city's place in the world, as a

00:36:01.920 --> 00:36:07.619
city of survivors who had found refuge

00:36:04.800 --> 00:36:10.020
here on the North African coast, a city

00:36:07.619 --> 00:36:12.720
of sailors and adventurers.

00:36:10.020 --> 00:36:15.180
They were resourceful and drove a hard

00:36:12.720 --> 00:36:17.760
bargain. They were clever, fond of

00:36:15.180 --> 00:36:21.060
outwitting their enemies, always finding

00:36:17.760 --> 00:36:23.880
a way to make a little go a long way,

00:36:21.060 --> 00:36:28.040
and also, perhaps that they would die

00:36:23.880 --> 00:36:28.040
before they gave up their freedom.

00:36:30.839 --> 00:36:35.700
Regardless of the truth of its origins,

00:36:33.119 --> 00:36:38.520
it's clear from archeology that after

00:36:35.700 --> 00:36:40.800
its founding in the 8th century BC, the

00:36:38.520 --> 00:36:43.200
new colony of Carthage did grow

00:36:40.800 --> 00:36:45.359
exceptionally quickly.

00:36:43.200 --> 00:36:47.579
In many ways, it was the perfect

00:36:45.359 --> 00:36:50.339
Phoenician settlement.

00:36:47.579 --> 00:36:53.040
Carthage was built in a small bay that

00:36:50.339 --> 00:36:56.400
itself belonged to a vast natural harbor,

00:36:53.040 --> 00:36:59.460
known today as the Bay of Tunis.

00:36:56.400 --> 00:37:01.980
The city sat on top of a series of sheer

00:36:59.460 --> 00:37:03.599
red cliffs that looked down over the

00:37:01.980 --> 00:37:05.940
glittering blue waters of the

00:37:03.599 --> 00:37:08.160
Mediterranean in the north, and it was

00:37:05.940 --> 00:37:11.460
also easily defended on its landward

00:37:08.160 --> 00:37:13.740
side, where a range of rocky hills and a

00:37:11.460 --> 00:37:16.500
number of lakes and saltwater lagoons

00:37:13.740 --> 00:37:19.140
break the land into a series of narrow

00:37:16.500 --> 00:37:21.599
approaches, protecting the city from any

00:37:19.140 --> 00:37:24.359
would-be attackers.

00:37:21.599 --> 00:37:27.660
The Roman writer Appian writes one

00:37:24.359 --> 00:37:30.420
description of the city's location.

00:37:27.660 --> 00:37:33.300
The city lay in a recess of a great gulf,

00:37:30.420 --> 00:37:35.160
and was in the form of a peninsula. It

00:37:33.300 --> 00:37:38.160
was separated from the mainland by an

00:37:35.160 --> 00:37:40.740
isthmus about five kilometers in width.

00:37:38.160 --> 00:37:43.380
From this isthmus, a narrow and longish

00:37:40.740 --> 00:37:46.440
tongue of land, about a kilometer wide,

00:37:43.380 --> 00:37:48.599
extended towards the west between a lake

00:37:46.440 --> 00:37:51.599
and the sea.

00:37:48.599 --> 00:37:54.359
Near to the site of Carthage flows a

00:37:51.599 --> 00:37:56.640
river known today as the Mejerda, which

00:37:54.359 --> 00:38:00.420
originates in the high Atlas Mountains

00:37:56.640 --> 00:38:02.940
of North Africa. This river flows for 460

00:38:00.420 --> 00:38:05.460
kilometers to the sea and brings crucial

00:38:02.940 --> 00:38:08.160
fresh water into the bay, turning the

00:38:05.460 --> 00:38:10.200
otherwise arid landscape green, and

00:38:08.160 --> 00:38:12.180
providing water for drinking and

00:38:10.200 --> 00:38:15.000
for irrigation.

00:38:12.180 --> 00:38:19.740
As a result, the land here was abundant

00:38:15.000 --> 00:38:21.839
with wheat, grapes, olives, and dates.

00:38:19.740 --> 00:38:24.480
In the distance over the bay to the

00:38:21.839 --> 00:38:27.300
south rises the blue outline of the

00:38:24.480 --> 00:38:30.180
mountain Djebel Ressas, literally the

00:38:27.300 --> 00:38:33.000
Mountain of Lead, a rugged outcrop of

00:38:30.180 --> 00:38:34.920
Jurassic limestone climbing nearly 800

00:38:33.000 --> 00:38:37.500
meters above the plain.

00:38:34.920 --> 00:38:39.720
The hot desert winds, known as the

00:38:37.500 --> 00:38:42.359
Sirocco, would blow in from the Sahara

00:38:39.720 --> 00:38:44.339
during the summer season, rattling the

00:38:42.359 --> 00:38:46.680
shutters on the windows and the leaves

00:38:44.339 --> 00:38:49.619
of the date palms, and at the end of

00:38:46.680 --> 00:38:52.160
summer, thunderstorms would roll in from

00:38:49.619 --> 00:38:52.160
the sea.

00:38:55.740 --> 00:38:59.940
As well as its ideal geography, the

00:38:58.200 --> 00:39:03.619
city's location in the Mediterranean

00:38:59.940 --> 00:39:03.619
world was also perfect.

00:39:04.500 --> 00:39:09.540
Carthage sat at a crucial halfway point

00:39:07.020 --> 00:39:12.240
between the city of Tyre and the wealthy

00:39:09.540 --> 00:39:15.119
mines of Spain, but it was also only

00:39:12.240 --> 00:39:17.520
about 200 kilometers by boat from the

00:39:15.119 --> 00:39:20.460
island of Sicily and about 300

00:39:17.520 --> 00:39:22.980
kilometers from Sardinia, two crucial

00:39:20.460 --> 00:39:25.320
sites of Phoenician industry that were

00:39:22.980 --> 00:39:27.480
only growing in importance.

00:39:25.320 --> 00:39:30.780
Pottery found in even the earliest

00:39:27.480 --> 00:39:34.200
layers of Carthage shows a huge range of

00:39:30.780 --> 00:39:37.020
styles coming from Greece, Italy, Spain,

00:39:34.200 --> 00:39:39.960
and all the Phoenician colonies.

00:39:37.020 --> 00:39:44.480
The Phoenician world was now a web, with

00:39:39.960 --> 00:39:44.480
Carthage sitting right at its center.

00:39:44.700 --> 00:39:49.680
The city in these early days must have

00:39:47.579 --> 00:39:52.380
been a humble sight.

00:39:49.680 --> 00:39:54.780
Archeology paints a picture of a simple

00:39:52.380 --> 00:39:57.599
collection of mud brick buildings lining

00:39:54.780 --> 00:39:59.280
the seashore, but within a century, this

00:39:57.599 --> 00:40:02.460
had exploded.

00:39:59.280 --> 00:40:04.680
One graveyard soon had to be moved in

00:40:02.460 --> 00:40:07.020
order to make space for a quarter filled

00:40:04.680 --> 00:40:09.240
with metal-working workshops, and the

00:40:07.020 --> 00:40:11.579
settlers built a wall about three meters

00:40:09.240 --> 00:40:12.599
in height to protect their burgeoning

00:40:11.579 --> 00:40:15.960
town.

00:40:12.599 --> 00:40:18.839
Soon, more monumental buildings would

00:40:15.960 --> 00:40:21.480
be constructed. The Roman poet Virgil

00:40:18.839 --> 00:40:23.940
imagines the activity that must have

00:40:21.480 --> 00:40:27.599
accompanied the growth of this town, from

00:40:23.940 --> 00:40:30.500
tiny settlement to booming city.

00:40:27.599 --> 00:40:33.599
Aeneas found where lately huts had been,

00:40:30.500 --> 00:40:37.200
marvelous buildings, gateways, cobbled

00:40:33.599 --> 00:40:40.020
ways, and din of wagons. There, the Tyrians

00:40:37.200 --> 00:40:42.300
were hard at work, laying courses for

00:40:40.020 --> 00:40:44.760
walls, rolling up stones to build the

00:40:42.300 --> 00:40:48.660
citadel, while others picked out building

00:40:44.760 --> 00:40:51.180
sites and plowed a boundary furrow. Laws

00:40:48.660 --> 00:40:53.820
were being enacted, magistrates and a

00:40:51.180 --> 00:40:56.400
sacred senate chosen. Here, men were

00:40:53.820 --> 00:40:58.680
dredging harbors. There, they laid the

00:40:56.400 --> 00:41:01.980
deep foundations of a theater and

00:40:58.680 --> 00:41:04.260
quarried massive pillars.

00:41:01.980 --> 00:41:06.780
Other than what we can glean from

00:41:04.260 --> 00:41:09.780
archeology, we know very little about the

00:41:06.780 --> 00:41:12.900
early history of Carthage apart from a

00:41:09.780 --> 00:41:15.480
few short inscriptions. No Carthaginian

00:41:12.900 --> 00:41:18.300
texts have survived into the modern day,

00:41:15.480 --> 00:41:20.040
and so, in terms of written history, we

00:41:18.300 --> 00:41:22.140
have virtually complete silence from

00:41:20.040 --> 00:41:25.200
that part of the Mediterranean for the

00:41:22.140 --> 00:41:27.839
first 200 years or so of its existence,

00:41:25.200 --> 00:41:31.160
and beyond that, we have to rely on the

00:41:27.839 --> 00:41:31.160
writings of others.

00:41:31.200 --> 00:41:36.359
From the work of Greek writers, we

00:41:33.540 --> 00:41:38.880
learned that Carthage was a republic.

00:41:36.359 --> 00:41:41.640
It was ruled under a kind of oligarchic

00:41:38.880 --> 00:41:44.040
system, governed by a council of its

00:41:41.640 --> 00:41:46.619
wealthiest citizens.

00:41:44.040 --> 00:41:49.680
The Greek philosopher Aristotle, writing

00:41:46.619 --> 00:41:51.540
in the 4th century, spoke approvingly of

00:41:49.680 --> 00:41:53.940
the Carthaginian system of government

00:41:51.540 --> 00:41:57.500
and compares it to that of the Greek

00:41:53.940 --> 00:41:57.500
city-state of Sparta.

00:41:58.020 --> 00:42:02.579
Carthage also appears to have a good

00:42:00.300 --> 00:42:04.560
constitution, with many outstanding

00:42:02.579 --> 00:42:07.200
features as compared with those of other

00:42:04.560 --> 00:42:09.780
nations, but most nearly resembling the

00:42:07.200 --> 00:42:12.240
Spartan at some points. Many regulations

00:42:09.780 --> 00:42:14.460
at Carthage are good, and a proof of a

00:42:12.240 --> 00:42:16.680
well-regulated constitution is that the

00:42:14.460 --> 00:42:18.480
populace willingly remain faithful to

00:42:16.680 --> 00:42:20.820
the constitutional system, and that

00:42:18.480 --> 00:42:26.160
neither civil strife has arisen in any

00:42:20.820 --> 00:42:29.400
degree worth mentioning, nor yet a tyrant.

00:42:26.160 --> 00:42:31.200
But Aristotle also warns that the

00:42:29.400 --> 00:42:33.420
Carthaginian system put too much

00:42:31.200 --> 00:42:35.640
emphasis on the wealth of its rulers

00:42:33.420 --> 00:42:37.920
rather than their competence, and

00:42:35.640 --> 00:42:40.200
expresses concerns that this could lead

00:42:37.920 --> 00:42:42.540
to corruption.

00:42:40.200 --> 00:42:45.240
They think that the rulers should be

00:42:42.540 --> 00:42:47.880
chosen not only for their merit but also

00:42:45.240 --> 00:42:50.520
for their wealth, as it is not possible

00:42:47.880 --> 00:42:53.820
for a poor man to govern well or to have

00:42:50.520 --> 00:42:56.760
leisure for his duties. It is a bad thing

00:42:53.820 --> 00:42:59.400
that the greatest officers of state, the

00:42:56.760 --> 00:43:02.400
kingship, and the general ship should be

00:42:59.400 --> 00:43:04.500
for sale, for this law makes wealth more

00:43:02.400 --> 00:43:07.619
honored than worth and renders the whole

00:43:04.500 --> 00:43:09.599
state avaricious, and it is probable that

00:43:07.619 --> 00:43:12.180
those who purchase their office will

00:43:09.599 --> 00:43:13.740
learn by degrees to make a profit out of

00:43:12.180 --> 00:43:16.079
it.

00:43:13.740 --> 00:43:18.480
The highest echelons of Carthaginian

00:43:16.079 --> 00:43:21.480
society were divided between the civil

00:43:18.480 --> 00:43:24.599
leaders, the shofetim, or judges, and

00:43:21.480 --> 00:43:26.240
the rabbim, or generals, who took care of

00:43:24.599 --> 00:43:29.460
military matters.

00:43:26.240 --> 00:43:32.099
These highest positions, senators and the

00:43:29.460 --> 00:43:33.660
heads of committees, drew no salary for

00:43:32.099 --> 00:43:36.300
their work, and so, they could

00:43:33.660 --> 00:43:38.220
realistically only be held by those who

00:43:36.300 --> 00:43:41.220
could support themselves on private

00:43:38.220 --> 00:43:44.040
incomes, usually successful merchants or

00:43:41.220 --> 00:43:45.660
wealthy landowners, but there was a

00:43:44.040 --> 00:43:47.880
certain fairness to this.

00:43:45.660 --> 00:43:50.460
There seems to have been no barrier

00:43:47.880 --> 00:43:52.800
other than wealth, and people from common

00:43:50.460 --> 00:43:55.079
backgrounds who became wealthy could

00:43:52.800 --> 00:43:56.359
quickly rise to the highest parts of

00:43:55.079 --> 00:43:59.280
government.

00:43:56.359 --> 00:44:01.200
Certain powerful families were

00:43:59.280 --> 00:44:03.660
constantly vying for the most powerful

00:44:01.200 --> 00:44:06.119
positions, but there was no hereditary

00:44:03.660 --> 00:44:08.940
royalty in Carthage.

00:44:06.119 --> 00:44:11.339
It's possible that the myth of Elishaya

00:44:08.940 --> 00:44:13.800
or Dido may have played a role in

00:44:11.339 --> 00:44:15.960
maintaining this situation.

00:44:13.800 --> 00:44:18.000
Since according to the legend, the city

00:44:15.960 --> 00:44:20.700
was founded by a woman who had no

00:44:18.000 --> 00:44:23.940
children, no one could ever claim to be

00:44:20.700 --> 00:44:27.480
her true descendants or have any kind of

00:44:23.940 --> 00:44:30.359
ancestral right to rule.

00:44:27.480 --> 00:44:32.400
Instead, the city was governed by a

00:44:30.359 --> 00:44:35.760
number of different semi-democratic

00:44:32.400 --> 00:44:38.520
bodies made up of wealthy citizens.

00:44:35.760 --> 00:44:41.520
One of these was called the Tribunal of

00:44:38.520 --> 00:44:44.040
the 104, and another, the Council of

00:44:41.520 --> 00:44:46.800
Elders, a kind of senate.

00:44:44.040 --> 00:44:49.440
The highest executive position was held

00:44:46.800 --> 00:44:52.260
by two elected officers who ruled

00:44:49.440 --> 00:44:53.280
simultaneously and who were elected each

00:44:52.260 --> 00:44:56.099
year.

00:44:53.280 --> 00:44:58.619
The arrangement was complex and likely

00:44:56.099 --> 00:45:02.720
prone to corruption, but for the most

00:44:58.619 --> 00:45:02.720
part, it seems to have worked.

00:45:06.420 --> 00:45:11.579
While Carthage flourished, the Phoenician

00:45:09.240 --> 00:45:13.440
cities that had given birth to it began

00:45:11.579 --> 00:45:16.500
to flounder.

00:45:13.440 --> 00:45:20.640
Tyre and Sidon were still under the boot

00:45:16.500 --> 00:45:23.460
of Assyria, and around 670 BC, the

00:45:20.640 --> 00:45:25.619
Assyrian king Esarhaddon began to place

00:45:23.460 --> 00:45:27.480
harsh restrictions on who they could

00:45:25.619 --> 00:45:30.380
trade with.

00:45:27.480 --> 00:45:33.119
When Assyria went to war with Egypt,

00:45:30.380 --> 00:45:37.200
Esarhaddon forced the Phoenicians of Tyre

00:45:33.119 --> 00:45:39.240
to place a trade embargo on the pharaohs.

00:45:37.200 --> 00:45:42.240
Without access to their once most

00:45:39.240 --> 00:45:44.640
lucrative market, these cities went into

00:45:42.240 --> 00:45:46.980
decline.

00:45:44.640 --> 00:45:49.440
Soon, the king of Tyre was not even

00:45:46.980 --> 00:45:51.599
allowed to open messages without an

00:45:49.440 --> 00:45:53.760
Assyrian official present, as the

00:45:51.599 --> 00:45:55.920
following surviving fragment of one

00:45:53.760 --> 00:45:59.339
treaty shows.

00:45:55.920 --> 00:46:01.079
Nor must you open a letter which I send

00:45:59.339 --> 00:46:02.339
you without the presence of the royal

00:46:01.079 --> 00:46:05.099
deputy.

00:46:02.339 --> 00:46:07.920
If the royal deputy is absent, wait for

00:46:05.099 --> 00:46:10.020
him and then open it. If a ship of the

00:46:07.920 --> 00:46:12.420
people of Tyre is shipwrecked off the

00:46:10.020 --> 00:46:14.280
coast of the land of the Philistines or

00:46:12.420 --> 00:46:16.980
anywhere on the borders of a Syrian

00:46:14.280 --> 00:46:22.560
territory, everything that is on the ship

00:46:16.980 --> 00:46:25.200
belongs to Esarhaddon, king of Assyria.

00:46:22.560 --> 00:46:28.200
As a result of the decline of cities

00:46:25.200 --> 00:46:30.599
like Tyre and Sidon, it's likely that

00:46:28.200 --> 00:46:33.060
large numbers of Phoenicians would have

00:46:30.599 --> 00:46:35.819
fled to what was now the undisputed

00:46:33.060 --> 00:46:39.000
capital of the Phoenician world, the

00:46:35.819 --> 00:46:40.800
booming port town of Carthage.

00:46:39.000 --> 00:46:44.400
They brought with them their language,

00:46:40.800 --> 00:46:46.640
their knowledge, their gods, and their

00:46:44.400 --> 00:46:46.640
gold.

00:46:46.740 --> 00:46:52.380
By the 6th century BC, Carthage was one

00:46:50.160 --> 00:46:53.640
of the largest and wealthiest cities in

00:46:52.380 --> 00:46:56.339
the Mediterranean,

00:46:53.640 --> 00:46:58.680
and its sailors, the finest in the world,

00:46:56.339 --> 00:47:01.020
would soon embark on voyages of

00:46:58.680 --> 00:47:05.060
exploration that would not be matched

00:47:01.020 --> 00:47:05.060
for another 2,000 years.

00:47:08.040 --> 00:47:13.140
By this time, the Phoenicians had already

00:47:10.859 --> 00:47:15.960
sailed right to the end of their world,

00:47:13.140 --> 00:47:18.420
through the Pillars of Hercules, and out

00:47:15.960 --> 00:47:21.560
into the Atlantic Ocean.

00:47:18.420 --> 00:47:24.359
But their exploration didn't stop there.

00:47:21.560 --> 00:47:26.400
In fact, if ancient sources are to be

00:47:24.359 --> 00:47:29.160
believed, they may have been the first

00:47:26.400 --> 00:47:32.160
navigators to successfully sail around

00:47:29.160 --> 00:47:35.339
the entire coast of Africa.

00:47:32.160 --> 00:47:38.119
Herodotus recounts one expedition that

00:47:35.339 --> 00:47:41.040
supposedly took place around 600 BC,

00:47:38.119 --> 00:47:44.040
sponsored by a pharaoh of Egypt named

00:47:41.040 --> 00:47:46.260
Nechos, although he is frustratingly vague

00:47:44.040 --> 00:47:49.020
and short on detail.

00:47:46.260 --> 00:47:52.200
The expedition apparently set sail from

00:47:49.020 --> 00:47:54.599
Egypt's Red Sea coast, voyaged around the

00:47:52.200 --> 00:47:57.000
Horn of Africa and the South African

00:47:54.599 --> 00:47:58.980
Cape, before sailing north through the

00:47:57.000 --> 00:48:00.960
Gulf of Guinea and back into the

00:47:58.980 --> 00:48:03.240
Mediterranean through the Pillars of

00:48:00.960 --> 00:48:05.819
Hercules.

00:48:03.240 --> 00:48:08.579
Nechos of Egypt sent Phoenicians and

00:48:05.819 --> 00:48:10.800
ships, instructing them to sail on their

00:48:08.579 --> 00:48:13.260
return voyage past the Pillars of

00:48:10.800 --> 00:48:16.380
Heracles until they came into the

00:48:13.260 --> 00:48:19.020
northern sea, and so, to Egypt.

00:48:16.380 --> 00:48:21.960
So, the Phoenicians set out from the Red

00:48:19.020 --> 00:48:24.780
Sea and sailed to the southern sea.

00:48:21.960 --> 00:48:27.000
Whenever autumn came, they would put in

00:48:24.780 --> 00:48:30.300
and plant the land in whatever part of

00:48:27.000 --> 00:48:31.740
Libya they had reached, and there await

00:48:30.300 --> 00:48:34.200
the harvest.

00:48:31.740 --> 00:48:37.079
Then, having gathered the crop, they

00:48:34.200 --> 00:48:39.480
sailed on, so that after two years had

00:48:37.079 --> 00:48:41.940
passed, it was in the third that they

00:48:39.480 --> 00:48:43.280
rounded the Pillars of Heracles and came

00:48:41.940 --> 00:48:46.560
to Egypt.

00:48:43.280 --> 00:48:48.480
There they said what some may believe,

00:48:46.560 --> 00:48:51.720
though I do not,

00:48:48.480 --> 00:48:55.700
that in sailing around Libya, they had

00:48:51.720 --> 00:48:55.700
the sun on their right hand.

00:48:56.660 --> 00:49:01.680
Interestingly, it is this detail that

00:48:59.520 --> 00:49:04.079
Herodotus personally finds unbelievable

00:49:01.680 --> 00:49:06.060
that has caused modern scholars to take

00:49:04.079 --> 00:49:07.800
the claim more seriously.

00:49:06.060 --> 00:49:10.140
The change in the position of the sun

00:49:07.800 --> 00:49:12.420
relative to the ship suggests that the

00:49:10.140 --> 00:49:14.599
voyage did indeed cross the Tropic of

00:49:12.420 --> 00:49:17.579
Cancer, and perhaps even the equator,

00:49:14.599 --> 00:49:18.240
causing the summer sun to appear in the

00:49:17.579 --> 00:49:20.640
north.

00:49:18.240 --> 00:49:22.740
Modern estimates consider a journey time

00:49:20.640 --> 00:49:25.200
of three years to be a reasonable

00:49:22.740 --> 00:49:27.540
duration for a circumnavigation of

00:49:25.200 --> 00:49:30.119
Africa that would have been about

00:49:27.540 --> 00:49:31.560
20,000 kilometers long, or half the way

00:49:30.119 --> 00:49:34.200
around the world.

00:49:31.560 --> 00:49:36.480
If this story is true, then it means the

00:49:34.200 --> 00:49:39.780
Phoenicians may have rounded the Cape of

00:49:36.480 --> 00:49:42.540
Africa more than 2,000 years before the

00:49:39.780 --> 00:49:46.020
Portuguese explorer, Bortolemeu Dias,

00:49:42.540 --> 00:49:48.720
would do the same thing in 1488, opening

00:49:46.020 --> 00:49:51.980
up the passage to India and the age of

00:49:48.720 --> 00:49:51.980
European colonialism.

00:49:56.640 --> 00:50:01.500
More solidly attested voyages of

00:49:59.400 --> 00:50:04.140
Phoenician discovery would see an

00:50:01.500 --> 00:50:06.119
explorer named Hanno the Navigator sail

00:50:04.140 --> 00:50:08.760
out into the Atlantic Ocean through the

00:50:06.119 --> 00:50:12.060
Pillars of Hercules, and sail perhaps as

00:50:08.760 --> 00:50:13.319
far south as Cameroon or Gabon in West

00:50:12.060 --> 00:50:15.420
Africa.

00:50:13.319 --> 00:50:18.599
His voyage is recounted in a Greek

00:50:15.420 --> 00:50:21.359
translation entitled The Periplus, or

00:50:18.599 --> 00:50:23.760
Travel Account of Hanno, supposedly an

00:50:21.359 --> 00:50:26.400
accurate copy of an inscription that

00:50:23.760 --> 00:50:28.319
actually hung in the temple of Baal Hammon

00:50:26.400 --> 00:50:31.260
in Carthage.

00:50:28.319 --> 00:50:33.240
It was decreed by the Carthaginians that

00:50:31.260 --> 00:50:35.099
Hanno should undertake a voyage beyond

00:50:33.240 --> 00:50:37.140
the Pillars of Hercules and found

00:50:35.099 --> 00:50:39.960
Phoenician cities.

00:50:37.140 --> 00:50:42.359
He sailed accordingly, with 60 ships or

00:50:39.960 --> 00:50:44.880
50 oars each, and the body of men and

00:50:42.359 --> 00:50:48.119
women to the number of 30,000, and

00:50:44.880 --> 00:50:50.520
provisions and other necessaries.

00:50:48.119 --> 00:50:52.980
Preceding a day's sail, we came to the

00:50:50.520 --> 00:50:56.460
extremity of the lake that was overhung

00:50:52.980 --> 00:50:59.400
by large mountains, inhabited by savage

00:50:56.460 --> 00:51:02.520
men clothed in the skins of wild beasts,

00:50:59.400 --> 00:51:04.920
who drove us away by throwing stones, and

00:51:02.520 --> 00:51:07.619
hindered us from landing.

00:51:04.920 --> 00:51:10.619
Sailing thence, we came to another river

00:51:07.619 --> 00:51:13.619
that was large and broad, and full of

00:51:10.619 --> 00:51:17.040
crocodiles and hippopotamuses.

00:51:13.619 --> 00:51:19.920
Hanno writes down vivid descriptions of

00:51:17.040 --> 00:51:21.960
seeing active volcanoes spewing lava

00:51:19.920 --> 00:51:25.440
into the ocean, possibly the active

00:51:21.960 --> 00:51:28.380
volcano Mount Cameroon.

00:51:25.440 --> 00:51:30.780
Then quickly sailing forth, we passed

00:51:28.380 --> 00:51:33.720
by a burning country full of fragrance,

00:51:30.780 --> 00:51:36.900
from which great torrents of fire flowed

00:51:33.720 --> 00:51:40.740
down to the sea, and we sailed along with

00:51:36.900 --> 00:51:43.859
all speed, being stricken by fear.

00:51:40.740 --> 00:51:46.680
After a journey of four days, we saw the

00:51:43.859 --> 00:51:48.540
land at night covered with flames, and in

00:51:46.680 --> 00:51:51.359
the midst there was one lofty fire

00:51:48.540 --> 00:51:54.500
greater than the rest, which seemed to

00:51:51.359 --> 00:51:54.500
touch the stars.

00:51:54.839 --> 00:51:59.819
Hanno even seems to have been the first

00:51:57.059 --> 00:52:01.680
to write down an encounter with what may

00:51:59.819 --> 00:52:05.940
have been Earth's largest living

00:52:01.680 --> 00:52:07.980
primates, with unfortunate results.

00:52:05.940 --> 00:52:10.319
We arrived at a bay called the Southern

00:52:07.980 --> 00:52:13.079
Horn, at the bottom of which lay an

00:52:10.319 --> 00:52:15.480
island full of savage people, the greater

00:52:13.079 --> 00:52:17.700
part of whom were women whose bodies

00:52:15.480 --> 00:52:20.220
were hairy, and whom our interpreters

00:52:17.700 --> 00:52:22.500
called Gorillae.

00:52:20.220 --> 00:52:25.579
Though we pursued the men, we could not

00:52:22.500 --> 00:52:28.319
seize any of them; but all fled from us,

00:52:25.579 --> 00:52:31.200
escaping over the precipices and

00:52:28.319 --> 00:52:34.380
defending themselves with stones.

00:52:31.200 --> 00:52:35.940
Three women were, however, taken, but they

00:52:34.380 --> 00:52:37.859
attacked their conductors with their

00:52:35.940 --> 00:52:40.079
teeth and hands, and could not be

00:52:37.859 --> 00:52:43.020
prevailed upon to accompany us.

00:52:40.079 --> 00:52:45.480
Having killed them, we flayed them, and

00:52:43.020 --> 00:52:48.000
brought their skins with us to Carthage.

00:52:45.480 --> 00:52:50.700
We did not sail farther on, our

00:52:48.000 --> 00:52:53.280
provisions failing us.

00:52:50.700 --> 00:52:56.460
These hairy creatures may have been

00:52:53.280 --> 00:52:59.339
chimpanzees, monkeys, or what we today

00:52:56.460 --> 00:53:02.579
would call gorillas, all of which can be

00:52:59.339 --> 00:53:05.700
encountered in the region of Cameroon.

00:53:02.579 --> 00:53:08.099
On Hanno's return, the hairy skins he

00:53:05.700 --> 00:53:10.740
brought home were kept in the temple to

00:53:08.099 --> 00:53:12.960
the god Tanit in Carthage, and according

00:53:10.740 --> 00:53:16.140
to Pliny the Elder, would remain in the

00:53:12.960 --> 00:53:18.780
city for as long as it existed.

00:53:16.140 --> 00:53:21.359
In the 19th century, when the American

00:53:18.780 --> 00:53:24.000
physician and missionary Thomas Staughton

00:53:21.359 --> 00:53:26.040
Savage and the naturalist Jeffries Wyman

00:53:24.000 --> 00:53:28.579
wrote the first scientific description

00:53:26.040 --> 00:53:30.900
of a gorilla, they gave them the name

00:53:28.579 --> 00:53:33.420
Troglodytes gorilla after the

00:53:30.900 --> 00:53:38.119
mysterious description in Hanno's writing,

00:53:33.420 --> 00:53:38.119
and the name has stuck ever since.

00:53:40.440 --> 00:53:46.140
Another explorer named Himilco sailed

00:53:43.980 --> 00:53:48.720
out into the Atlantic and went in the

00:53:46.140 --> 00:53:51.359
opposite direction, sailing north up the

00:53:48.720 --> 00:53:52.980
coast of Spain and France, and even on to

00:53:51.359 --> 00:53:56.339
the British Isles.

00:53:52.980 --> 00:53:59.640
Here, he saw Celtic tribespeople sailing

00:53:56.339 --> 00:54:01.680
in coracles made of deerskin, a sight he

00:53:59.640 --> 00:54:05.040
found remarkable.

00:54:01.680 --> 00:54:07.140
They cleave the tempestuous sea and the

00:54:05.040 --> 00:54:10.559
current of the ocean abounding in

00:54:07.140 --> 00:54:13.440
monsters, with woven boats. Indeed, these

00:54:10.559 --> 00:54:16.920
people do not know how to fashion keels

00:54:13.440 --> 00:54:19.380
with pine and maple, but in a miraculous

00:54:16.920 --> 00:54:22.380
thing, they always fit out vessels from

00:54:19.380 --> 00:54:24.599
hides stretched together, and often

00:54:22.380 --> 00:54:26.280
travel through the immense sea in a

00:54:24.599 --> 00:54:29.520
skin.

00:54:26.280 --> 00:54:31.880
Himilco also brought back stories of the

00:54:29.520 --> 00:54:35.160
vast expanse of the Atlantic to the West,

00:54:31.880 --> 00:54:37.920
a frightening sight to the sailors brought

00:54:35.160 --> 00:54:39.599
up in the enclosed inland sea of the

00:54:37.920 --> 00:54:42.599
Mediterranean.

00:54:39.599 --> 00:54:45.960
Beyond, towards the area to the West,

00:54:42.599 --> 00:54:49.200
there is a sea without end.

00:54:45.960 --> 00:54:52.740
The ocean lies open across a wide area,

00:54:49.200 --> 00:54:55.619
and the sea stretches out.

00:54:52.740 --> 00:54:58.440
No man has entered upon these seas,

00:54:55.619 --> 00:55:01.440
because the sea lacks winds that would

00:54:58.440 --> 00:55:04.680
drive the ships along, and no breeze from

00:55:01.440 --> 00:55:06.780
the sky favors a ship.

00:55:04.680 --> 00:55:08.880
It also seems that he may have seen

00:55:06.780 --> 00:55:11.640
whales swimming out there in the ocean,

00:55:08.880 --> 00:55:15.140
which were then nearly four times more

00:55:11.640 --> 00:55:15.140
numerous than they are today.

00:55:15.480 --> 00:55:23.359
Here and there, sea monsters swim amid

00:55:19.619 --> 00:55:26.220
the slow ships sluggishly crawling along.

00:55:23.359 --> 00:55:28.800
Himilco reported that he had once seen

00:55:26.220 --> 00:55:31.920
these creatures in the ocean and proved

00:55:28.800 --> 00:55:35.520
their existence. These we have related to

00:55:31.920 --> 00:55:39.200
you, revealed a long time ago deep in the

00:55:35.520 --> 00:55:39.200
annals of the Carthaginians.

00:55:41.700 --> 00:55:48.480
In 2019, a team of twenty modern sailors

00:55:45.599 --> 00:55:50.579
successfully piloted a replica of a

00:55:48.480 --> 00:55:52.760
single-mastered Carthaginian merchant

00:55:50.579 --> 00:55:55.680
vessel across the Atlantic Ocean,

00:55:52.760 --> 00:55:57.960
departing from the site of Carthage and

00:55:55.680 --> 00:56:00.599
landing in the Caribbean five months

00:55:57.960 --> 00:56:02.520
later, demonstrating that Phoenician

00:56:00.599 --> 00:56:04.559
ships had the ability to reach the

00:56:02.520 --> 00:56:06.980
Americas 2,000 years before

00:56:04.559 --> 00:56:06.980
Columbus.

00:56:10.440 --> 00:56:15.240
As the city of Carthage grew, its

00:56:13.140 --> 00:56:18.359
population boomed.

00:56:15.240 --> 00:56:21.180
While some ancient writers record it as

00:56:18.359 --> 00:56:23.460
having a population of more than 700,000

00:56:21.180 --> 00:56:25.740
people, this is thought to be unlikely.

00:56:23.460 --> 00:56:28.440
But estimates based on the size of the

00:56:25.740 --> 00:56:30.780
city and the size of civilian armies

00:56:28.440 --> 00:56:32.400
drawn up in times of crisis have

00:56:30.780 --> 00:56:34.980
suggested that the population may have

00:56:32.400 --> 00:56:38.400
reached 400,000.

00:56:34.980 --> 00:56:41.400
By the year 400 BC, the city walls had

00:56:38.400 --> 00:56:44.220
been rebuilt to now stand a towering 15

00:56:41.400 --> 00:56:46.680
meters high, with a triple line of

00:56:44.220 --> 00:56:50.400
ditches and defenses on the landward

00:56:46.680 --> 00:56:52.680
side. The hill of Byrsa, where legend has

00:56:50.400 --> 00:56:55.200
it that Elishaya played her trick with

00:56:52.680 --> 00:56:58.020
the ox hide, was now itself ringed with

00:56:55.200 --> 00:57:00.359
an inner defensive wall and loomed over

00:56:58.020 --> 00:57:01.800
the rest of the city as a fortified

00:57:00.359 --> 00:57:04.380
citadel.

00:57:01.800 --> 00:57:07.319
The Roman writer Appian writes the

00:57:04.380 --> 00:57:09.660
following description of the city.

00:57:07.319 --> 00:57:10.859
On the seaside, the city was protected by

00:57:09.660 --> 00:57:13.319
a single wall. Toward

00:57:10.859 --> 00:57:15.300
the south and the mainland, where the

00:57:13.319 --> 00:57:18.119
citadel of Byrsa stood on the isthmus,

00:57:15.300 --> 00:57:20.819
there was a triple wall. The height of

00:57:18.119 --> 00:57:22.500
each wall was 15 meter without counting

00:57:20.819 --> 00:57:25.200
parapets and towers,

00:57:22.500 --> 00:57:27.720
which was separated from each other by a

00:57:25.200 --> 00:57:30.059
space of 60 meters.

00:57:27.720 --> 00:57:32.220
One of the most remarkable features of

00:57:30.059 --> 00:57:37.400
ancient Carthage was the innovative

00:57:32.220 --> 00:57:37.400
design of its harbor, known as the cothon.

00:57:38.119 --> 00:57:44.640
Likely built sometime in the third or

00:57:41.220 --> 00:57:46.980
second century BC, this comprised a large,

00:57:44.640 --> 00:57:49.859
rectangular commercial harbor for

00:57:46.980 --> 00:57:52.020
civilian ships that led into a unique,

00:57:49.859 --> 00:57:54.839
circular docking bay for the military

00:57:52.020 --> 00:57:57.720
ships of Carthage's war fleet.

00:57:54.839 --> 00:58:00.000
The harbor was so large that today the

00:57:57.720 --> 00:58:03.059
shape of its outline can still be seen

00:58:00.000 --> 00:58:06.059
in the coast of the city of Tunis.

00:58:03.059 --> 00:58:07.619
Appian describes the unique design of

00:58:06.059 --> 00:58:09.480
this harbor.

00:58:07.619 --> 00:58:11.760
The harbors have communication with each

00:58:09.480 --> 00:58:14.160
other and a common entrance from the sea

00:58:11.760 --> 00:58:15.900
20 meters wide, which could be closed

00:58:14.160 --> 00:58:18.059
with iron chains.

00:58:15.900 --> 00:58:20.160
The first port was for merchant vessels,

00:58:18.059 --> 00:58:21.780
and here were collected all kinds of

00:58:20.160 --> 00:58:23.700
shipsí tackle.

00:58:21.780 --> 00:58:25.980
Within the second port was an island

00:58:23.700 --> 00:58:28.740
which, together with the port itself, was

00:58:25.980 --> 00:58:30.900
enclosed by high embankments. These

00:58:28.740 --> 00:58:34.020
embankments were full of shipyards, which

00:58:30.900 --> 00:58:36.119
had capacity for 220 vessels.

00:58:34.020 --> 00:58:37.920
Above, there were magazines for their

00:58:36.119 --> 00:58:40.680
tackle and furniture.

00:58:37.920 --> 00:58:41.640
Two ionic columns stood in front of each

00:58:40.680 --> 00:58:43.559
dock.

00:58:41.640 --> 00:58:45.420
On the island was built the admiral's

00:58:43.559 --> 00:58:48.359
house, from which the trumpeter gave

00:58:45.420 --> 00:58:50.220
signals, the herald delivered orders, and

00:58:48.359 --> 00:58:52.700
the admiral himself overlooked

00:58:50.220 --> 00:58:52.700
everything.

00:58:54.180 --> 00:58:58.680
At this time, Carthage had the largest

00:58:56.819 --> 00:59:01.380
and most powerful fleet in the

00:58:58.680 --> 00:59:03.780
Mediterranean, and the military port was

00:59:01.380 --> 00:59:06.839
built to conceal the ships docked within

00:59:03.780 --> 00:59:09.900
and ensure that no spies could glean any

00:59:06.839 --> 00:59:11.280
of their secrets or keep tabs on their

00:59:09.900 --> 00:59:13.319
movements.

00:59:11.280 --> 00:59:15.480
The island lay near the entrance to the

00:59:13.319 --> 00:59:17.700
harbor and rose to a considerable height

00:59:15.480 --> 00:59:20.040
so that the admiral could observe what

00:59:17.700 --> 00:59:22.319
was going on at sea while those who were

00:59:20.040 --> 00:59:25.079
approaching by water could not get any

00:59:22.319 --> 00:59:27.240
clear view of what took place within.

00:59:25.079 --> 00:59:29.700
Not even the incoming merchants could

00:59:27.240 --> 00:59:32.220
see the docks, for a double wall enclosed

00:59:29.700 --> 00:59:34.200
them, and there were gates by which

00:59:32.220 --> 00:59:36.420
merchant ships could pass from the first

00:59:34.200 --> 00:59:38.880
port of the city without traversing the

00:59:36.420 --> 00:59:41.839
dockyards. Such was the appearance of

00:59:38.880 --> 00:59:41.839
Carthage at the time.

00:59:55.260 --> 01:00:01.260
Between the harbor and the citadel of

00:59:57.660 --> 01:00:04.200
Byrsa on the hill stood the Agora, the

01:00:01.260 --> 01:00:06.480
large open marketplace of the city, where

01:00:04.200 --> 01:00:07.500
all manner of goods and foods could be

01:00:06.480 --> 01:00:09.660
bought.

01:00:07.500 --> 01:00:12.380
Archaeological studies of plant matter

01:00:09.660 --> 01:00:15.540
found in Carthage show that the ancient

01:00:12.380 --> 01:00:17.400
Carthaginians enjoyed a varied diet.

01:00:15.540 --> 01:00:20.220
Walking through the markets of the city,

01:00:17.400 --> 01:00:22.859
you would be able to buy wheat, barley, and

01:00:20.220 --> 01:00:25.440
other grains, numerous vegetables like

01:00:22.859 --> 01:00:27.240
artichokes and cabbages, pulses and

01:00:25.440 --> 01:00:31.380
lentils, and fruits including

01:00:27.240 --> 01:00:34.079
pomegranates, grapes, figs, olives, peaches,

01:00:31.380 --> 01:00:36.599
plums, and melons, as well as nuts like

01:00:34.079 --> 01:00:39.540
pistachios and almonds.

01:00:36.599 --> 01:00:42.359
Olives were pressed into oil, and its

01:00:39.540 --> 01:00:45.420
people ate fish like grey mullet, sea

01:00:42.359 --> 01:00:49.200
perch, eels, and dolphins, as well as the

01:00:45.420 --> 01:00:51.480
meat of sheep, pigs, goats, chickens, and

01:00:49.200 --> 01:00:53.700
occasionally even dogs.

01:00:51.480 --> 01:00:55.740
The Carthaginians, like most people in

01:00:53.700 --> 01:00:58.380
the ancient world, were obsessed with a

01:00:55.740 --> 01:01:00.900
pungent salty source known as garum,

01:00:58.380 --> 01:01:03.359
which was brewed from the fermenting of

01:01:00.900 --> 01:01:06.420
fish entrails, and which was probably

01:01:03.359 --> 01:01:09.359
similar to the fish sauce used today in

01:01:06.420 --> 01:01:12.240
East Asian cuisine.

01:01:09.359 --> 01:01:15.380
In the wreck of one Carthaginian ship

01:01:12.240 --> 01:01:17.520
found off the coast of Sicily in Masala,

01:01:15.380 --> 01:01:20.099
archaeologists have also uncovered the

01:01:17.520 --> 01:01:21.960
remains of cannabis stalks which may

01:01:20.099 --> 01:01:24.900
have been chewed by the ship's rowers,

01:01:21.960 --> 01:01:28.680
and could also have been enjoyed on land,

01:01:24.900 --> 01:01:31.799
either chewed or brewed into a tea.

01:01:28.680 --> 01:01:33.839
Wine was particularly beloved, too, and

01:01:31.799 --> 01:01:37.740
especially a particular kind of sweet

01:01:33.839 --> 01:01:40.980
dessert wine made from sun-dried grapes.

01:01:37.740 --> 01:01:43.559
One agricultural handbook, written by a

01:01:40.980 --> 01:01:45.839
Carthaginian named Mago, has survived

01:01:43.559 --> 01:01:48.059
in fragments of Greek and Latin

01:01:45.839 --> 01:01:50.540
translation, and it describes the process

01:01:48.059 --> 01:01:53.839
of making this wine.

01:01:50.540 --> 01:01:56.880
Pick some well-ripened, early grapes.

01:01:53.839 --> 01:02:00.180
Discard any that are mildewed or damaged.

01:01:56.880 --> 01:02:03.240
Lay down reeds and spread the grapes out

01:02:00.180 --> 01:02:05.339
in the sun on top. Cover them at night so

01:02:03.240 --> 01:02:08.160
that the dew will not moisten them.

01:02:05.339 --> 01:02:10.559
When they are dried, pick the grapes off

01:02:08.160 --> 01:02:13.799
stems and put them in a jar or pitcher.

01:02:10.559 --> 01:02:16.980
Add some un-fermented wine, the best you

01:02:13.799 --> 01:02:19.020
have, until the grapes are just covered.

01:02:16.980 --> 01:02:21.480
After six days, when the grapes have

01:02:19.020 --> 01:02:23.579
absorbed it all and are swollen, put them

01:02:21.480 --> 01:02:26.700
in a basket, put them through the press,

01:02:23.579 --> 01:02:29.700
and collect the resulting liquid. Bottle

01:02:26.700 --> 01:02:32.160
the liquid in stopper jars, and after 20

01:02:29.700 --> 01:02:34.859
or 30 days, when the fermentation is over,

01:02:32.160 --> 01:02:37.760
coat the lids with plaster and cover

01:02:34.859 --> 01:02:37.760
them with leather.

01:02:37.920 --> 01:02:43.319
As a typical Phoenician city, Carthage

01:02:40.920 --> 01:02:45.960
initially had a small footprint in North

01:02:43.319 --> 01:02:48.720
Africa and in its early days, it was

01:02:45.960 --> 01:02:51.059
reliant on its overseas territories in

01:02:48.720 --> 01:02:53.700
Sardinia and Sicily for more than half

01:02:51.059 --> 01:02:55.440
of its food, brought across the sea on

01:02:53.700 --> 01:02:57.780
grain ships.

01:02:55.440 --> 01:03:00.720
But in the 6th century, it began to

01:02:57.780 --> 01:03:03.420
expand its territory around the city.

01:03:00.720 --> 01:03:05.940
The Carthaginians either expelled local

01:03:03.420 --> 01:03:08.640
people or came to agreements with them,

01:03:05.940 --> 01:03:11.640
and built a network of towns and forts to

01:03:08.640 --> 01:03:15.000
the south, east, and west, and began to

01:03:11.640 --> 01:03:18.240
farm the land themselves.

01:03:15.000 --> 01:03:20.460
A later writer, Diodorus of Sicily, would

01:03:18.240 --> 01:03:22.440
pan the following description of the

01:03:20.460 --> 01:03:26.000
abundant hinterland that would soon

01:03:22.440 --> 01:03:26.000
stretch beyond the city.

01:03:26.099 --> 01:03:32.160
All the lands were set with gardens and

01:03:29.339 --> 01:03:33.359
orchards, watered by numerous springs and

01:03:32.160 --> 01:03:35.040
canals.

01:03:33.359 --> 01:03:37.579
There were well-constructed country

01:03:35.040 --> 01:03:40.440
houses built with lime along the route,

01:03:37.579 --> 01:03:43.380
announcing widespread wealth.

01:03:40.440 --> 01:03:47.280
The land was cultivated with vines, olive

01:03:43.380 --> 01:03:49.559
trees, and a whole host of fruit trees. On

01:03:47.280 --> 01:03:52.200
both sides, there were herds of oxen and

01:03:49.559 --> 01:03:54.599
sheep grazing on the plain, and near the

01:03:52.200 --> 01:03:56.640
main pastures and the marshes, there were

01:03:54.599 --> 01:03:59.819
studs of horses.

01:03:56.640 --> 01:04:02.599
In its outposts in Sardinia, Spain, and

01:03:59.819 --> 01:04:05.520
Sicily, Carthage began a similar process,

01:04:02.599 --> 01:04:07.980
turning what had once been small trading

01:04:05.520 --> 01:04:10.740
posts into more solid and fortified

01:04:07.980 --> 01:04:12.540
territories with their own agricultural

01:04:10.740 --> 01:04:15.180
land.

01:04:12.540 --> 01:04:17.640
Soon, the city of Carthage would be more

01:04:15.180 --> 01:04:21.000
or less self-sufficient, as the Roman

01:04:17.640 --> 01:04:23.520
writer Appian describes.

01:04:21.000 --> 01:04:25.619
Gradually acquiring strength, they

01:04:23.520 --> 01:04:27.180
mastered Africa and the greater part of

01:04:25.619 --> 01:04:30.180
the Mediterranean,

01:04:27.180 --> 01:04:32.579
carried war into Sicily and Sardinia and

01:04:30.180 --> 01:04:35.099
the other islands of that scene, and also

01:04:32.579 --> 01:04:36.299
into Spain. They sent out numerous

01:04:35.099 --> 01:04:38.339
colonies.

01:04:36.299 --> 01:04:42.980
They became a match for the Greeks in

01:04:38.339 --> 01:04:42.980
power and next to the Persians in wealth.

01:04:43.500 --> 01:04:48.359
The typical Carthaginian house was built

01:04:46.319 --> 01:04:50.760
around a central courtyard, and the

01:04:48.359 --> 01:04:52.020
wealthier dwellings had an upstairs and

01:04:50.760 --> 01:04:54.720
a terrace.

01:04:52.020 --> 01:04:57.359
Finer houses had cupboards and shelves

01:04:54.720 --> 01:04:58.920
built into the walls, and often a clay

01:04:57.359 --> 01:05:01.619
bread oven.

01:04:58.920 --> 01:05:04.020
We can imagine the smells of this baking

01:05:01.619 --> 01:05:06.480
bread wafting through the city streets,

01:05:04.020 --> 01:05:09.000
along with the pungent aromas from the

01:05:06.480 --> 01:05:11.940
tanneries and wineries, the smells of

01:05:09.000 --> 01:05:14.940
animals and incense, cooked fish, and

01:05:11.940 --> 01:05:18.180
salty garum sauce.

01:05:14.940 --> 01:05:20.220
Wealthy houses also contained elaborate

01:05:18.180 --> 01:05:22.859
bathrooms with separate changing

01:05:20.220 --> 01:05:25.859
facilities, and baths plastered with

01:05:22.859 --> 01:05:28.920
water-resistant stucco. Before bathing,

01:05:25.859 --> 01:05:31.799
oil would be applied to the body, and a

01:05:28.920 --> 01:05:34.500
bronze tool known as a strigil was used

01:05:31.799 --> 01:05:37.079
to scrape dirt from the skin.

01:05:34.500 --> 01:05:39.180
While in Greek houses these bathrooms

01:05:37.079 --> 01:05:41.339
were usually built off the kitchen, the

01:05:39.180 --> 01:05:43.799
Carthaginians built their bathrooms next

01:05:41.339 --> 01:05:45.599
to the entrance to the house, suggesting

01:05:43.799 --> 01:05:47.460
that there was some sort of ritual

01:05:45.599 --> 01:05:50.280
purpose to the bathing,

01:05:47.460 --> 01:05:52.920
separating the dusty, unclean world of

01:05:50.280 --> 01:05:55.339
outside from the clean inner space of

01:05:52.920 --> 01:05:55.339
the home.

01:05:57.780 --> 01:06:02.880
A variety of animals would have been

01:06:00.119 --> 01:06:04.920
visible on the crowded city streets.

01:06:02.880 --> 01:06:08.400
These would have included beasts of

01:06:04.920 --> 01:06:11.339
burden like donkeys, oxen, and horses, stray

01:06:08.400 --> 01:06:13.319
dogs and cats, and noisy caravans of camels

01:06:11.339 --> 01:06:15.660
coming in from the desert.

01:06:13.319 --> 01:06:20.040
But they also seem to have drawn animals

01:06:15.660 --> 01:06:23.220
as curiosities from all parts of Africa.

01:06:20.040 --> 01:06:25.740
A species of huge lion known as the

01:06:23.220 --> 01:06:28.079
Barbary lion could be found all across

01:06:25.740 --> 01:06:30.839
this region and would later be captured

01:06:28.079 --> 01:06:32.039
for spectacles, including in the Roman

01:06:30.839 --> 01:06:35.039
arenas,

01:06:32.039 --> 01:06:37.680
and a species of monkey known as the

01:06:35.039 --> 01:06:39.059
Barbary macaque is also native to this

01:06:37.680 --> 01:06:42.000
area.

01:06:39.059 --> 01:06:44.640
Diodorus of Sicily records one account of

01:06:42.000 --> 01:06:48.720
Carthaginians keeping these monkeys as

01:06:44.640 --> 01:06:51.359
apparently much-beloved pets.

01:06:48.720 --> 01:06:53.400
In these cities, many of the customs were

01:06:51.359 --> 01:06:54.180
very different from those current among

01:06:53.400 --> 01:06:56.700
us.

01:06:54.180 --> 01:06:59.160
For the apes lived in the same houses as

01:06:56.700 --> 01:07:01.859
the men, being regarded among them as

01:06:59.160 --> 01:07:04.260
gods, just as the dogs are among the

01:07:01.859 --> 01:07:06.900
Egyptians, and from the provisions laid

01:07:04.260 --> 01:07:08.579
up in the storerooms, the beasts took

01:07:06.900 --> 01:07:09.780
their food without hindrance whenever

01:07:08.579 --> 01:07:12.480
they wished.

01:07:09.780 --> 01:07:14.579
For any who killed this animal, as if he

01:07:12.480 --> 01:07:18.980
had committed the greatest sacrilege,

01:07:14.579 --> 01:07:18.980
death was established as the penalty.

01:07:19.140 --> 01:07:25.140
Around this time, monkeys began appearing

01:07:22.020 --> 01:07:28.200
as a motif in the art of regions of

01:07:25.140 --> 01:07:29.819
Italy, Sardinia, and elsewhere, suggesting

01:07:28.200 --> 01:07:33.359
that the Carthaginians were even

01:07:29.819 --> 01:07:36.720
exporting this animal to other regions.

01:07:33.359 --> 01:07:39.780
Some Barbary macaques were mummified in

01:07:36.720 --> 01:07:42.539
Egyptian tombs alongside pharaohs, and

01:07:39.780 --> 01:07:44.940
the skull of a Barbary macaque dated to

01:07:42.539 --> 01:07:48.480
around this time has even been unearthed

01:07:44.940 --> 01:07:51.539
as far away as Northern Ireland.

01:07:48.480 --> 01:07:53.880
Of course, in vast stables to the

01:07:51.539 --> 01:07:56.160
south of the city, were kept the animals

01:07:53.880 --> 01:07:59.160
that in most people's minds are most

01:07:56.160 --> 01:08:00.359
inseparably associated with the city of

01:07:59.160 --> 01:08:04.220
Carthage;

01:08:00.359 --> 01:08:04.220
that is the elephant.

01:08:07.500 --> 01:08:13.140
The North African elephant is an extinct

01:08:10.380 --> 01:08:16.020
subspecies of the African elephant that

01:08:13.140 --> 01:08:18.719
lived north of the Sahara Desert.

01:08:16.020 --> 01:08:21.000
Carthaginian paintings on walls, coins,

01:08:18.719 --> 01:08:23.640
and mosaics show that these elephants

01:08:21.000 --> 01:08:26.160
had the swooping backs and large ears

01:08:23.640 --> 01:08:27.779
typical of the African elephant that

01:08:26.160 --> 01:08:30.960
roams the Savannah,

01:08:27.779 --> 01:08:33.179
but it was considerably smaller and was

01:08:30.960 --> 01:08:36.299
likely similar in size to another

01:08:33.179 --> 01:08:37.560
surviving subspecies, the African forest

01:08:36.299 --> 01:08:39.779
elephant.

01:08:37.560 --> 01:08:41.940
These reach a shoulder height of about

01:08:39.779 --> 01:08:44.940
two and a half meters, only a little

01:08:41.940 --> 01:08:47.279
taller than the largest Shire horses, but

01:08:44.940 --> 01:08:50.580
of course, their thick and heavy frames

01:08:47.279 --> 01:08:52.380
mean they weigh more than 15 times the

01:08:50.580 --> 01:08:54.660
average horse.

01:08:52.380 --> 01:08:57.299
For this reason, these elephants were

01:08:54.660 --> 01:09:00.560
used by the Carthaginians as fearsome

01:08:57.299 --> 01:09:00.560
weapons of war.

01:09:00.719 --> 01:09:06.540
Some historians have speculated that

01:09:03.239 --> 01:09:09.420
Carthage may also have imported some

01:09:06.540 --> 01:09:12.000
much larger Indian elephants, which were

01:09:09.420 --> 01:09:13.920
at that time being used by the Seleucid

01:09:12.000 --> 01:09:16.319
dynasty in Syria.

01:09:13.920 --> 01:09:19.140
One elephant that was the pride of the

01:09:16.319 --> 01:09:22.020
later Carthaginian army was known by the

01:09:19.140 --> 01:09:24.060
name Surus, which some have translated to

01:09:22.020 --> 01:09:27.359
mean the Syrian.

01:09:24.060 --> 01:09:29.640
If true, this Syrian elephant would have

01:09:27.359 --> 01:09:32.100
towered as much as a meter over the

01:09:29.640 --> 01:09:34.739
smaller Carthaginian elephants, and would

01:09:32.100 --> 01:09:36.779
have been a truly terrifying sight on

01:09:34.739 --> 01:09:39.480
the battlefield.

01:09:36.779 --> 01:09:41.640
In India and Southeast Asia, it has

01:09:39.480 --> 01:09:44.279
always been common to use elephants as

01:09:41.640 --> 01:09:46.319
work animals to transport heavy loads

01:09:44.279 --> 01:09:48.299
for construction, but it's not clear

01:09:46.319 --> 01:09:50.339
whether the Carthaginians used their

01:09:48.299 --> 01:09:52.620
elephants in this manner or whether

01:09:50.339 --> 01:09:55.739
these precious animals were only

01:09:52.620 --> 01:09:57.840
reserved for their power and prestige, to

01:09:55.739 --> 01:10:00.239
be used as living tanks on the

01:09:57.840 --> 01:10:03.120
battlefield, as the writer Pliny the

01:10:00.239 --> 01:10:06.239
Elder prescribes.

01:10:03.120 --> 01:10:08.460
Elephants, when tamed, are employed in war

01:10:06.239 --> 01:10:10.800
and carry into the ranks of the enemy

01:10:08.460 --> 01:10:13.679
towers filled with armed men,

01:10:10.800 --> 01:10:15.960
and on them, in a very great measure,

01:10:13.679 --> 01:10:18.060
depends the ultimate result of the

01:10:15.960 --> 01:10:21.360
battles that are fought in the East.

01:10:18.060 --> 01:10:24.679
They tread underfoot whole companies and

01:10:21.360 --> 01:10:24.679
crush the men in their armor.

01:10:24.960 --> 01:10:30.540
But I think it's not hard to imagine

01:10:26.699 --> 01:10:33.600
that as in India, elephants may also have

01:10:30.540 --> 01:10:36.960
been used ceremonially in festivals and

01:10:33.600 --> 01:10:39.960
parades to carry kings and generals, a

01:10:36.960 --> 01:10:42.739
living embodiment of the might of this

01:10:39.960 --> 01:10:42.739
new empire.

01:10:49.080 --> 01:10:55.020
While Carthage didn't hesitate to go to

01:10:52.140 --> 01:10:58.320
war to defend its interests and protect

01:10:55.020 --> 01:11:00.540
its trade, it was not at heart a warrior

01:10:58.320 --> 01:11:02.640
culture, and it never suffered a conflict

01:11:00.540 --> 01:11:04.380
to continue any longer than it

01:11:02.640 --> 01:11:06.659
absolutely had to.

01:11:04.380 --> 01:11:09.659
The Carthaginians often relied on

01:11:06.659 --> 01:11:11.340
diplomatic solutions and agreements to

01:11:09.659 --> 01:11:14.159
avoid fighting with their various

01:11:11.340 --> 01:11:16.860
neighbors in the Mediterranean.

01:11:14.159 --> 01:11:20.940
One such agreement was settled in the

01:11:16.860 --> 01:11:23.520
year 509 BC with a minor city-state in

01:11:20.940 --> 01:11:26.159
central Italy, in the region of Latium,

01:11:23.520 --> 01:11:28.860
whose people spoke a small Italic

01:11:26.159 --> 01:11:31.560
dialect called Latin.

01:11:28.860 --> 01:11:34.199
This city's people had just that year

01:11:31.560 --> 01:11:36.900
thrown off the rule of their Etruscan

01:11:34.199 --> 01:11:40.020
king and abolished kingship in the city

01:11:36.900 --> 01:11:42.540
for good. In place of a king, they had

01:11:40.020 --> 01:11:45.780
brought in the rule of a pair of elected

01:11:42.540 --> 01:11:48.719
consuls drawn from the aristocracy, a

01:11:45.780 --> 01:11:51.780
system strikingly similar to and perhaps

01:11:48.719 --> 01:11:56.300
even inspired by the Carthaginians.

01:11:51.780 --> 01:11:56.300
This city's name was Rome.

01:11:56.400 --> 01:12:01.980
The Romans at that time were among

01:11:58.800 --> 01:12:05.100
several powers in central Italy facing

01:12:01.980 --> 01:12:07.380
rivals in the Etruscans to the north, and

01:12:05.100 --> 01:12:10.020
powerful tribal confederacies like the

01:12:07.380 --> 01:12:13.440
Samnites all fighting for dominance

01:12:10.020 --> 01:12:15.719
in the plains of central Italy.

01:12:13.440 --> 01:12:18.300
The Carthaginians seem to have taken

01:12:15.719 --> 01:12:20.880
note of this regional development and

01:12:18.300 --> 01:12:22.380
proceeded to sign a treaty with this new

01:12:20.880 --> 01:12:24.540
Roman republic,

01:12:22.380 --> 01:12:28.679
the contents of which the Greek

01:12:24.540 --> 01:12:28.679
historian Polybius records.

01:12:28.860 --> 01:12:34.620
There shall be friendship between the Romans

01:12:31.140 --> 01:12:37.440
and their allies, and the Carthaginians and their

01:12:34.620 --> 01:12:39.960
allies, on these conditions;

01:12:37.440 --> 01:12:42.960
neither the Romans nor their allies are

01:12:39.960 --> 01:12:45.480
to sail beyond the fair peninsula unless

01:12:42.960 --> 01:12:48.360
driven by stress of weather or the fear

01:12:45.480 --> 01:12:50.820
of enemies. If any one of them be driven

01:12:48.360 --> 01:12:53.520
ashore, he shall not buy or take anything

01:12:50.820 --> 01:12:56.100
for himself, save what is needed for the

01:12:53.520 --> 01:12:59.219
repair of his ship and the service of

01:12:56.100 --> 01:13:02.520
the gods, and he shall depart within five

01:12:59.219 --> 01:13:05.100
days. Carthage shall build no fort in

01:13:02.520 --> 01:13:09.679
Latium, and if they enter the district in

01:13:05.100 --> 01:13:09.679
arms, they shall not stay a night therein.

01:13:11.520 --> 01:13:17.040
The theme of this treaty was simple; you

01:13:14.460 --> 01:13:18.060
leave us alone and we will leave you

01:13:17.040 --> 01:13:20.460
alone.

01:13:18.060 --> 01:13:23.159
While Rome was at this point very

01:13:20.460 --> 01:13:25.080
much on the Carthaginian's radar, it

01:13:23.159 --> 01:13:28.320
seems that they considered this Italian

01:13:25.080 --> 01:13:30.860
city republic to be little cause of

01:13:28.320 --> 01:13:30.860
concern.

01:13:37.440 --> 01:13:43.860
Around the year 410 BC, Carthage began

01:13:41.280 --> 01:13:46.260
minting its own silver coins, and each

01:13:43.860 --> 01:13:49.140
coin would be stamped with the symbol of

01:13:46.260 --> 01:13:51.960
a palm tree in Greek, known as Phoenike,

01:13:49.140 --> 01:13:53.400
now becoming a symbol of Phoenician

01:13:51.960 --> 01:13:56.159
identity.

01:13:53.400 --> 01:13:58.199
Carthage was now presenting itself as

01:13:56.159 --> 01:14:00.840
the new champion of the Phoenician

01:13:58.199 --> 01:14:02.100
people, the capital of the Phoenician

01:14:00.840 --> 01:14:04.620
world.

01:14:02.100 --> 01:14:07.980
It was now beginning to look a lot Like

01:14:04.620 --> 01:14:10.860
an empire, and like all empires, it soon

01:14:07.980 --> 01:14:13.860
found an increasing need to defend and

01:14:10.860 --> 01:14:16.260
expand its territory.

01:14:13.860 --> 01:14:18.840
It's often said that Carthage relied on

01:14:16.260 --> 01:14:20.640
mercenaries to fight its wars, but this

01:14:18.840 --> 01:14:23.940
is something of an oversimplification.

01:14:20.640 --> 01:14:26.520
While these kinds of armies-for-hire did

01:14:23.940 --> 01:14:28.199
make up one part of their forces, in fact,

01:14:26.520 --> 01:14:30.540
there were all kinds of reasons that

01:14:28.199 --> 01:14:31.560
people came to fight for the empire of

01:14:30.540 --> 01:14:33.719
Carthage.

01:14:31.560 --> 01:14:35.940
Many of their soldiers were sent to

01:14:33.719 --> 01:14:38.159
fight for them as part of treaties, just

01:14:35.940 --> 01:14:40.620
as the Phoenicians had once promised to

01:14:38.159 --> 01:14:43.260
send their ships to fight for Assyria.

01:14:40.620 --> 01:14:45.420
As Carthage expanded to conquer new

01:14:43.260 --> 01:14:47.520
peoples all along the North African

01:14:45.420 --> 01:14:50.940
coast and across the Mediterranean,

01:14:47.520 --> 01:14:52.500
ever more power and variety was added to

01:14:50.940 --> 01:14:55.739
its forces.

01:14:52.500 --> 01:14:58.219
When war came, each ally and province

01:14:55.739 --> 01:15:01.860
would send fighters of a particular kind

01:14:58.219 --> 01:15:04.679
based on what they specialized in.

01:15:01.860 --> 01:15:07.199
The North African power of Numidia to

01:15:04.679 --> 01:15:09.960
the west of Carthage sent powerful and

01:15:07.199 --> 01:15:13.020
experienced cavalry and javelin-throwers,

01:15:09.960 --> 01:15:15.960
while colonies in the island of Majorca

01:15:13.020 --> 01:15:18.179
would send slingers, and peasant spearmen

01:15:15.960 --> 01:15:20.580
with large, round shields were

01:15:18.179 --> 01:15:22.020
conscripted from the fields of Libya in

01:15:20.580 --> 01:15:25.020
the East.

01:15:22.020 --> 01:15:27.600
Celts from Spain made up some part of

01:15:25.020 --> 01:15:30.239
their forces, and sometimes even Greeks

01:15:27.600 --> 01:15:31.260
and Italians ended up fighting in these

01:15:30.239 --> 01:15:33.900
armies.

01:15:31.260 --> 01:15:36.960
There was only one group of people who

01:15:33.900 --> 01:15:41.540
hardly ever fought for Carthage, and that

01:15:36.960 --> 01:15:41.540
was the citizens of Carthage themselves.

01:15:42.420 --> 01:15:47.280
The Carthaginian system relied largely

01:15:45.120 --> 01:15:50.219
on making life as comfortable as

01:15:47.280 --> 01:15:53.520
possible for the people of the capital.

01:15:50.219 --> 01:15:56.340
Few Carthaginian politicians ever risked

01:15:53.520 --> 01:15:58.679
the unpopular move of conscripting its

01:15:56.340 --> 01:16:01.020
citizens into the army, and so, they

01:15:58.679 --> 01:16:03.239
amassed their forces out of units

01:16:01.020 --> 01:16:06.900
brought from all the four corners of the

01:16:03.239 --> 01:16:09.179
empire. Each army of Carthage was its own

01:16:06.900 --> 01:16:11.640
unique patchwork and would have spoken

01:16:09.179 --> 01:16:15.000
dozens of different languages, as the

01:16:11.640 --> 01:16:17.340
Greek historian Polybius writes.

01:16:15.000 --> 01:16:19.500
It was therefore impossible to assemble

01:16:17.340 --> 01:16:22.199
them and address them as a body or to do

01:16:19.500 --> 01:16:24.060
so by any other means, for how could any

01:16:22.199 --> 01:16:27.179
general be expected to know all their

01:16:24.060 --> 01:16:29.400
languages? And again to address them

01:16:27.179 --> 01:16:32.219
through several interpreters, repeating

01:16:29.400 --> 01:16:36.080
the same thing four or five times, was, if

01:16:32.219 --> 01:16:36.080
anything, more impractical.

01:16:36.239 --> 01:16:40.860
It was a system that had many weaknesses,

01:16:38.940 --> 01:16:43.739
but it allowed the empire to raise

01:16:40.860 --> 01:16:45.120
large armies at short notice, and it

01:16:43.739 --> 01:16:47.580
meant that since they could never be

01:16:45.120 --> 01:16:50.880
accused of sending good Carthaginian men

01:16:47.580 --> 01:16:53.340
to die, the politicians of the city were

01:16:50.880 --> 01:16:56.159
largely insulated from the consequences

01:16:53.340 --> 01:16:58.440
of going to war.

01:16:56.159 --> 01:17:00.540
But soon these armies would find

01:16:58.440 --> 01:17:02.940
themselves embroiled in a bitter

01:17:00.540 --> 01:17:05.400
struggle that would test this system to

01:17:02.940 --> 01:17:07.560
its breaking point and threaten to bring

01:17:05.400 --> 01:17:08.940
the whole empire to the brink of

01:17:07.560 --> 01:17:11.580
destruction.

01:17:08.940 --> 01:17:13.739
These wars would erupt over what would

01:17:11.580 --> 01:17:16.199
soon become the most fought-over piece

01:17:13.739 --> 01:17:21.080
of land in the Mediterranean;

01:17:16.199 --> 01:17:21.080
that is the island of Sicily.

01:17:28.739 --> 01:17:33.900
Sicily is the largest island in the

01:17:31.620 --> 01:17:36.719
Mediterranean Sea.

01:17:33.900 --> 01:17:39.360
It sits off the southern end of Italy,

01:17:36.719 --> 01:17:42.300
separated by the narrow waters of the

01:17:39.360 --> 01:17:45.360
Straits of Messina, only three kilometers

01:17:42.300 --> 01:17:48.420
wide at its narrowest point.

01:17:45.360 --> 01:17:51.300
Sicily's most prominent landmark is the

01:17:48.420 --> 01:17:54.120
volcano Mount Etna, towering

01:17:51.300 --> 01:17:56.520
3,000 meters over its eastern coast,

01:17:54.120 --> 01:17:59.340
and due to the islandís particularly

01:17:56.520 --> 01:18:03.320
violent geology, this is one of the most

01:17:59.340 --> 01:18:03.320
active volcanoes in the world.

01:18:04.560 --> 01:18:08.760
Although we think of it today as part of

01:18:06.719 --> 01:18:11.159
Europe, Sicily is actually on the

01:18:08.760 --> 01:18:14.219
northern edge of the African continental

01:18:11.159 --> 01:18:16.440
plate, right at the impact point where

01:18:14.219 --> 01:18:19.380
the European plate is grinding it

01:18:16.440 --> 01:18:22.140
downwards into the Earth's mantle.

01:18:19.380 --> 01:18:24.719
The collision of these titanic forces

01:18:22.140 --> 01:18:28.760
means that Mount Etna erupts an average

01:18:24.719 --> 01:18:28.760
200 times every year.

01:18:29.280 --> 01:18:35.219
The volcanic ash spewed by this volcano

01:18:32.400 --> 01:18:37.980
gives the soil of Sicily an incredible

01:18:35.219 --> 01:18:40.440
fertility, meaning that its farmlands

01:18:37.980 --> 01:18:43.860
have always been rich.

01:18:40.440 --> 01:18:46.380
At first, Carthage enjoyed an unrivaled

01:18:43.860 --> 01:18:48.960
position on the island, trading with the

01:18:46.380 --> 01:18:52.020
Sicilian locals in the west just a short

01:18:48.960 --> 01:18:54.239
hop away from their capital in Africa,

01:18:52.020 --> 01:18:56.699
but soon they would come into conflict

01:18:54.239 --> 01:18:58.679
with another group of people that for

01:18:56.699 --> 01:19:01.679
much of this history would be their

01:18:58.679 --> 01:19:05.100
greatest rivals on the sea and the land,

01:19:01.679 --> 01:19:07.440
a people who were at the same time also

01:19:05.100 --> 01:19:09.179
busy establishing colonies across the

01:19:07.440 --> 01:19:13.040
Mediterranean.

01:19:09.179 --> 01:19:13.040
These were the Greeks.

01:19:16.260 --> 01:19:21.960
The Greeks, like the Phoenicians, were

01:19:19.199 --> 01:19:24.840
expert sailors and had built a number of

01:19:21.960 --> 01:19:27.900
thriving colonies in southern Italy, in

01:19:24.840 --> 01:19:30.360
what is now Turkey and in the Black Sea.

01:19:27.900 --> 01:19:33.060
Beginning in the 8th century BC,

01:19:30.360 --> 01:19:35.280
Greek explorers and traders began

01:19:33.060 --> 01:19:37.560
expanding their interests onto the

01:19:35.280 --> 01:19:40.080
island of Sicily.

01:19:37.560 --> 01:19:42.480
Like the Phoenicians, the Greeks at this

01:19:40.080 --> 01:19:44.880
time weren't a unified people.

01:19:42.480 --> 01:19:47.640
They spoke four different dialects of

01:19:44.880 --> 01:19:49.560
Greek and countless sub-dialects, and

01:19:47.640 --> 01:19:52.080
came from dozens of independent

01:19:49.560 --> 01:19:54.000
city-states and island kingdoms that

01:19:52.080 --> 01:19:56.460
often fought with each other more

01:19:54.000 --> 01:19:59.219
bitterly than with any foreigners.

01:19:56.460 --> 01:20:00.960
But despite these internal divisions, the

01:19:59.219 --> 01:20:03.960
Greeks would expand across the southern

01:20:00.960 --> 01:20:06.540
portion of Italy and Sicily, and joined

01:20:03.960 --> 01:20:10.199
up this series of colonies into an area

01:20:06.540 --> 01:20:13.280
that they would call Megale Hellas, or

01:20:10.199 --> 01:20:13.280
Greater Greece.

01:20:14.159 --> 01:20:19.800
Wherever they went, Greek settlers were

01:20:16.920 --> 01:20:22.800
in part inspired by the myth of their

01:20:19.800 --> 01:20:24.480
hero Heracles, who the Romans would call

01:20:22.800 --> 01:20:27.360
Hercules.

01:20:24.480 --> 01:20:29.040
He was a half-divine warrior who

01:20:27.360 --> 01:20:31.739
traveled the length and breadth of

01:20:29.040 --> 01:20:34.320
Europe, performing his famous twelve

01:20:31.739 --> 01:20:36.659
labors, and meanwhile performing great

01:20:34.320 --> 01:20:39.659
deeds wherever he passed through.

01:20:36.659 --> 01:20:41.820
Wherever a new Greek colony sprung

01:20:39.659 --> 01:20:44.100
up around the Mediterranean, a new

01:20:41.820 --> 01:20:47.100
installment of the Hercules myth would

01:20:44.100 --> 01:20:49.980
quickly be added, to show that this had

01:20:47.100 --> 01:20:51.960
also been one of his stops. In some

01:20:49.980 --> 01:20:54.600
places, he was celebrated for slaying

01:20:51.960 --> 01:20:57.540
giants and mythical beasts, while in

01:20:54.600 --> 01:20:59.880
others his feats were more mundane.

01:20:57.540 --> 01:21:02.219
In the Greek colonies of southern Italy,

01:20:59.880 --> 01:21:05.159
he was remembered for banishing a plague

01:21:02.219 --> 01:21:07.739
of flies that was harming the livestock.

01:21:05.159 --> 01:21:10.920
In Crete, he had rid the island of wild

01:21:07.739 --> 01:21:13.800
beasts, and in Sicily, he had caught an

01:21:10.920 --> 01:21:15.300
errant bull and bested the king in a

01:21:13.800 --> 01:21:18.480
wrestling match.

01:21:15.300 --> 01:21:21.480
In Spain, Diodorus of Sicily recounts that

01:21:18.480 --> 01:21:23.219
depending on who you asked, Hercules was

01:21:21.480 --> 01:21:25.440
credited with either creating the

01:21:23.219 --> 01:21:28.620
Straits of Gibraltar by tearing the land

01:21:25.440 --> 01:21:30.900
apart or with narrowing it to keep out

01:21:28.620 --> 01:21:32.940
sea monsters.

01:21:30.900 --> 01:21:35.640
Whereas before that time a great space

01:21:32.940 --> 01:21:37.800
had stood between Africa and Europe, he

01:21:35.640 --> 01:21:40.380
now narrowed the passage, in order that

01:21:37.800 --> 01:21:42.120
by making it shallow and narrow he might

01:21:40.380 --> 01:21:43.920
prevent the great sea monsters from

01:21:42.120 --> 01:21:45.420
passing out of the ocean and into the

01:21:43.920 --> 01:21:48.179
inner sea.

01:21:45.420 --> 01:21:50.820
Some authorities, however, say just the

01:21:48.179 --> 01:21:53.219
opposite, namely that the two continents

01:21:50.820 --> 01:21:55.500
were originally joined and that he cut a

01:21:53.219 --> 01:21:57.300
passage between them, that the ocean was

01:21:55.500 --> 01:21:59.820
mingled with the sea.

01:21:57.300 --> 01:22:02.460
On this question, however, it would be

01:21:59.820 --> 01:22:04.940
possible for every man to think as he

01:22:02.460 --> 01:22:04.940
may please.

01:22:05.699 --> 01:22:10.440
In one of the most dramatic episodes of

01:22:08.100 --> 01:22:13.440
these tales, during his tenth labor,

01:22:10.440 --> 01:22:16.560
Hercules is tasked with stealing the red

01:22:13.440 --> 01:22:19.500
cattle of the ogre Geryon, who lived in

01:22:16.560 --> 01:22:21.900
Erythia in southern Spain, close to the

01:22:19.500 --> 01:22:24.840
Phoenician colony of Gades.

01:22:21.900 --> 01:22:27.120
Since Geryon lived so far in the west, it

01:22:24.840 --> 01:22:29.040
was said, the hides of his cattle had

01:22:27.120 --> 01:22:32.280
been stained red by their close

01:22:29.040 --> 01:22:35.340
proximity to the setting sun.

01:22:32.280 --> 01:22:37.860
After killing Geryon, Hercules takes his

01:22:35.340 --> 01:22:39.960
cattle and herds them all the way back

01:22:37.860 --> 01:22:42.239
home to Greece in a meandering route

01:22:39.960 --> 01:22:44.640
that took him from Spain, through

01:22:42.239 --> 01:22:47.699
southern France, and over the soaring

01:22:44.640 --> 01:22:51.840
snowy mountains of the Alps, and on into

01:22:47.699 --> 01:22:55.320
Italy, as Diodorus recounts.

01:22:51.840 --> 01:22:57.120
Hercules then made his way to Italy, and

01:22:55.320 --> 01:22:59.820
as he traversed the mountain pass

01:22:57.120 --> 01:23:01.860
through the Alps, he made a highway out

01:22:59.820 --> 01:23:05.040
of the route, which was rough and almost

01:23:01.860 --> 01:23:07.380
impassible. The barbarians who had

01:23:05.040 --> 01:23:09.600
inhabited this mountain region had been

01:23:07.380 --> 01:23:12.060
accustomed to butcher and to plunder

01:23:09.600 --> 01:23:13.800
such armies as pass through when they

01:23:12.060 --> 01:23:17.640
came to the difficult portions of the

01:23:13.800 --> 01:23:19.320
way, but he subdued them all.

01:23:19.320 --> 01:23:24.300
The story of Hercules bringing these

01:23:21.900 --> 01:23:27.120
cattle from Spain over these mountains

01:23:24.300 --> 01:23:29.460
was the dramatic pinnacle of a series of

01:23:27.120 --> 01:23:31.320
myths that would become known as the

01:23:29.460 --> 01:23:33.780
Heraclean way.

01:23:31.320 --> 01:23:36.060
It was a series of stories that would be

01:23:33.780 --> 01:23:38.699
told to countless generations of Greek

01:23:36.060 --> 01:23:41.340
settlers and then to the children of the

01:23:38.699 --> 01:23:44.100
Romans who followed them. As the

01:23:41.340 --> 01:23:46.679
Phoenician hero god Melqart became

01:23:44.100 --> 01:23:49.260
increasingly associated with Hercules in

01:23:46.679 --> 01:23:52.560
later years, these stories would also be

01:23:49.260 --> 01:23:54.960
told to the children of Carthage.

01:23:52.560 --> 01:23:57.060
With stories of this wandering hero on

01:23:54.960 --> 01:23:59.760
their lips, the Greek settlements in

01:23:57.060 --> 01:24:02.400
eastern Sicily grew.

01:23:59.760 --> 01:24:04.380
For several centuries, they maintained an

01:24:02.400 --> 01:24:07.140
uneasy peace with the Carthaginian

01:24:04.380 --> 01:24:09.360
colonies in the west of the island,

01:24:07.140 --> 01:24:12.239
but as both powers began to require

01:24:09.360 --> 01:24:16.020
greater amounts of land, they would soon

01:24:12.239 --> 01:24:18.840
find themselves on a collision course.

01:24:16.020 --> 01:24:22.199
The exact dating and details of these

01:24:18.840 --> 01:24:24.179
wars is still fiercely contested, but

01:24:22.199 --> 01:24:27.960
it's clear that by the late 5th century

01:24:24.179 --> 01:24:30.600
BC, Sicily had erupted in warfare between

01:24:27.960 --> 01:24:33.179
Carthage and the Greeks.

01:24:30.600 --> 01:24:37.760
Soon, it would resemble a piece of meat

01:24:33.179 --> 01:24:37.760
being torn apart by two hungry dogs.

01:24:38.100 --> 01:24:43.260
The economy of the island suffered.

01:24:40.400 --> 01:24:46.440
Warlords established themselves as the

01:24:43.260 --> 01:24:50.040
tyrant rulers of its cities, and banditry

01:24:46.440 --> 01:24:52.140
and lawlessness spread.

01:24:50.040 --> 01:24:54.600
For much of these centuries of fighting,

01:24:52.140 --> 01:24:57.600
the Carthaginians were happy to let the

01:24:54.600 --> 01:25:00.360
wars with the Greeks simmer on.

01:24:57.600 --> 01:25:02.880
The citizens of its capital never went

01:25:00.360 --> 01:25:04.620
to war, and so long as the peace and

01:25:02.880 --> 01:25:07.440
comfort of their city was never

01:25:04.620 --> 01:25:10.140
disturbed, it must have felt to them that

01:25:07.440 --> 01:25:12.179
these wars were a very long way from

01:25:10.140 --> 01:25:14.699
home.

01:25:12.179 --> 01:25:18.060
But the final episode of these conflicts,

01:25:14.699 --> 01:25:22.460
known as the Seventh Sicilian War, would

01:25:18.060 --> 01:25:22.460
puncture this sense of invulnerability.

01:25:22.920 --> 01:25:27.600
That's because Carthage would find

01:25:24.840 --> 01:25:29.699
itself in a life or death struggle with

01:25:27.600 --> 01:25:33.060
a man who would bring the war home to

01:25:29.699 --> 01:25:36.600
their shores in dramatic fashion. He was

01:25:33.060 --> 01:25:39.239
a king of Syracuse, a Greek city-state on

01:25:36.600 --> 01:25:43.400
the southeastern coast of Sicily, and his

01:25:39.239 --> 01:25:43.400
name was Agathocles.

01:26:02.719 --> 01:26:08.520
Agathocles began life as a commoner

01:26:05.699 --> 01:26:12.000
in the Sicilian colonies, the son of a

01:26:08.520 --> 01:26:14.219
potter in the port city of Syracuse.

01:26:12.000 --> 01:26:16.560
At first he learned his father's trade,

01:26:14.219 --> 01:26:19.199
but soon entered the army and rose

01:26:16.560 --> 01:26:22.020
through its ranks until he was able to

01:26:19.199 --> 01:26:26.639
enact a military coup and seize the

01:26:22.020 --> 01:26:29.040
throne of the city, in the year 317 BC.

01:26:26.639 --> 01:26:32.520
Agathocles had a high opinion of

01:26:29.040 --> 01:26:34.800
himself, and as the tyrant of Syracuse, he

01:26:32.520 --> 01:26:37.260
minted silver coins that portrayed

01:26:34.800 --> 01:26:40.440
himself as the heir to Alexander the

01:26:37.260 --> 01:26:43.860
Great, the greatest of all the Greeks,

01:26:40.440 --> 01:26:47.219
and like Alexander, Agathocles had

01:26:43.860 --> 01:26:50.580
dreams of conquest. He soon set about

01:26:47.219 --> 01:26:54.620
subjugating cities all around him, as the

01:26:50.580 --> 01:26:57.360
historian Diodorus of Sicily recalls.

01:26:54.620 --> 01:26:59.340
Agathocles began unhampered to

01:26:57.360 --> 01:27:00.179
subject the cities and strongholds to

01:26:59.340 --> 01:27:02.340
himself.

01:27:00.179 --> 01:27:03.900
Mastering many of them quickly, he made

01:27:02.340 --> 01:27:06.239
his power secure.

01:27:03.900 --> 01:27:08.820
In fact, he built up for himself a host

01:27:06.239 --> 01:27:10.560
of allies, ample revenues, and a

01:27:08.820 --> 01:27:12.360
considerable army.

01:27:10.560 --> 01:27:15.480
He had picked a mercenary force

01:27:12.360 --> 01:27:17.219
comprising 10,000 foot soldiers and

01:27:15.480 --> 01:27:20.280
3,500 horse.

01:27:17.219 --> 01:27:22.980
Moreover, he prepared a store of weapons

01:27:20.280 --> 01:27:24.600
and of missiles of all kinds, since he

01:27:22.980 --> 01:27:28.219
knew that the Carthaginians would

01:27:24.600 --> 01:27:28.219
shortly wage war against him.

01:27:28.739 --> 01:27:34.800
As predicted, it wasn't long before the

01:27:31.679 --> 01:27:36.780
Carthaginians began to see Agathocles as

01:27:34.800 --> 01:27:39.780
a serious threat.

01:27:36.780 --> 01:27:42.540
Carthage amassed a huge army in its

01:27:39.780 --> 01:27:45.120
usual way, gathering mercenaries and

01:27:42.540 --> 01:27:48.360
levees from all of its territories and

01:27:45.120 --> 01:27:50.940
allies; slingers, spearmen, cavalry,

01:27:48.360 --> 01:27:53.460
elephants, likely speaking a dozen

01:27:50.940 --> 01:27:55.080
different languages, and sailed all of

01:27:53.460 --> 01:27:57.420
them to Sicily.

01:27:55.080 --> 01:27:59.699
On the way, many of their ships were

01:27:57.420 --> 01:28:01.920
wrecked in a storm, but the force that

01:27:59.699 --> 01:28:04.800
arrived was still easily enough to

01:28:01.920 --> 01:28:07.380
overpower the tyrant Agathocles, as

01:28:04.800 --> 01:28:09.600
Diodorus recounts.

01:28:07.380 --> 01:28:11.639
As Agathocles saw the forces of

01:28:09.600 --> 01:28:14.040
the Carthaginians were superior to his

01:28:11.639 --> 01:28:15.420
own, he surmised that not a few of the

01:28:14.040 --> 01:28:17.820
strongholds could go over to the

01:28:15.420 --> 01:28:20.460
Phoenicians, and also those of the cities

01:28:17.820 --> 01:28:23.100
that were offended with him. After a

01:28:20.460 --> 01:28:25.920
stinging defeat on the Himera River in

01:28:23.100 --> 01:28:29.040
central Sicily, Agathocles retreated east

01:28:25.920 --> 01:28:31.380
to his port capital of Syracuse, where

01:28:29.040 --> 01:28:34.199
the Carthaginians surrounded the city

01:28:31.380 --> 01:28:37.020
and laid siege.

01:28:34.199 --> 01:28:38.400
For Agathocles, it looked like all hope

01:28:37.020 --> 01:28:41.159
was lost,

01:28:38.400 --> 01:28:44.100
but it's here in this desperate moment

01:28:41.159 --> 01:28:45.780
that he decided on a truly daring course

01:28:44.100 --> 01:28:48.659
of action.

01:28:45.780 --> 01:28:52.020
He hatched a plan to break free of the

01:28:48.659 --> 01:28:54.659
siege by ship, set sail for Africa, and

01:28:52.020 --> 01:28:58.560
make a desperate strike at the heart of

01:28:54.659 --> 01:29:00.600
his enemy, the city of Carthage itself.

01:28:58.560 --> 01:29:03.000
When he saw that all his allies had

01:29:00.600 --> 01:29:05.520
changed sides and that barbarians were

01:29:03.000 --> 01:29:08.520
masters of almost all Sicily except

01:29:05.520 --> 01:29:11.219
Syracuse and were far superior in both

01:29:08.520 --> 01:29:13.800
land and sea forces, he carried out an

01:29:11.219 --> 01:29:15.120
undertaking that was unexpected and most

01:29:13.800 --> 01:29:17.040
reckless.

01:29:15.120 --> 01:29:19.620
He determined to leave an adequate

01:29:17.040 --> 01:29:21.900
garrison for the city, to select those of

01:29:19.620 --> 01:29:25.020
the soldiers who were fit, and with these

01:29:21.900 --> 01:29:27.780
to cross over into Libya, for he hoped

01:29:25.020 --> 01:29:30.179
that if he did this, those in Carthage

01:29:27.780 --> 01:29:33.540
who had been living luxuriously in long-

01:29:30.179 --> 01:29:35.400
-continued peace and were therefore

01:29:33.540 --> 01:29:39.540
without experience in the dangers of

01:29:35.400 --> 01:29:41.699
battle, would easily be defeated.

01:29:39.540 --> 01:29:44.520
When the Carthaginians saw the Greek

01:29:41.699 --> 01:29:46.920
fleet leaving Syracuse, they believed

01:29:44.520 --> 01:29:48.000
Agathocles to be fleeing, and they pursued

01:29:46.920 --> 01:29:50.520
him.

01:29:48.000 --> 01:29:52.260
They chased the Greeks, harrying them

01:29:50.520 --> 01:29:54.840
across the sea for hundreds of

01:29:52.260 --> 01:29:56.639
kilometers, pelting them with arrows and

01:29:54.840 --> 01:29:59.040
slingstones.

01:29:56.639 --> 01:30:01.980
But luck was on the side of the Greeks,

01:29:59.040 --> 01:30:06.440
and Agathocles and his soldiers were

01:30:01.980 --> 01:30:06.440
able to land on the beaches of Africa.

01:30:06.719 --> 01:30:11.159
Agathocles must have feared that his

01:30:09.120 --> 01:30:14.040
soldiers would lose courage and attempt

01:30:11.159 --> 01:30:17.219
to flee, and so, he ordered their ships to

01:30:14.040 --> 01:30:20.040
be burned in an offering to the gods, as

01:30:17.219 --> 01:30:22.260
Diodorus recounts.

01:30:20.040 --> 01:30:24.360
Standing by the stern, he bade the others

01:30:22.260 --> 01:30:26.580
also to follow his example.

01:30:24.360 --> 01:30:28.620
Then, as all the captains threw in the

01:30:26.580 --> 01:30:30.840
fire and the flames quickly blazed high,

01:30:28.620 --> 01:30:33.060
the trumpeter sounded the signal for

01:30:30.840 --> 01:30:35.280
battle and the army raised the war cry,

01:30:33.060 --> 01:30:36.540
while altogether prayed for a safe

01:30:35.280 --> 01:30:39.600
return home.

01:30:36.540 --> 01:30:41.699
This Agathocles did, for it was clear

01:30:39.600 --> 01:30:43.800
that if the retreat to the ships was cut

01:30:41.699 --> 01:30:47.159
off, in victory alone would they have

01:30:43.800 --> 01:30:49.020
hope for safety. Nevertheless, when all

01:30:47.159 --> 01:30:52.080
the ships were aflame and the fire was

01:30:49.020 --> 01:30:54.600
spreading widely, terror laid hold upon

01:30:52.080 --> 01:30:56.520
the Sicilians as they considered the

01:30:54.600 --> 01:30:58.020
vastness of the sea that separated them

01:30:56.520 --> 01:31:00.719
from home.

01:30:58.020 --> 01:31:02.699
From the city walls of Carthage, the

01:31:00.719 --> 01:31:05.760
fires of the burning ships would have

01:31:02.699 --> 01:31:07.860
been visible on the horizon, and now fear

01:31:05.760 --> 01:31:09.480
was beginning to spread among its

01:31:07.860 --> 01:31:12.000
citizens.

01:31:09.480 --> 01:31:14.219
For them, war was something that happened

01:31:12.000 --> 01:31:16.440
in other places.

01:31:14.219 --> 01:31:18.540
The city had never been significantly

01:31:16.440 --> 01:31:22.020
threatened before, and there were

01:31:18.540 --> 01:31:24.540
virtually no forces there to defend it.

01:31:22.020 --> 01:31:25.320
Panic and great confusion seized upon the

01:31:24.540 --> 01:31:27.719
city.

01:31:25.320 --> 01:31:29.580
The crowds rushed to the marketplace, and

01:31:27.719 --> 01:31:30.719
the Council of Elders consulted what

01:31:29.580 --> 01:31:33.719
should be done.

01:31:30.719 --> 01:31:36.000
In fact, there was no army at hand that

01:31:33.719 --> 01:31:38.159
could take the field against the enemy.

01:31:36.000 --> 01:31:40.560
The mass of the citizens, who had no

01:31:38.159 --> 01:31:42.840
experience in warfare, were already in

01:31:40.560 --> 01:31:45.060
despair, and the enemy was thought to be

01:31:42.840 --> 01:31:47.639
near the walls.

01:31:45.060 --> 01:31:51.000
For the first time, the citizens of

01:31:47.639 --> 01:31:54.360
Carthage would actually have to fight.

01:31:51.000 --> 01:31:57.179
They were conscripted en masse, given long

01:31:54.360 --> 01:32:00.179
spears and shields, perhaps given some

01:31:57.179 --> 01:32:02.760
rudimentary training, and along with the

01:32:00.179 --> 01:32:05.600
small complement of city guards, marched

01:32:02.760 --> 01:32:08.760
out to meet the Greeks in battle.

01:32:05.600 --> 01:32:11.040
The Carthaginians hoped to make up for

01:32:08.760 --> 01:32:14.340
the poor quality of their citizen troops

01:32:11.040 --> 01:32:16.560
with sheer numbers, and, vastly

01:32:14.340 --> 01:32:19.560
outnumbering Agathocles, they were

01:32:16.560 --> 01:32:21.360
confident of victory, but that was not to

01:32:19.560 --> 01:32:24.420
be the case.

01:32:21.360 --> 01:32:27.060
When they met, the experienced and now

01:32:24.420 --> 01:32:29.580
desperate Greeks smashed the citizen

01:32:27.060 --> 01:32:31.940
soldiers of Carthage, ran them off the

01:32:29.580 --> 01:32:35.460
battlefield, and flooded into their camp.

01:32:31.940 --> 01:32:38.420
Here, Diodorus writes that they made a

01:32:35.460 --> 01:32:38.420
telling discovery.

01:32:38.699 --> 01:32:43.679
In the camp of the Carthaginians were

01:32:40.860 --> 01:32:46.080
found, along with other goods, many wagons

01:32:43.679 --> 01:32:49.620
in which were being transported more

01:32:46.080 --> 01:32:51.900
than 20,000 pairs of manacles. For the

01:32:49.620 --> 01:32:54.480
Carthaginians, having expected to master

01:32:51.900 --> 01:32:56.880
the Greeks easily, had passed the word

01:32:54.480 --> 01:32:59.820
along among themselves to take alive as

01:32:56.880 --> 01:33:02.520
many as possible, and, after shackling, 

01:32:59.820 --> 01:33:05.100
to throw them into slave pens.

01:33:02.520 --> 01:33:07.260
With this army defeated, the city of

01:33:05.100 --> 01:33:10.500
Carthage was now completely surrounded

01:33:07.260 --> 01:33:12.600
by hostile forces, and Diodorus can't

01:33:10.500 --> 01:33:15.659
help but comment on the ridiculous

01:33:12.600 --> 01:33:18.239
nature of the situation.

01:33:15.659 --> 01:33:20.100
In Sicily, the Carthaginians, who had

01:33:18.239 --> 01:33:23.280
defeated Agathocles in a great battle,

01:33:20.100 --> 01:33:25.380
were besieging Syracuse, but in Libya,

01:33:23.280 --> 01:33:29.120
Agathocles had brought the

01:33:25.380 --> 01:33:29.120
Carthaginians under siege.

01:33:29.900 --> 01:33:35.699
It's here that the Carthaginians, in

01:33:32.880 --> 01:33:38.460
their desperation, seem to have turned to

01:33:35.699 --> 01:33:40.980
an ancient ritual that forms one of the

01:33:38.460 --> 01:33:42.420
darkest and most controversial aspects

01:33:40.980 --> 01:33:47.600
of their history;

01:33:42.420 --> 01:33:47.600
that is, the rite of child sacrifice.

01:33:53.580 --> 01:33:59.639
Human sacrifice was, at certain times, a

01:33:57.360 --> 01:34:02.760
feature of various societies in the

01:33:59.639 --> 01:34:05.280
ancient world. Rituals of this kind have

01:34:02.760 --> 01:34:07.800
been attested in several indigenous

01:34:05.280 --> 01:34:10.800
American societies and in the early

01:34:07.800 --> 01:34:13.860
histories of Israel and Judah, as well as

01:34:10.800 --> 01:34:15.360
the cities of Phoenicia, like Tyre and

01:34:13.860 --> 01:34:18.420
Sidon.

01:34:15.360 --> 01:34:20.600
The Book of Kings records one king of

01:34:18.420 --> 01:34:23.760
the Levantine kingdom of Moab

01:34:20.600 --> 01:34:25.980
sacrificing his firstborn child when a

01:34:23.760 --> 01:34:28.860
war isn't going his way.

01:34:25.980 --> 01:34:32.100
In Ireland, Britain, and Northern Germany,

01:34:28.860 --> 01:34:34.860
during the Iron Age, sacrificial victims

01:34:32.100 --> 01:34:38.040
were ritually strangled and cast into

01:34:34.860 --> 01:34:42.480
bogs, where the acidic waters mummified

01:34:38.040 --> 01:34:45.719
them in a state of perfect preservation.

01:34:42.480 --> 01:34:48.420
This idea of a deadly exchange with the

01:34:45.719 --> 01:34:50.880
gods seems to be one that recurs in

01:34:48.420 --> 01:34:53.820
human psychology, and has independently

01:34:50.880 --> 01:34:55.860
arisen in multiple cultures. The idea

01:34:53.820 --> 01:34:57.780
that if we want to ask the gods for a

01:34:55.860 --> 01:35:01.560
great favor, we have to give them

01:34:57.780 --> 01:35:03.840
something truly precious in exchange, and

01:35:01.560 --> 01:35:05.460
what could be more precious than a human

01:35:03.840 --> 01:35:07.440
life?

01:35:05.460 --> 01:35:11.040
With the writing down of the Hebrew

01:35:07.440 --> 01:35:13.920
Bible and the law codes of Moses, this

01:35:11.040 --> 01:35:16.320
practice was condemned and outlawed in

01:35:13.920 --> 01:35:18.900
much of the Levant, and from then on,

01:35:16.320 --> 01:35:20.520
animals were sacrificed in the place of

01:35:18.900 --> 01:35:23.460
human victims.

01:35:20.520 --> 01:35:25.620
In Tyre and other Phoenician cities, the

01:35:23.460 --> 01:35:27.060
practice also seems to have died out in

01:35:25.620 --> 01:35:29.340
the first millennium,

01:35:27.060 --> 01:35:31.920
but there is one place it seems to have

01:35:29.340 --> 01:35:36.620
continued well into the second century

01:35:31.920 --> 01:35:36.620
BC, and that is Carthage.

01:35:36.780 --> 01:35:43.739
These were violent times, when human life

01:35:40.199 --> 01:35:46.139
was cheap, but even so, these rituals were

01:35:43.739 --> 01:35:48.780
mentioned with some revulsion by several

01:35:46.139 --> 01:35:51.300
ancient writers, among them the Greek

01:35:48.780 --> 01:35:54.840
philosopher Plato.

01:35:51.300 --> 01:35:58.679
With us, for instance, human sacrifice is

01:35:54.840 --> 01:36:01.440
not legal but unholy, whereas the

01:35:58.679 --> 01:36:05.159
Carthaginians perform it as a thing they

01:36:01.440 --> 01:36:07.679
account holy and legal, and that too when

01:36:05.159 --> 01:36:09.480
some of them even sacrifice their own

01:36:07.679 --> 01:36:12.420
sons.

01:36:09.480 --> 01:36:15.179
At first, these rituals seem to have been

01:36:12.420 --> 01:36:17.340
an authentic sacrifice, giving up the

01:36:15.179 --> 01:36:20.280
life of one of your own children in the

01:36:17.340 --> 01:36:23.340
hope of receiving favor from the gods,

01:36:20.280 --> 01:36:25.500
but before long, wealthy Carthaginians

01:36:23.340 --> 01:36:27.900
found a way around this.

01:36:25.500 --> 01:36:30.480
In fact, they seem to have developed a

01:36:27.900 --> 01:36:33.540
macabre industry, a trade in other

01:36:30.480 --> 01:36:36.120
people's children for sacrifice.

01:36:33.540 --> 01:36:38.219
The writer Plutarch describes this

01:36:36.120 --> 01:36:42.179
system and gives a sense for the

01:36:38.219 --> 01:36:44.040
atmosphere of these grisly rituals.

01:36:42.179 --> 01:36:45.900
Those who had no children would buy

01:36:44.040 --> 01:36:48.600
little ones from poor people, and

01:36:45.900 --> 01:36:51.000
cut their throats as if they were so

01:36:48.600 --> 01:36:54.120
many lambs or young birds.

01:36:51.000 --> 01:36:55.679
Meanwhile, the mother stood by without a

01:36:54.120 --> 01:36:58.139
tear or moan,

01:36:55.679 --> 01:37:00.420
but should she utter a single moan or

01:36:58.139 --> 01:37:01.860
let fall a single tear, she had to

01:37:00.420 --> 01:37:03.600
forfeit the money,

01:37:01.860 --> 01:37:04.920
and her child was sacrificed

01:37:03.600 --> 01:37:07.620
nevertheless.

01:37:04.920 --> 01:37:10.139
The whole area before the statue was

01:37:07.620 --> 01:37:12.600
filled with a loud noise of flutes and

01:37:10.139 --> 01:37:16.699
drums so that the cries of wailing

01:37:12.600 --> 01:37:16.699
should not reach the ears of the people.

01:37:17.699 --> 01:37:22.800
For a long time, it was assumed that

01:37:20.219 --> 01:37:25.679
these stories were exaggerations, pieces

01:37:22.800 --> 01:37:28.320
of Greek propaganda designed to demonize

01:37:25.679 --> 01:37:30.900
their enemies in Carthage, but more

01:37:28.320 --> 01:37:32.760
modern archaeological discoveries have

01:37:30.900 --> 01:37:35.580
more or less confirmed that child

01:37:32.760 --> 01:37:37.560
sacrifice did take place at least at

01:37:35.580 --> 01:37:38.940
some times, and at least by some people

01:37:37.560 --> 01:37:41.159
in the city.

01:37:38.940 --> 01:37:42.960
Large collections of buried urns

01:37:41.159 --> 01:37:45.780
containing the cremated remains of

01:37:42.960 --> 01:37:49.199
children have been found in large temple

01:37:45.780 --> 01:37:51.900
sites known as tophets. Some of these

01:37:49.199 --> 01:37:54.960
temples are exceedingly large, with

01:37:51.900 --> 01:37:57.120
collections of cremation urns exceeding

01:37:54.960 --> 01:38:00.420
2,000 in number.

01:37:57.120 --> 01:38:03.360
Archeology has uncovered masks and

01:38:00.420 --> 01:38:06.020
symbols at these sites, incense burners,

01:38:03.360 --> 01:38:08.580
and other paraphernalia of ritual,

01:38:06.020 --> 01:38:11.540
suggesting that the ceremonies were

01:38:08.580 --> 01:38:11.540
highly structured.

01:38:12.900 --> 01:38:16.260
It is worth being cautious with these

01:38:15.060 --> 01:38:18.840
findings.

01:38:16.260 --> 01:38:20.639
At most of the sites, analysis has shown

01:38:18.840 --> 01:38:22.980
that the vast majority of these

01:38:20.639 --> 01:38:25.500
children's remains are of stillborn

01:38:22.980 --> 01:38:27.179
babies or babies that had died of

01:38:25.500 --> 01:38:29.820
natural causes.

01:38:27.179 --> 01:38:32.880
At a time when child mortality has been

01:38:29.820 --> 01:38:35.040
estimated at around 30 to 40 percent, the

01:38:32.880 --> 01:38:37.380
Carthaginians may have considered the

01:38:35.040 --> 01:38:38.940
tragedy of infant death to be a kind of

01:38:37.380 --> 01:38:41.520
sacred sign,

01:38:38.940 --> 01:38:43.800
a human life being taken back by the

01:38:41.520 --> 01:38:47.340
gods, and the bodies of these children

01:38:43.800 --> 01:38:49.560
were burned in the tophets as a result.

01:38:47.340 --> 01:38:51.659
The relative lack of children's remains

01:38:49.560 --> 01:38:54.900
in the regular graveyards of the city

01:38:51.659 --> 01:38:57.420
seem to show that these tophets were at

01:38:54.900 --> 01:38:59.100
least in part cremation sites for the

01:38:57.420 --> 01:39:00.420
remains of children who had died of

01:38:59.100 --> 01:39:03.300
other causes,

01:39:00.420 --> 01:39:06.239
but analysis of the ages of other

01:39:03.300 --> 01:39:09.060
remains at other times don't seem to fit

01:39:06.239 --> 01:39:12.239
with patterns of child mortality.

01:39:09.060 --> 01:39:14.100
However the ritual had begun, at least in

01:39:12.239 --> 01:39:16.560
the later years of the city, it had

01:39:14.100 --> 01:39:17.880
evolved into something much darker and

01:39:16.560 --> 01:39:20.280
crueler.

01:39:17.880 --> 01:39:23.040
The inscriptions at these later sites of

01:39:20.280 --> 01:39:25.199
sacrifice left over the cremation urns

01:39:23.040 --> 01:39:28.020
don't seem to leave much room for

01:39:25.199 --> 01:39:30.239
interpretation, as this typical example

01:39:28.020 --> 01:39:34.080
shows.

01:39:30.239 --> 01:39:37.320
To Lady Tinnit, face of Baal and Lord Baal

01:39:34.080 --> 01:39:40.199
Hammon; the thing that Arish, son of

01:39:37.320 --> 01:39:43.800
Bodashtart, son of Baalshillem, maker of

01:39:40.199 --> 01:39:46.260
strigils, vowed, because the Lord heard

01:39:43.800 --> 01:39:47.940
his voice.

01:39:46.260 --> 01:39:50.340
There are countless of these

01:39:47.940 --> 01:39:53.040
inscriptions, and they all follow this

01:39:50.340 --> 01:39:56.219
pattern. The child was not offered up

01:39:53.040 --> 01:39:59.340
front, but was promised in advance if the

01:39:56.219 --> 01:40:01.620
gods came through on their request. The

01:39:59.340 --> 01:40:04.560
Greek historian Cleitarchus seems to

01:40:01.620 --> 01:40:06.600
confirm this order of events.

01:40:04.560 --> 01:40:08.639
The Phoenicians, and above all, the

01:40:06.600 --> 01:40:11.400
Carthaginians, whenever they were eager

01:40:08.639 --> 01:40:13.500
for a great thing to succeed, made a vow

01:40:11.400 --> 01:40:15.900
by one of their children.

01:40:13.500 --> 01:40:18.659
If they would receive the desired things,

01:40:15.900 --> 01:40:21.420
they would sacrifice to the gods.

01:40:18.659 --> 01:40:24.239
A bronze Kronos, having been erected by

01:40:21.420 --> 01:40:27.239
them, stretched out upward hands over a

01:40:24.239 --> 01:40:29.159
bronze oven to burn the child. The flame

01:40:27.239 --> 01:40:32.280
of the burning child reached its body

01:40:29.159 --> 01:40:33.900
until, the limbs having shriveled up and

01:40:32.280 --> 01:40:35.040
smiling mouth appeared to be almost

01:40:33.900 --> 01:40:38.520
laughing,

01:40:35.040 --> 01:40:40.860
it would slip into the oven.

01:40:38.520 --> 01:40:43.260
We can't imagine the kinds of things

01:40:40.860 --> 01:40:45.480
people might have asked for in exchange

01:40:43.260 --> 01:40:47.880
for these sacrifices.

01:40:45.480 --> 01:40:49.679
Perhaps in some instances, we can imagine

01:40:47.880 --> 01:40:52.860
the ritual was performed out of

01:40:49.679 --> 01:40:55.199
desperation, an extreme measure.

01:40:52.860 --> 01:40:57.719
Other times, perhaps the wishes were

01:40:55.199 --> 01:41:00.480
trivial; good weather on a journey, maybe,

01:40:57.719 --> 01:41:04.560
good fortune and wealth in the year to

01:41:00.480 --> 01:41:07.080
come, or the downfall of a business rival.

01:41:04.560 --> 01:41:09.780
Whatever their wish was, it seems that if

01:41:07.080 --> 01:41:12.120
it went on to come true, the child's fate

01:41:09.780 --> 01:41:14.159
would be sealed.

01:41:12.120 --> 01:41:16.260
With only fragmentary secondhand

01:41:14.159 --> 01:41:18.719
accounts and the little that can be

01:41:16.260 --> 01:41:20.460
gleaned from archaeological sites, we're

01:41:18.719 --> 01:41:23.639
left guessing about the questions that

01:41:20.460 --> 01:41:26.760
desperately need answers; how widespread

01:41:23.639 --> 01:41:29.940
this practice was in society, why and

01:41:26.760 --> 01:41:32.639
when people engaged in it, and how the

01:41:29.940 --> 01:41:35.000
majority of Carthaginian citizens felt

01:41:32.639 --> 01:41:35.000
about it.

01:41:40.080 --> 01:41:45.960
With the army of Agathocles drawing near

01:41:43.080 --> 01:41:49.080
and the last citizen defenders defeated

01:41:45.960 --> 01:41:51.300
in the field, the Carthaginians began to

01:41:49.080 --> 01:41:54.000
believe that their gods must be angry

01:41:51.300 --> 01:41:55.800
with them, and at least some people in

01:41:54.000 --> 01:41:58.619
the city believed that it was this

01:41:55.800 --> 01:42:00.780
practice of sacrificing the children of

01:41:58.619 --> 01:42:05.820
the poor instead of their own that was

01:42:00.780 --> 01:42:08.639
to blame, as Diodorus of Sicily recounts.

01:42:05.820 --> 01:42:11.280
They also alleged that Kronos had turned

01:42:08.639 --> 01:42:13.380
against them, as in former times they had

01:42:11.280 --> 01:42:16.139
been accustomed to sacrifice to this god

01:42:13.380 --> 01:42:19.020
the noblest of their sons, but more

01:42:16.139 --> 01:42:21.060
recently, secretly buying and nurturing

01:42:19.020 --> 01:42:23.880
children, they had sent these to the

01:42:21.060 --> 01:42:26.340
sacrifice. When they had given thought to

01:42:23.880 --> 01:42:28.679
these things and saw their enemy encamped

01:42:26.340 --> 01:42:31.139
before their walls, they were filled with

01:42:28.679 --> 01:42:32.820
superstitious dread, for they believed

01:42:31.139 --> 01:42:34.619
that they had neglected the honors of

01:42:32.820 --> 01:42:37.380
the gods that had been established by

01:42:34.619 --> 01:42:39.960
their fathers. In their zeal to make

01:42:37.380 --> 01:42:42.719
amends for their omission, they selected

01:42:39.960 --> 01:42:45.300
200 of the noblest children and

01:42:42.719 --> 01:42:46.980
sacrificed them publicly, and others who

01:42:45.300 --> 01:42:49.679
were under suspicion sacrificed

01:42:46.980 --> 01:42:51.780
themselves voluntarily, in number not

01:42:49.679 --> 01:42:54.719
less than 300.

01:42:51.780 --> 01:42:57.540
In this time of peril, the citizens of

01:42:54.719 --> 01:43:00.360
Carthage reverted to a kind of suicidal

01:42:57.540 --> 01:43:02.580
religious fundamentalism, but this would

01:43:00.360 --> 01:43:05.100
not be the end of the city.

01:43:02.580 --> 01:43:07.380
Agathocles rampaged around the

01:43:05.100 --> 01:43:09.840
countryside of Carthage for years,

01:43:07.380 --> 01:43:12.960
but the city's formidable triple wall

01:43:09.840 --> 01:43:16.080
defenses would keep him at bay, and soon

01:43:12.960 --> 01:43:18.600
the Greek king ran out of steam.

01:43:16.080 --> 01:43:21.000
In his absence, some of his Sicilian

01:43:18.600 --> 01:43:22.860
vassals were taking the opportunity to

01:43:21.000 --> 01:43:25.139
declare independence.

01:43:22.860 --> 01:43:27.780
He hurried back home, leaving his

01:43:25.139 --> 01:43:30.300
inexperienced son in charge of his army,

01:43:27.780 --> 01:43:32.460
who was easily outmaneuvered by

01:43:30.300 --> 01:43:34.980
Carthaginian generals.

01:43:32.460 --> 01:43:37.739
By the time Agathocles returned to

01:43:34.980 --> 01:43:40.619
Africa, he saw that the situation had

01:43:37.739 --> 01:43:43.260
become untenable, and he fled back home

01:43:40.619 --> 01:43:45.179
to Sicily.

01:43:43.260 --> 01:43:47.760
But his achievements had been

01:43:45.179 --> 01:43:49.940
significant; he had left a lasting

01:43:47.760 --> 01:43:52.280
impression on the people of Carthage,

01:43:49.940 --> 01:43:55.080
laid waste to their countryside,

01:43:52.280 --> 01:43:57.119
terrified them so deeply that they had

01:43:55.080 --> 01:43:59.159
slaughtered their own children, and

01:43:57.119 --> 01:44:01.199
likely left them on the brink of

01:43:59.159 --> 01:44:05.100
bankruptcy.

01:44:01.199 --> 01:44:07.800
A peace treaty in 307 BC essentially

01:44:05.100 --> 01:44:11.100
returned the situation to exactly how it

01:44:07.800 --> 01:44:14.159
had been before the war started.

01:44:11.100 --> 01:44:16.560
The example of Agathocles, of a daring

01:44:14.159 --> 01:44:19.020
strike at the heart of your enemy right

01:44:16.560 --> 01:44:21.060
at the moment they least expect it, was

01:44:19.020 --> 01:44:24.300
an example that later Carthaginian

01:44:21.060 --> 01:44:26.639
generals would remember and learn from.

01:44:24.300 --> 01:44:28.619
But it was also an episode that

01:44:26.639 --> 01:44:31.380
other powers in the region paid

01:44:28.619 --> 01:44:33.900
particular attention to.

01:44:31.380 --> 01:44:36.780
Carthage had once been considered the

01:44:33.900 --> 01:44:39.360
region's major power, but a small Greek

01:44:36.780 --> 01:44:41.940
army had come within a hair's breadth of

01:44:39.360 --> 01:44:45.480
bringing it to its knees.

01:44:41.940 --> 01:44:48.840
The historian Plutarch puts it bluntly in

01:44:45.480 --> 01:44:51.300
the mouth of one of his characters.

01:44:48.840 --> 01:44:54.239
For who could keep his hands off Libya

01:44:51.300 --> 01:44:56.820
or Carthage, when that city got within

01:44:54.239 --> 01:44:59.639
his reach, a city which Agathocles,

01:44:56.820 --> 01:45:01.760
slipping stealthily out of Syracuse and

01:44:59.639 --> 01:45:05.480
crossing the sea with only a few ships,

01:45:01.760 --> 01:45:05.480
narrowly missed taking?

01:45:05.820 --> 01:45:10.800
The first who would seek to take

01:45:07.800 --> 01:45:15.440
advantage of this perceived weakness was

01:45:10.800 --> 01:45:15.440
a Greek king named Pyrrhus.

01:45:18.300 --> 01:45:24.300
Pyrrhus was the king of the Greek kingdom

01:45:21.420 --> 01:45:25.800
of Epiros, around what is today Southern

01:45:24.300 --> 01:45:29.159
Albania.

01:45:25.800 --> 01:45:31.440
His name meant fiery or red-haired,

01:45:29.159 --> 01:45:33.119
coming from the same root as the English

01:45:31.440 --> 01:45:36.060
word pyre,

01:45:33.119 --> 01:45:37.980
and Plutarch recalls that he seems to

01:45:36.060 --> 01:45:40.500
have suffered from some kind of

01:45:37.980 --> 01:45:42.960
developmental disorder that fused

01:45:40.500 --> 01:45:46.080
together the teeth of his upper jaw,

01:45:42.960 --> 01:45:49.199
giving him an unsettling look.

01:45:46.080 --> 01:45:51.239
In the aspect of his countenance, Pyrrhus

01:45:49.199 --> 01:45:53.100
had more of the terror than of the

01:45:51.239 --> 01:45:55.860
majesty of kingly power.

01:45:53.100 --> 01:45:58.739
He had not many teeth, but his upper jaw

01:45:55.860 --> 01:46:00.780
was one continuous bone on which the

01:45:58.739 --> 01:46:04.440
usual intervals between the teeth were

01:46:00.780 --> 01:46:07.320
indicated by slight depressions.

01:46:04.440 --> 01:46:09.960
But just like Agathocles, Pyrrhus had an

01:46:07.320 --> 01:46:12.659
immensely high opinion of himself and

01:46:09.960 --> 01:46:15.179
fancied himself as the inheritor of the

01:46:12.659 --> 01:46:18.480
legacy of Alexander.

01:46:15.179 --> 01:46:21.300
In his later life, he styled himself as a

01:46:18.480 --> 01:46:24.060
hero of the Hellenic world, the defender

01:46:21.300 --> 01:46:26.219
of everything Greek, and right at that

01:46:24.060 --> 01:46:28.800
moment, the Greeks who needed the most

01:46:26.219 --> 01:46:31.739
defending were the beleaguered colonies

01:46:28.800 --> 01:46:36.679
in southern Italy, the region known as

01:46:31.739 --> 01:46:36.679
Megale Hellas or Greater Greece.

01:46:38.100 --> 01:46:44.100
These city-states were suddenly being

01:46:40.980 --> 01:46:47.340
menaced by a powerful new force in the

01:46:44.100 --> 01:46:49.980
region, a people from the river plains of

01:46:47.340 --> 01:46:53.159
central Italy that the Greeks considered

01:46:49.980 --> 01:46:55.739
to be barbarians, and that had recently

01:46:53.159 --> 01:46:56.940
emerged as something of a regional

01:46:55.739 --> 01:46:59.580
superpower.

01:46:56.940 --> 01:47:02.639
This was the once small and

01:46:59.580 --> 01:47:05.060
insignificant city-state republic of

01:47:02.639 --> 01:47:05.060
Rome.

01:47:07.560 --> 01:47:13.260
Throughout the 4th century BC, this

01:47:10.560 --> 01:47:15.600
bizarre republic had begun expanding

01:47:13.260 --> 01:47:17.820
into the hinterlands of its region of

01:47:15.600 --> 01:47:20.520
Latium, and brought a number of other

01:47:17.820 --> 01:47:22.980
cities under its control.

01:47:20.520 --> 01:47:25.380
From there, they had managed to upset the

01:47:22.980 --> 01:47:27.659
power balance of central Italy, and

01:47:25.380 --> 01:47:31.020
toppled a number of well-established

01:47:27.659 --> 01:47:33.239
rivals, absorbing all of Latium and the

01:47:31.020 --> 01:47:36.300
region of Campania.

01:47:33.239 --> 01:47:38.699
Wherever they went, the Romans took a

01:47:36.300 --> 01:47:41.219
remarkably clever and pragmatic approach

01:47:38.699 --> 01:47:42.780
to absorbing other peoples into their

01:47:41.219 --> 01:47:45.960
society.

01:47:42.780 --> 01:47:48.360
While empires like Carthage kept full

01:47:45.960 --> 01:47:51.239
citizenship only for the people living

01:47:48.360 --> 01:47:53.400
in their home city, Rome was far more

01:47:51.239 --> 01:47:56.219
generous with citizenship.

01:47:53.400 --> 01:47:58.679
Unlike the armies of Carthage, Rome's

01:47:56.219 --> 01:48:01.920
legions were made up of citizen soldiers,

01:47:58.679 --> 01:48:04.500
and with every free man now a citizen,

01:48:01.920 --> 01:48:07.400
they were able to draw on vast reserves

01:48:04.500 --> 01:48:07.400
of manpower.

01:48:07.440 --> 01:48:12.420
As Rome grew in size and influence,

01:48:09.980 --> 01:48:15.960
Carthage took notice.

01:48:12.420 --> 01:48:18.119
About 160 years after the first treaty

01:48:15.960 --> 01:48:21.000
they had signed, they penned a new

01:48:18.119 --> 01:48:23.940
expanded agreement with Rome.

01:48:21.000 --> 01:48:26.159
This new treaty added the condition that

01:48:23.940 --> 01:48:29.100
Rome would not try to found any cities

01:48:26.159 --> 01:48:32.040
in Carthaginian territory, suggesting

01:48:29.100 --> 01:48:34.860
that Roman expansion had become at least

01:48:32.040 --> 01:48:36.179
a small concern for the region's major

01:48:34.860 --> 01:48:38.880
power.

01:48:36.179 --> 01:48:41.520
But for the most part, relations between

01:48:38.880 --> 01:48:42.960
Rome and Carthage were friendly, if

01:48:41.520 --> 01:48:46.260
suspicious.

01:48:42.960 --> 01:48:48.119
Carthage welcomed the rise of Rome as a

01:48:46.260 --> 01:48:51.420
potential ally against their mutual

01:48:48.119 --> 01:48:54.360
enemies, the Greeks, and one district of

01:48:51.420 --> 01:48:57.719
the city of Rome was known as the Vicus

01:48:54.360 --> 01:48:59.760
Africus, or African quarter, suggesting

01:48:57.719 --> 01:49:02.219
that a population of Carthaginian

01:48:59.760 --> 01:49:03.600
merchants already lived and traded in

01:49:02.219 --> 01:49:06.780
the city.

01:49:03.600 --> 01:49:09.719
It seems Carthage viewed Rome not as an

01:49:06.780 --> 01:49:12.540
unwelcome rival, but as a new potential

01:49:09.719 --> 01:49:14.520
source of customers.

01:49:12.540 --> 01:49:20.060
But for the Greek colonies of southern

01:49:14.520 --> 01:49:20.060
Italy, Rome was a voracious new predator.

01:49:25.199 --> 01:49:31.199
As Roman power expanded, the Greeks found

01:49:28.560 --> 01:49:34.199
themselves surrounded, and many of them

01:49:31.199 --> 01:49:38.040
began sending out letters of distress to

01:49:34.199 --> 01:49:40.619
the fiery Greek king Pyrrhus.

01:49:38.040 --> 01:49:44.460
One of these colonies was the city of

01:49:40.619 --> 01:49:46.080
Tarentum, as Plutarch recalls.

01:49:44.460 --> 01:49:48.719
The Romans were at war with the people

01:49:46.080 --> 01:49:51.119
of Tarentum, who, being able neither to

01:49:48.719 --> 01:49:53.699
carry on the war nor put an end to it,

01:49:51.119 --> 01:49:56.460
wish to make Pyrrhus their leader and

01:49:53.699 --> 01:50:00.900
summon him to the war, believing him to

01:49:56.460 --> 01:50:03.420
be a most formidable general.

01:50:00.900 --> 01:50:06.179
Pyrrhus couldn't resist this opportunity

01:50:03.420 --> 01:50:08.940
to position himself as the valiant

01:50:06.179 --> 01:50:11.460
defender of Greek civilization against

01:50:08.940 --> 01:50:14.580
these Latin barbarians.

01:50:11.460 --> 01:50:17.460
He gathered an armada and a large army

01:50:14.580 --> 01:50:20.580
complete with 20 war elephants, and in

01:50:17.460 --> 01:50:23.699
the year 280 BC, he sailed to southern

01:50:20.580 --> 01:50:26.699
Italy in full force.

01:50:23.699 --> 01:50:29.520
Himself a sophisticated Greek, Pyrrhus

01:50:26.699 --> 01:50:32.460
expected to meet an unruly barbarian

01:50:29.520 --> 01:50:34.920
horde on the battlefield, but Roman

01:50:32.460 --> 01:50:38.219
troops were by now toughened from their

01:50:34.920 --> 01:50:40.080
long wars of expansion in Italy, and they

01:50:38.219 --> 01:50:42.420
were already exhibiting the kind of

01:50:40.080 --> 01:50:44.400
organization that would one day make

01:50:42.420 --> 01:50:46.139
them famous.

01:50:44.400 --> 01:50:47.880
When he learned that the Romans were

01:50:46.139 --> 01:50:50.159
near and lay encamped on the further

01:50:47.880 --> 01:50:52.619
side of the river Siris, he rode up to

01:50:50.159 --> 01:50:54.540
the river to get a view of them; and when

01:50:52.619 --> 01:50:56.760
he observed their discipline, the

01:50:54.540 --> 01:50:59.040
appointment of their watches, their order,

01:50:56.760 --> 01:51:01.920
and the general arrangement of their

01:50:59.040 --> 01:51:03.480
camp, he was amazed, and said to the

01:51:01.920 --> 01:51:05.760
friend that was nearest him,

01:51:03.480 --> 01:51:08.880
ëThe discipline of these barbarians is

01:51:05.760 --> 01:51:11.820
not barbarous.í

01:51:08.880 --> 01:51:14.820
But these early Roman legions were still

01:51:11.820 --> 01:51:17.219
no match for Greek phalanxes, and the

01:51:14.820 --> 01:51:20.480
site of Pyrrhus' elephants terrified

01:51:17.219 --> 01:51:20.480
the Roman horses.

01:51:20.580 --> 01:51:26.880
Pyrrhus defeated the Romans in two battles,

01:51:23.520 --> 01:51:30.840
at Heraclea and at Ausculum, in the year

01:51:26.880 --> 01:51:33.780
279 BC, and he believed that Rome must

01:51:30.840 --> 01:51:36.420
soon concede the war and agree to the

01:51:33.780 --> 01:51:39.060
terms of his demands.

01:51:36.420 --> 01:51:43.199
But slightly to the bemusement of Pyrrhus,

01:51:39.060 --> 01:51:46.800
Rome simply refused to admit defeat.

01:51:43.199 --> 01:51:50.280
This refusal to ever sue for peace would

01:51:46.800 --> 01:51:52.800
become something of a Roman hallmark.

01:51:50.280 --> 01:51:54.960
Some have argued that Rome's very nature

01:51:52.800 --> 01:51:57.600
as a citizen democracy actually

01:51:54.960 --> 01:51:59.520
contributed to their immense doggedness

01:51:57.600 --> 01:52:01.920
in warfare.

01:51:59.520 --> 01:52:03.780
Their leaders were politicians and

01:52:01.920 --> 01:52:05.699
existed in a state of constant

01:52:03.780 --> 01:52:08.159
competition with each other for the

01:52:05.699 --> 01:52:10.679
support of the voting public.

01:52:08.159 --> 01:52:13.440
Any politician who signed a damaging

01:52:10.679 --> 01:52:16.440
peace treaty could be eviscerated in the

01:52:13.440 --> 01:52:19.260
senate as a coward, a fool, or even a

01:52:16.440 --> 01:52:21.900
traitor. This meant that Roman senators

01:52:19.260 --> 01:52:25.320
would often overwhelmingly vote to

01:52:21.900 --> 01:52:28.080
continue a war rather than admit defeat.

01:52:25.320 --> 01:52:31.139
This will to continue, along with their

01:52:28.080 --> 01:52:33.060
large reserves of citizen manpower, meant

01:52:31.139 --> 01:52:36.360
that Rome could often absorb terrific

01:52:33.060 --> 01:52:37.920
defeats, losing whole armies, and simply

01:52:36.360 --> 01:52:40.139
keep going.

01:52:37.920 --> 01:52:42.900
This often had the effect of simply

01:52:40.139 --> 01:52:44.639
grinding down their enemiesí will to

01:52:42.900 --> 01:52:47.400
fight.

01:52:44.639 --> 01:52:49.560
According to Plutarch, who was fond of

01:52:47.400 --> 01:52:52.440
inventing dialogue for his historical

01:52:49.560 --> 01:52:56.580
characters, Pyrrhus made the following quip

01:52:52.440 --> 01:52:59.760
after his third victory with Rome.

01:52:56.580 --> 01:53:02.820
We are told that Pyrrhus said to one who

01:52:59.760 --> 01:53:04.800
was congratulating him on his victory, ëIf

01:53:02.820 --> 01:53:07.080
we are victorious in one more battle

01:53:04.800 --> 01:53:10.080
with the Romans, we shall be utterly

01:53:07.080 --> 01:53:12.960
ruined!í For he had lost great part of the

01:53:10.080 --> 01:53:15.719
forces with which he came, and all his

01:53:12.960 --> 01:53:18.600
friends and generals except a few;

01:53:15.719 --> 01:53:21.659
he had no others who we could summon

01:53:18.600 --> 01:53:24.360
from home, and he saw that his allies in

01:53:21.659 --> 01:53:27.060
Italy were becoming indifferent, while

01:53:24.360 --> 01:53:29.760
the army of the Romans, as if from a

01:53:27.060 --> 01:53:33.860
fountain gushing forth indoors, was

01:53:29.760 --> 01:53:37.080
easily and speedily filled up again.

01:53:33.860 --> 01:53:39.780
After this series of Pyrrhic victories,

01:53:37.080 --> 01:53:42.780
Pyrrhus soon realized the conquest of

01:53:39.780 --> 01:53:46.080
Italy would elude him. He came within

01:53:42.780 --> 01:53:48.239
miles of Rome, but the tall Servian walls

01:53:46.080 --> 01:53:51.600
of the city meant that his beleaguered

01:53:48.239 --> 01:53:54.300
force had no hope of capturing it.

01:53:51.600 --> 01:53:58.139
Still, he couldn't bear the thought of

01:53:54.300 --> 01:53:58.139
returning home empty-handed.

01:53:58.560 --> 01:54:03.300
Pyrrhus decided that he would head to

01:54:00.600 --> 01:54:06.060
Sicily and see if he could have any more

01:54:03.300 --> 01:54:08.880
success helping the Greek colonies there

01:54:06.060 --> 01:54:11.460
fight against the Carthaginians.

01:54:08.880 --> 01:54:15.119
He arrived in the Greek town of Syracuse

01:54:11.460 --> 01:54:18.119
to a hero's welcome. Every Greek colony

01:54:15.119 --> 01:54:20.340
on the island sent troops to fill his

01:54:18.119 --> 01:54:23.100
army, and Pyrrhus would find the

01:54:20.340 --> 01:54:25.560
Carthaginian forces on Sicily to be a

01:54:23.100 --> 01:54:26.460
much softer target than the legions of

01:54:25.560 --> 01:54:28.920
Rome.

01:54:26.460 --> 01:54:31.139
The Carthaginian response to Pyrrhus

01:54:28.920 --> 01:54:32.280
couldn't have been more different to the

01:54:31.139 --> 01:54:34.500
Romans.

01:54:32.280 --> 01:54:37.320
With little desire to be dragged back

01:54:34.500 --> 01:54:39.480
into another war in Sicily, they offered

01:54:37.320 --> 01:54:43.619
to pay him off generously to leave them

01:54:39.480 --> 01:54:45.420
alone, but Pyrrhus refused, as Plutarch

01:54:43.619 --> 01:54:48.179
describes.

01:54:45.420 --> 01:54:50.820
When the Carthaginians were inclined to

01:54:48.179 --> 01:54:53.639
come to terms and were willing to pay

01:54:50.820 --> 01:54:56.280
him money and send him ships, he replied

01:54:53.639 --> 01:54:58.500
to them -- his heart being set on greater

01:54:56.280 --> 01:55:01.560
things -- that there could be no settlement

01:54:58.500 --> 01:55:05.880
or friendship between himself and them

01:55:01.560 --> 01:55:09.960
unless they abandoned all Sicily.

01:55:05.880 --> 01:55:13.020
But Sicily, too, eventually defeated him.

01:55:09.960 --> 01:55:15.780
After years of war, his men were tired.

01:55:13.020 --> 01:55:17.219
The Carthaginians and Romans were now

01:55:15.780 --> 01:55:19.739
working together,

01:55:17.219 --> 01:55:22.800
so he faced the powerful armies of Rome

01:55:19.739 --> 01:55:24.300
on land and the vast navy of Carthage by

01:55:22.800 --> 01:55:26.699
sea.

01:55:24.300 --> 01:55:29.639
After finally meeting with defeat in

01:55:26.699 --> 01:55:32.100
southern Italy, he cut his losses and

01:55:29.639 --> 01:55:34.619
sailed for home with little to show for

01:55:32.100 --> 01:55:37.199
his years of war.

01:55:34.619 --> 01:55:40.560
As he sailed away, Plutarch imagines

01:55:37.199 --> 01:55:42.600
Pyrrhus reflecting on the situation he has

01:55:40.560 --> 01:55:45.780
left behind.

01:55:42.600 --> 01:55:49.199
He could not master Sicily, which was

01:55:45.780 --> 01:55:52.260
like a storm-tossed ship, but desired to

01:55:49.199 --> 01:55:55.380
leave her, and it is said that at the

01:55:52.260 --> 01:55:57.179
time of his departure, Pyrrhus looked back

01:55:55.380 --> 01:56:00.420
at the island and said to those about

01:55:57.179 --> 01:56:02.940
him, ëMy friend, what a wrestling ground

01:56:00.420 --> 01:56:05.960
for Carthaginians and Romans we are

01:56:02.940 --> 01:56:05.960
leaving behind us.í

01:56:07.580 --> 01:56:15.060
Pyrrhus' campaign had ended in failure.

01:56:11.760 --> 01:56:17.400
With him gone, Rome quickly swept over

01:56:15.060 --> 01:56:20.219
the remaining Greek city-states of Italy,

01:56:17.400 --> 01:56:21.840
and solidified its hold on the south of

01:56:20.219 --> 01:56:24.840
their peninsula.

01:56:21.840 --> 01:56:26.880
The Romans built roads connecting these

01:56:24.840 --> 01:56:29.340
wealthy Greek cities to the Roman

01:56:26.880 --> 01:56:31.860
network, and used the treasure they

01:56:29.340 --> 01:56:34.619
seized to build a grand series of new

01:56:31.860 --> 01:56:37.500
temples in the capital, as well as an

01:56:34.619 --> 01:56:40.139
enormous second aqueduct for Rome, the

01:56:37.500 --> 01:56:43.199
Aqua Anio Vetus.

01:56:40.139 --> 01:56:46.440
Meanwhile, Carthage reclaimed many of the

01:56:43.199 --> 01:56:49.020
cities that Pyrrhus had taken in Sicily,

01:56:46.440 --> 01:56:51.420
but without a common enemy, the twin

01:56:49.020 --> 01:56:53.820
powers of Carthage and Rome were now

01:56:51.420 --> 01:56:57.600
butting up against each other.

01:56:53.820 --> 01:57:00.480
By the year 270 BC, Rome had captured the

01:56:57.600 --> 01:57:02.219
city of Rhegium, right across the Straits

01:57:00.480 --> 01:57:04.679
of Messina.

01:57:02.219 --> 01:57:08.400
They could now look over the water and

01:57:04.679 --> 01:57:10.739
gazed directly at the coast of Sicily.

01:57:08.400 --> 01:57:13.679
The wrestling ground that Pyrrhus had left

01:57:10.739 --> 01:57:15.599
behind in Sicily would set the stage for

01:57:13.679 --> 01:57:17.280
the next dramatic period of

01:57:15.599 --> 01:57:19.980
Mediterranean history.

01:57:17.280 --> 01:57:22.679
It was a stage that would see a conflict

01:57:19.980 --> 01:57:25.800
unfold that would dwarf the Sicilian

01:57:22.679 --> 01:57:27.900
wars for intensity and scale, that would

01:57:25.800 --> 01:57:29.880
last for a hundred years, that would

01:57:27.900 --> 01:57:33.060
bring both powers to the brink of

01:57:29.880 --> 01:57:34.679
bankruptcy, and cost more than a million

01:57:33.060 --> 01:57:39.980
lives.

01:57:34.679 --> 01:57:39.980
This was the beginning of the Punic Wars.

01:57:57.119 --> 01:58:03.659
The word Punic comes from Latin and is a

01:58:01.080 --> 01:58:06.480
mutation of the Greek word Phoenike or

01:58:03.659 --> 01:58:09.119
Phoenician, and at this time, the Romans

01:58:06.480 --> 01:58:11.699
had come to use it to describe the

01:58:09.119 --> 01:58:14.460
Phoenician superpower of Carthage that

01:58:11.699 --> 01:58:18.540
sat facing them only three daysí voyage

01:58:14.460 --> 01:58:21.900
away on the other side of the sea.

01:58:18.540 --> 01:58:24.780
The historian Cassius Dio summarizes the

01:58:21.900 --> 01:58:28.260
situation, as both the powers of Rome and

01:58:24.780 --> 01:58:30.360
Carthage slid towards war.

01:58:28.260 --> 01:58:32.520
The Carthaginians, who had long been

01:58:30.360 --> 01:58:34.980
powerful, and the Romans, who are now

01:58:32.520 --> 01:58:37.260
growing more rapidly stronger, kept

01:58:34.980 --> 01:58:39.599
viewing each other with jealousy.

01:58:37.260 --> 01:58:42.719
They were led into war partly by the

01:58:39.599 --> 01:58:46.020
desire of continually acquiring more, and

01:58:42.719 --> 01:58:48.719
partly also by fear.

01:58:46.020 --> 01:58:52.520
It was a chance incident that broke

01:58:48.719 --> 01:58:52.520
their truce and plunged them into war.

01:58:53.460 --> 01:58:58.860
The main source for almost every aspect

01:58:55.980 --> 01:59:02.280
of the First Punic War is the historian

01:58:58.860 --> 01:59:05.880
Polybius, a Greek who was sent to Rome in

01:59:02.280 --> 01:59:08.520
167 BC as a hostage.

01:59:05.880 --> 01:59:11.340
Polybius was writing about the events of

01:59:08.520 --> 01:59:14.040
the First Punic War a century after they

01:59:11.340 --> 01:59:16.920
took place, but he was meticulous in his

01:59:14.040 --> 01:59:19.020
research and traveled widely, gathering

01:59:16.920 --> 01:59:22.260
as much first-hand knowledge and

01:59:19.020 --> 01:59:24.719
archival material as he could, and as a

01:59:22.260 --> 01:59:27.239
Greek, he was something of an outsider in

01:59:24.719 --> 01:59:29.340
Rome, meaning that his portrayal of the

01:59:27.239 --> 01:59:31.320
war is considered to be relatively

01:59:29.340 --> 01:59:34.560
even-handed.

01:59:31.320 --> 01:59:37.440
The story that Polybius tells begins in

01:59:34.560 --> 01:59:39.599
the volcanic island of Sicily, where,

01:59:37.440 --> 01:59:43.679
around the beginning of the 3rd century

01:59:39.599 --> 01:59:46.159
BC, trouble was once again threatening to

01:59:43.679 --> 01:59:46.159
erupt.

01:59:48.860 --> 01:59:54.360
At this time, Sicily had something of the

01:59:52.619 --> 01:59:57.599
Wild West about it.

01:59:54.360 --> 02:00:00.000
Large parts of it were lawless and fell

01:59:57.599 --> 02:00:01.440
between the influences of Carthage and

02:00:00.000 --> 02:00:03.960
the Greeks.

02:00:01.440 --> 02:00:05.099
Both sides often used mercenaries to

02:00:03.960 --> 02:00:07.320
fight for them,

02:00:05.099 --> 02:00:10.080
but when a particular war was finished,

02:00:07.320 --> 02:00:13.500
it wasn't always so easy to get rid of

02:00:10.080 --> 02:00:16.260
these bands of rough and violent men.

02:00:13.500 --> 02:00:18.420
One such band were a group of mostly

02:00:16.260 --> 02:00:21.960
southern Italians who called themselves

02:00:18.420 --> 02:00:24.000
the Mamertines, or the Sons of Mars, the

02:00:21.960 --> 02:00:26.400
Roman god of war.

02:00:24.000 --> 02:00:28.920
In the past, they had been hired by

02:00:26.400 --> 02:00:31.980
Agathocles to fight Carthage in

02:00:28.920 --> 02:00:34.800
Sicily, but when the tyrant of Syracuse

02:00:31.980 --> 02:00:36.179
had died, they found themselves out of

02:00:34.800 --> 02:00:38.639
work.

02:00:36.179 --> 02:00:41.699
The Mamertines wandered the island for

02:00:38.639 --> 02:00:44.340
some time, likely engaging in theft and

02:00:41.699 --> 02:00:47.639
petty banditry to survive, until they

02:00:44.340 --> 02:00:50.460
reached the walled Greek town of Messina.

02:00:47.639 --> 02:00:52.800
Messina was a small settlement on the

02:00:50.460 --> 02:00:55.199
northeastern tip of Sicily, with the

02:00:52.800 --> 02:00:58.560
shadow of Mount Etna looming over the

02:00:55.199 --> 02:01:01.560
horizon, and its location was of great

02:00:58.560 --> 02:01:04.320
strategic importance. That's because

02:01:01.560 --> 02:01:07.980
Messina was one side of the narrowest

02:01:04.320 --> 02:01:10.199
crossing point between Sicily and Italy.

02:01:07.980 --> 02:01:13.320
Standing on the shore there, you can see

02:01:10.199 --> 02:01:15.599
the Italian mainland just over the water,

02:01:13.320 --> 02:01:17.099
and a ship could make the crossing in

02:01:15.599 --> 02:01:20.099
under thirty minutes.

02:01:17.099 --> 02:01:22.739
Anyone who controlled Messina would also

02:01:20.099 --> 02:01:25.739
control this crossing, and this meant

02:01:22.739 --> 02:01:29.300
that both Carthage and Rome were anxious

02:01:25.739 --> 02:01:29.300
about the city's future.

02:01:30.239 --> 02:01:35.520
When the band of Mamertines arrived in

02:01:33.000 --> 02:01:37.679
Messina, they must have made quite a

02:01:35.520 --> 02:01:40.440
sorry sight, and the people of the city

02:01:37.679 --> 02:01:42.780
originally took pity on them. They took

02:01:40.440 --> 02:01:44.040
them in and even gave them shelter in

02:01:42.780 --> 02:01:47.040
their own homes,

02:01:44.040 --> 02:01:49.860
but soon these hired swords became

02:01:47.040 --> 02:01:51.540
restless and jealous of the people's

02:01:49.860 --> 02:01:54.659
comfortable lives.

02:01:51.540 --> 02:01:56.820
In fact, they began to plot to seize the

02:01:54.659 --> 02:02:01.260
city for themselves.

02:01:56.820 --> 02:02:04.139
Polybius recounts what happened next.

02:02:01.260 --> 02:02:07.560
Certain Campanians serving under

02:02:04.139 --> 02:02:10.679
Agathocles had long cast covetous eyes

02:02:07.560 --> 02:02:12.960
on the beauty and prosperity of Messina,

02:02:10.679 --> 02:02:16.199
and they availed themselves of the first

02:02:12.960 --> 02:02:18.659
opportunity to capture it by treachery.

02:02:16.199 --> 02:02:21.420
After being admitted as friends and

02:02:18.659 --> 02:02:24.060
occupying the city, they first expelled

02:02:21.420 --> 02:02:26.580
or massacred the citizens, and then took

02:02:24.060 --> 02:02:28.560
possession of the wives and families of

02:02:26.580 --> 02:02:31.619
the dispossessed victims.

02:02:28.560 --> 02:02:34.920
They next divided among themselves the

02:02:31.619 --> 02:02:37.199
land and all other property.

02:02:34.920 --> 02:02:39.719
For the next twenty years or so, the

02:02:37.199 --> 02:02:41.340
Mamertines would run Messina as a kind of

02:02:39.719 --> 02:02:43.320
pirate fortress.

02:02:41.340 --> 02:02:46.619
They would use it as a base to conduct

02:02:43.320 --> 02:02:48.960
raids on nearby towns and villages, and

02:02:46.619 --> 02:02:50.820
to rob ships that sailed through the

02:02:48.960 --> 02:02:53.580
narrow straits.

02:02:50.820 --> 02:02:57.540
But soon, the last remaining Greek king

02:02:53.580 --> 02:02:59.340
in Sicily, a king of Syracuse named Hiero,

02:02:57.540 --> 02:03:02.880
had had enough.

02:02:59.340 --> 02:03:05.940
In the year 265 BC, he moved to attack

02:03:02.880 --> 02:03:09.020
the city of Messina to stamp out these

02:03:05.940 --> 02:03:09.020
troublesome pirates.

02:03:11.599 --> 02:03:17.520
Fearing execution for their crimes, the

02:03:14.940 --> 02:03:20.400
Mamertines played the only card left to

02:03:17.520 --> 02:03:23.820
them; trading on the strategic importance

02:03:20.400 --> 02:03:26.520
of the city. They sent out requests for

02:03:23.820 --> 02:03:29.699
help to both of the big players in the

02:03:26.520 --> 02:03:32.880
region, to Rome and to Carthage.

02:03:29.699 --> 02:03:35.880
The Carthaginians, being closer, came to

02:03:32.880 --> 02:03:39.000
their help first, delighted as always to

02:03:35.880 --> 02:03:41.940
kick sand in the face of the Greeks.

02:03:39.000 --> 02:03:44.940
They moved a small army into Messina and

02:03:41.940 --> 02:03:47.699
helped the Mamertines to defend it.

02:03:44.940 --> 02:03:50.040
This was just the latest move in the

02:03:47.699 --> 02:03:53.159
nearly two-century chess game between

02:03:50.040 --> 02:03:56.340
Carthage and the Greeks of Sicily, but to

02:03:53.159 --> 02:03:58.619
the Romans, it was a worrying move.

02:03:56.340 --> 02:04:00.900
With control of the crossing over to

02:03:58.619 --> 02:04:03.540
Italy, the Romans began to fear that

02:04:00.900 --> 02:04:07.159
Carthage was plotting an invasion of the

02:04:03.540 --> 02:04:11.159
mainland, as Polybius recalls.

02:04:07.159 --> 02:04:13.920
The Romans saw all this and felt that it

02:04:11.159 --> 02:04:17.159
was absolutely necessary not to let

02:04:13.920 --> 02:04:20.159
Messina slip or allow the Carthaginians

02:04:17.159 --> 02:04:23.099
to secure what would be like a bridge to

02:04:20.159 --> 02:04:26.340
enable them to cross into Italy.

02:04:23.099 --> 02:04:29.460
The Roman senate was bitterly divided on

02:04:26.340 --> 02:04:32.219
what to do, with many expressing disgust

02:04:29.460 --> 02:04:34.020
at coming to the aid of what amounted to

02:04:32.219 --> 02:04:37.260
a band of pirates,

02:04:34.020 --> 02:04:40.139
but eventually their fears won out.

02:04:37.260 --> 02:04:42.900
They voted to send a force to Messina to

02:04:40.139 --> 02:04:46.699
secure the crossing led by a consul

02:04:42.900 --> 02:04:46.699
named Appius Claudius.

02:04:48.540 --> 02:04:54.540
Rome was an inland city situated on the

02:04:52.020 --> 02:04:56.940
river Tiber, and so, the Romans were not a

02:04:54.540 --> 02:04:59.340
naturally seagoing people.

02:04:56.940 --> 02:05:01.260
With few ships of their own, they

02:04:59.340 --> 02:05:04.260
borrowed as many as they could from the

02:05:01.260 --> 02:05:06.719
coastal cities of southern Italy.

02:05:04.260 --> 02:05:09.420
When they first took in hand to send

02:05:06.719 --> 02:05:12.719
troops across to Messina, they not only

02:05:09.420 --> 02:05:15.780
had no decked vessels, but no warships at

02:05:12.719 --> 02:05:18.239
all, not so much as a single galley, but

02:05:15.780 --> 02:05:21.239
they borrowed quinqueremes and triremes

02:05:18.239 --> 02:05:23.880
from Tarentum and Locri, and even from

02:05:21.239 --> 02:05:26.239
Elea and Neapolis.

02:05:23.880 --> 02:05:28.980
The Romans, under the command of Appius,

02:05:26.239 --> 02:05:31.980
successfully made the short crossing in

02:05:28.980 --> 02:05:34.500
264 BC, catching the powerful

02:05:31.980 --> 02:05:36.840
Carthaginian navy off guard.

02:05:34.500 --> 02:05:39.840
When they arrived in Messina, the Italian

02:05:36.840 --> 02:05:42.060
Mamertines ousted the Carthaginians who

02:05:39.840 --> 02:05:46.679
had come to their aid, and welcomed the

02:05:42.060 --> 02:05:49.679
Roman army into the town in their place.

02:05:46.679 --> 02:05:52.980
The Roman capture of Messina immediately

02:05:49.679 --> 02:05:55.800
shifted the balance of power in Sicily.

02:05:52.980 --> 02:05:57.840
The Greeks of Syracuse formed a hasty

02:05:55.800 --> 02:06:00.540
alliance with their ancient enemies in

02:05:57.840 --> 02:06:04.320
Carthage, overturning two centuries of

02:06:00.540 --> 02:06:05.940
war to repel this new invader, but it was

02:06:04.320 --> 02:06:08.820
no good.

02:06:05.940 --> 02:06:12.300
The Roman commander Appius descended on

02:06:08.820 --> 02:06:14.760
Syracuse with lightning speed, as

02:06:12.300 --> 02:06:17.599
Polybius writes.

02:06:14.760 --> 02:06:20.400
Having succeeded in engaging the enemy,

02:06:17.599 --> 02:06:23.119
thenceforth he scoured the territory of

02:06:20.400 --> 02:06:26.340
Syracuse and her allies with impunity,

02:06:23.119 --> 02:06:28.080
and laid it waste without finding anyone

02:06:26.340 --> 02:06:30.960
to dispute the possession of the open

02:06:28.080 --> 02:06:34.500
country with him, and finally he sat down

02:06:30.960 --> 02:06:36.179
before Syracuse itself and laid siege to

02:06:34.500 --> 02:06:39.840
it.

02:06:36.179 --> 02:06:41.340
King Hiero saw no other way out.

02:06:39.840 --> 02:06:44.340
He surrendered,

02:06:41.340 --> 02:06:46.260
switched sides, and swore allegiance to

02:06:44.340 --> 02:06:49.080
the Romans.

02:06:46.260 --> 02:06:52.679
This was the end of the last independent

02:06:49.080 --> 02:06:55.080
Greek states in Italy and Sicily, and the

02:06:52.679 --> 02:06:59.159
future of the Mediterranean would now be

02:06:55.080 --> 02:07:04.280
decided by either Carthage or Rome.

02:06:59.159 --> 02:07:04.280
Both sides now marched to war.

02:07:10.800 --> 02:07:16.199
In this First Punic War, the

02:07:13.560 --> 02:07:18.900
Carthaginians were clearly concerned.

02:07:16.199 --> 02:07:21.540
They drew up a large army of Celts,

02:07:18.900 --> 02:07:24.480
Iberians, and other peoples, and

02:07:21.540 --> 02:07:27.060
dispatched it to Sicily, but they were

02:07:24.480 --> 02:07:29.460
also confident in their overall strategy,

02:07:27.060 --> 02:07:31.800
which had served them well in previous

02:07:29.460 --> 02:07:34.619
Sicilian wars.

02:07:31.800 --> 02:07:37.440
While the warships of Carthage commanded

02:07:34.619 --> 02:07:39.360
the waves, their trading empire would

02:07:37.440 --> 02:07:41.580
continue to fill their treasury with

02:07:39.360 --> 02:07:45.000
gold, and that meant there would always

02:07:41.580 --> 02:07:47.460
be soldiers ready to fight for them.

02:07:45.000 --> 02:07:50.520
At first, it seemed the Romans had no

02:07:47.460 --> 02:07:52.920
hope of changing this situation; they had

02:07:50.520 --> 02:07:55.380
virtually no navy, and their own

02:07:52.920 --> 02:07:57.900
shipbuilding technology lagged behind,

02:07:55.380 --> 02:08:01.800
perhaps by centuries,

02:07:57.900 --> 02:08:04.980
as the historian Polybius writes.

02:08:01.800 --> 02:08:07.199
Yet, so long as the Carthaginians were an

02:08:04.980 --> 02:08:09.360
undisturbed command of the sea, the

02:08:07.199 --> 02:08:12.420
balance of success could not incline

02:08:09.360 --> 02:08:14.940
decisively in their favor, so they took

02:08:12.420 --> 02:08:17.639
upon themselves there and then to meet

02:08:14.940 --> 02:08:20.639
the Carthaginians at sea, on which they

02:08:17.639 --> 02:08:23.099
had for generations held undisputed

02:08:20.639 --> 02:08:26.219
supremacy.

02:08:23.099 --> 02:08:28.020
The Carthaginian navy benefited from a

02:08:26.219 --> 02:08:30.659
thousand years of Phoenician

02:08:28.020 --> 02:08:32.400
shipbuilding and sailing tradition, but

02:08:30.659 --> 02:08:35.280
their centuries of relatively

02:08:32.400 --> 02:08:38.340
unchallenged dominance of the sea had

02:08:35.280 --> 02:08:40.260
also made them somewhat complacent.

02:08:38.340 --> 02:08:43.080
Their method of fighting on the water

02:08:40.260 --> 02:08:45.960
was based mostly on the use of heavy

02:08:43.080 --> 02:08:47.099
bronze rams fixed to the front of their

02:08:45.960 --> 02:08:49.500
ships.

02:08:47.099 --> 02:08:51.300
The Phoenician sailors relied on

02:08:49.500 --> 02:08:53.520
outmaneuvering their enemies on the

02:08:51.300 --> 02:08:56.280
waves with their superior sailing,

02:08:53.520 --> 02:08:58.500
drawing close with their oars, and

02:08:56.280 --> 02:09:00.960
crashing into the sides of enemy ships

02:08:58.500 --> 02:09:03.179
with these rams, striking them in the

02:09:00.960 --> 02:09:05.580
hulls below the water line.

02:09:03.179 --> 02:09:07.920
It was a method of warfare that had

02:09:05.580 --> 02:09:10.739
remained unchanged for the last 500

02:09:07.920 --> 02:09:13.560
years, and the Carthaginians were among

02:09:10.739 --> 02:09:15.060
the best in the world at this tricky way

02:09:13.560 --> 02:09:17.699
of fighting.

02:09:15.060 --> 02:09:20.040
But soon, the Romans would come across a

02:09:17.699 --> 02:09:22.920
stroke of good luck.

02:09:20.040 --> 02:09:25.380
After one skirmish on the sea, a

02:09:22.920 --> 02:09:27.060
Carthaginian galley had run aground on

02:09:25.380 --> 02:09:29.580
the shores of Italy.

02:09:27.060 --> 02:09:32.460
It was a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity

02:09:29.580 --> 02:09:34.800
to learn what made the Carthaginian navy

02:09:32.460 --> 02:09:37.260
so effective.

02:09:34.800 --> 02:09:41.159
The Romans rushed to secure the vessel,

02:09:37.260 --> 02:09:44.599
to haul it away and study its secrets, as

02:09:41.159 --> 02:09:44.599
Polybius records.

02:09:45.179 --> 02:09:50.639
The Carthaginians, having put to sea in

02:09:47.880 --> 02:09:53.580
the strait to attack, a decked vessel of

02:09:50.639 --> 02:09:56.099
theirs charged so furiously that it ran

02:09:53.580 --> 02:09:58.860
aground, and, falling into the hands of

02:09:56.099 --> 02:10:01.199
the Romans, served them as a model on

02:09:58.860 --> 02:10:04.320
which they constructed their whole fleet.

02:10:01.199 --> 02:10:05.880
If this had not happened, it is clear

02:10:04.320 --> 02:10:10.159
that they would have been completely

02:10:05.880 --> 02:10:10.159
hindered from carrying out their design.

02:10:11.099 --> 02:10:16.800
What the Romans found on this vessel

02:10:13.260 --> 02:10:19.260
would have intrigued and excited them.

02:10:16.800 --> 02:10:21.420
At that time, the Carthaginians were

02:10:19.260 --> 02:10:24.000
legendary not just for their sailing and

02:10:21.420 --> 02:10:27.000
the size of their fleet, but also how

02:10:24.000 --> 02:10:29.760
quickly they could build ships.

02:10:27.000 --> 02:10:33.300
The writer Pliny the Elder recounts what

02:10:29.760 --> 02:10:37.500
was possible in those days.

02:10:33.300 --> 02:10:40.560
Piso relates that 220 ships were wholly

02:10:37.500 --> 02:10:43.860
constructed in 45 days;

02:10:40.560 --> 02:10:46.619
in the Second Punic War, too, the fleet was

02:10:43.860 --> 02:10:49.580
at sea the fortieth day after the axe had

02:10:46.619 --> 02:10:49.580
been put to the tree.

02:10:50.280 --> 02:10:55.380
This was long considered to be an

02:10:52.619 --> 02:10:57.480
exaggeration by ancient writers, but the

02:10:55.380 --> 02:11:00.360
discovery of the Phoenician shipwreck,

02:10:57.480 --> 02:11:02.099
known as the Marsala ship, has thrown

02:11:00.360 --> 02:11:04.199
light on how this kind of mass-

02:11:02.099 --> 02:11:05.340
-manufacture could actually have been

02:11:04.199 --> 02:11:06.860
possible.

02:11:05.340 --> 02:11:09.300
When the wreck was discovered,

02:11:06.860 --> 02:11:11.639
archaeologists found that the ship had

02:11:09.300 --> 02:11:13.920
each section of its hull marked with

02:11:11.639 --> 02:11:15.719
certain Phoenician letters.

02:11:13.920 --> 02:11:18.060
It's thought that these sections would

02:11:15.719 --> 02:11:20.340
have been built separately, mass-produced

02:11:18.060 --> 02:11:23.040
in separate factories, and then brought

02:11:20.340 --> 02:11:24.960
together in their final location, with a

02:11:23.040 --> 02:11:26.639
level of coordination that would not be

02:11:24.960 --> 02:11:28.260
seen again before the Industrial

02:11:26.639 --> 02:11:31.139
Revolution.

02:11:28.260 --> 02:11:33.000
These ships were a kind of ancient

02:11:31.139 --> 02:11:35.639
flatpack furniture.

02:11:33.000 --> 02:11:37.440
Armed with this new knowledge, the Romans

02:11:35.639 --> 02:11:40.500
began the process of copying the

02:11:37.440 --> 02:11:43.500
Carthaginian ship exactly, but they

02:11:40.500 --> 02:11:45.540
didn't do very well.

02:11:43.500 --> 02:11:48.119
In their first engagement with Carthage,

02:11:45.540 --> 02:11:50.159
the inferior mobility of these Roman

02:11:48.119 --> 02:11:52.260
ships and the inexperience of their

02:11:50.159 --> 02:11:55.080
sailors meant that a squadron of 17

02:11:52.260 --> 02:11:57.540
Roman vessels was destroyed, easily

02:11:55.080 --> 02:12:01.639
outmaneuvered by the Phoenicians, and

02:11:57.540 --> 02:12:01.639
dealt death blows by their rams.

02:12:01.739 --> 02:12:05.940
Following this, the Romans began to

02:12:03.900 --> 02:12:07.679
change their tactics.

02:12:05.940 --> 02:12:10.260
Getting the hang of the complicated

02:12:07.679 --> 02:12:13.320
business of outmaneuvering and ramming

02:12:10.260 --> 02:12:15.300
enemy ships would take too long, and so,

02:12:13.320 --> 02:12:18.000
they tried to bring the battles at sea

02:12:15.300 --> 02:12:20.159
into more familiar territory.

02:12:18.000 --> 02:12:23.060
To do this, they developed an ingenious

02:12:20.159 --> 02:12:23.060
new technology.

02:12:23.219 --> 02:12:28.980
It was a kind of boarding bridge that

02:12:25.800 --> 02:12:31.380
they called a corvus, the Latin word for

02:12:28.980 --> 02:12:34.500
crow.

02:12:31.380 --> 02:12:36.420
These were raised like a drawbridge at

02:12:34.500 --> 02:12:39.060
the front of the ship, and when they drew

02:12:36.420 --> 02:12:40.860
near to an enemy vessel, these gangplanks

02:12:39.060 --> 02:12:42.900
would have dropped down onto the enemy

02:12:40.860 --> 02:12:46.020
deck, where a metal spike on the

02:12:42.900 --> 02:12:46.980
underside would drive its way into the

02:12:46.020 --> 02:12:49.380
wood.

02:12:46.980 --> 02:12:51.900
These bridges would now hold the two

02:12:49.380 --> 02:12:54.500
ships together, neutralizing the speed

02:12:51.900 --> 02:12:56.880
and agility of the Carthaginian vessels,

02:12:54.500 --> 02:12:59.099
preventing them from ramming, and

02:12:56.880 --> 02:13:00.599
allowing the Roman legionaries to flood

02:12:59.099 --> 02:13:03.119
on board.

02:13:00.599 --> 02:13:05.760
It was a crude but surprisingly

02:13:03.119 --> 02:13:07.739
effective tactic.

02:13:05.760 --> 02:13:10.079
The Romans kept their new inventions

02:13:07.739 --> 02:13:12.179
hidden, and now with a secret naval

02:13:10.079 --> 02:13:16.639
weapon of their own, they risked a

02:13:12.179 --> 02:13:16.639
large-scale confrontation on the sea.

02:13:19.920 --> 02:13:24.900
The Carthaginian fleet was busy

02:13:22.199 --> 02:13:26.880
plundering at a place called Mylae, on

02:13:24.900 --> 02:13:30.300
the coast of northern Sicily, when they

02:13:26.880 --> 02:13:32.099
saw the Roman sails on the horizon.

02:13:30.300 --> 02:13:34.619
They were delighted that their enemies

02:13:32.099 --> 02:13:36.840
had finally risked a battle, and were

02:13:34.619 --> 02:13:39.239
supremely confident of sending the whole

02:13:36.840 --> 02:13:42.599
fleet of this troublesome Italian power

02:13:39.239 --> 02:13:46.440
straight to the bottom of the ocean.

02:13:42.599 --> 02:13:49.320
Polybius recounts what happened next.

02:13:46.440 --> 02:13:53.219
No sooner did the Carthaginians sight him

02:13:49.320 --> 02:13:56.400
than with joy they put to sea with 130

02:13:53.219 --> 02:13:58.639
sail, feeling supreme contempt for the

02:13:56.400 --> 02:14:01.320
Roman ignorance of seamanship.

02:13:58.639 --> 02:14:03.780
Accordingly, they all sailed with their

02:14:01.320 --> 02:14:06.659
prows directed straight at their enemy;

02:14:03.780 --> 02:14:09.179
they did not think the engagement worth

02:14:06.659 --> 02:14:12.540
even the trouble of ranging their ships

02:14:09.179 --> 02:14:15.840
in any order. When they neared the enemy,

02:14:12.540 --> 02:14:17.940
they saw the crows raised aloft on the

02:14:15.840 --> 02:14:20.579
prows of several ships. The

02:14:17.940 --> 02:14:22.739
Carthaginians were, for a time, in a state

02:14:20.579 --> 02:14:25.800
of perplexity, for they were quite

02:14:22.739 --> 02:14:28.560
strangers to such contrivances as these

02:14:25.800 --> 02:14:30.960
engines. Feeling, however, a complete

02:14:28.560 --> 02:14:33.060
contempt for their opponent, they charged

02:14:30.960 --> 02:14:35.760
without flinching, but as soon as they

02:14:33.060 --> 02:14:38.219
came to close quarters, their ships were

02:14:35.760 --> 02:14:41.040
invariably tightly grappled by these

02:14:38.219 --> 02:14:43.199
machines. The enemy boarded by means of

02:14:41.040 --> 02:14:45.599
the crows and engaged them on their

02:14:43.199 --> 02:14:48.420
decks, and in the end, some of the

02:14:45.599 --> 02:14:51.239
Carthaginians were cut down, while others

02:14:48.420 --> 02:14:52.980
surrendered in bewildered terror at the

02:14:51.239 --> 02:14:56.099
battle in which they found themselves

02:14:52.980 --> 02:14:58.679
engaged, which eventually became exactly

02:14:56.099 --> 02:15:01.500
like a land fight. Eventually, the

02:14:58.679 --> 02:15:04.440
Carthaginians turned and fled, bewildered at

02:15:01.500 --> 02:15:07.579
the novelty of the occurrence, and with a

02:15:04.440 --> 02:15:07.579
loss of fifty ships.

02:15:07.679 --> 02:15:14.099
For Carthage, this was an utter disaster.

02:15:11.579 --> 02:15:16.440
Flying high from their successes, the

02:15:14.099 --> 02:15:18.500
Romans soon organized invasions of the

02:15:16.440 --> 02:15:21.000
islands of Sardinia and Corsica,

02:15:18.500 --> 02:15:24.300
Carthaginian possessions for centuries

02:15:21.000 --> 02:15:26.460
that had never been seriously threatened.

02:15:24.300 --> 02:15:29.040
They even organized an invasion of North

02:15:26.460 --> 02:15:31.860
Africa itself, hoping to follow in the

02:15:29.040 --> 02:15:34.500
footsteps of Agathocles and march on

02:15:31.860 --> 02:15:36.659
the capital of Carthage.

02:15:34.500 --> 02:15:39.599
For the Carthaginians, things were

02:15:36.659 --> 02:15:42.119
starting to get out of hand.

02:15:39.599 --> 02:15:44.639
As the Roman invasion force descended

02:15:42.119 --> 02:15:46.800
upon the coast, Carthage sent out the

02:15:44.639 --> 02:15:48.540
entirety of its fleet to meet them on

02:15:46.800 --> 02:15:51.360
the open sea.

02:15:48.540 --> 02:15:53.699
Polybius recounts that as they sighted the

02:15:51.360 --> 02:15:55.739
Roman sails on the horizon, the

02:15:53.699 --> 02:15:58.560
commanders of Carthage spoke to their

02:15:55.739 --> 02:16:00.659
sailors and soldiers, and vocalized a

02:15:58.560 --> 02:16:02.940
fear that must have been on the lips of

02:16:00.659 --> 02:16:06.000
every man and woman in the Phoenician

02:16:02.940 --> 02:16:09.060
territories, that this war was now in

02:16:06.000 --> 02:16:11.699
danger of coming home.

02:16:09.060 --> 02:16:14.460
Meanwhile, the Carthaginian commanders

02:16:11.699 --> 02:16:16.980
had briefly addressed their men.

02:16:14.460 --> 02:16:18.780
They pointed out to them that victory in

02:16:16.980 --> 02:16:20.520
this battle would ensure that the war in

02:16:18.780 --> 02:16:23.579
the future was confined to the question

02:16:20.520 --> 02:16:24.900
of the possession of Sicily, while if

02:16:23.579 --> 02:16:27.719
they were beaten, they would have

02:16:24.900 --> 02:16:32.000
hereafter to fight for their native land

02:16:27.719 --> 02:16:32.000
and for all that they held dear.

02:16:32.280 --> 02:16:37.500
Polybius records that more than 600

02:16:35.160 --> 02:16:40.260
ships came together in the battle that

02:16:37.500 --> 02:16:42.540
ensued. By the time he was writing his

02:16:40.260 --> 02:16:45.059
history of the Punic Wars more than a

02:16:42.540 --> 02:16:47.580
hundred years later, the size of warships

02:16:45.059 --> 02:16:49.740
had dramatically increased, and so, he

02:16:47.580 --> 02:16:52.380
likely wildly overestimates the number

02:16:49.740 --> 02:16:55.380
of men involved, putting it at well over

02:16:52.380 --> 02:16:57.479
300,000. Nevertheless, the

02:16:55.380 --> 02:17:01.200
battle was enormous and probably

02:16:57.479 --> 02:17:04.380
involved at least 120,000 sailors,

02:17:01.200 --> 02:17:06.899
soldiers, rowers, and marines.

02:17:04.380 --> 02:17:09.780
The vast battlefield would have devolved

02:17:06.899 --> 02:17:12.540
into a chaos of clashing oars and rams,

02:17:09.780 --> 02:17:15.719
shouting men, and the thud of the corvus

02:17:12.540 --> 02:17:18.120
bridges crushing down onto the decks, the

02:17:15.719 --> 02:17:20.639
clashing of shields and swords, the

02:17:18.120 --> 02:17:22.679
crashing of waves, and the shrieking of

02:17:20.639 --> 02:17:25.200
gulls overhead.

02:17:22.679 --> 02:17:27.780
By the end of the day, the result of the

02:17:25.200 --> 02:17:30.559
battle was a decisive defeat for the

02:17:27.780 --> 02:17:30.559
Carthaginians.

02:17:31.740 --> 02:17:36.420
With the fleet of Carthage scattered, the

02:17:34.380 --> 02:17:39.179
Romans successfully made the crossing

02:17:36.420 --> 02:17:41.639
into Africa and landed on the peninsula

02:17:39.179 --> 02:17:43.920
of Cape Bon, on the other side of the

02:17:41.639 --> 02:17:46.620
bay from the city.

02:17:43.920 --> 02:17:48.719
The citizens of Carthage would now have

02:17:46.620 --> 02:17:51.840
been able to see the campfires of the

02:17:48.719 --> 02:17:53.880
Roman army in the distance at night.

02:17:51.840 --> 02:17:55.740
Some of the city's oldest residents

02:17:53.880 --> 02:17:58.200
would still have remembered when the

02:17:55.740 --> 02:18:00.899
army of Agathocles had menaced the city

02:17:58.200 --> 02:18:03.300
only half a century before, when they had

02:18:00.899 --> 02:18:05.160
watched those ships burning on the

02:18:03.300 --> 02:18:08.219
shoreline.

02:18:05.160 --> 02:18:10.500
The Carthaginians had had enough.

02:18:08.219 --> 02:18:13.080
They asked the Romans for a peace treaty

02:18:10.500 --> 02:18:15.660
to sign, but the Roman demands were so

02:18:13.080 --> 02:18:17.639
punishing that the Carthaginians, even in

02:18:15.660 --> 02:18:22.139
their desperate state, could not accept

02:18:17.639 --> 02:18:25.200
it, and so, the war dragged on.

02:18:22.139 --> 02:18:27.540
But the Romans, like Agathocles, found

02:18:25.200 --> 02:18:28.740
themselves unable to take the city of

02:18:27.540 --> 02:18:31.200
Carthage.

02:18:28.740 --> 02:18:34.019
The Roman expeditionary force sent to

02:18:31.200 --> 02:18:36.660
capture the city was beaten disastrously

02:18:34.019 --> 02:18:39.420
by a smaller Carthaginian army at the

02:18:36.660 --> 02:18:42.599
battle of Tunis, and the Roman consul

02:18:39.420 --> 02:18:45.179
leading it was captured and killed.

02:18:42.599 --> 02:18:50.000
In this way, the fortunes of each side

02:18:45.179 --> 02:18:50.000
ticked back and forth like a pendulum.

02:18:50.460 --> 02:18:56.099
Another naval battle at Cape Hermaeum saw

02:18:53.880 --> 02:18:59.160
another Roman victory and another

02:18:56.099 --> 02:19:01.679
hundred Carthaginian ships sunk, but the

02:18:59.160 --> 02:19:04.439
Romans had no time to celebrate.

02:19:01.679 --> 02:19:06.840
On its return voyage home, the victorious

02:19:04.439 --> 02:19:10.979
Roman fleet was hit by a devastating

02:19:06.840 --> 02:19:14.099
storm, as Polybius records.

02:19:10.979 --> 02:19:18.780
The disaster was indeed extreme, for out

02:19:14.099 --> 02:19:21.240
of their 364 vessels, 80 only remained.

02:19:18.780 --> 02:19:24.000
The rest were either swamped or driven

02:19:21.240 --> 02:19:27.059
by the surf upon the rocks and headlands,

02:19:24.000 --> 02:19:29.340
where they went to pieces and filled all

02:19:27.059 --> 02:19:32.939
the seaboard with corpses and wreckage.

02:19:29.340 --> 02:19:35.939
No greater catastrophe is to be found in

02:19:32.939 --> 02:19:38.179
all history as befalling a fleet at one

02:19:35.939 --> 02:19:38.179
time.

02:19:38.300 --> 02:19:45.240
284 ships were lost, with an estimated

02:19:42.780 --> 02:19:46.620
60,000 sailors sinking to the bottom of the

02:19:45.240 --> 02:19:49.260
sea.

02:19:46.620 --> 02:19:51.979
It was among the worst naval disasters

02:19:49.260 --> 02:19:51.979
in history.

02:19:52.920 --> 02:19:58.560
Some historians have speculated that the

02:19:55.560 --> 02:20:00.780
Romansí secret weapon, the corvus boarding

02:19:58.560 --> 02:20:03.600
bridges, may have actually made their

02:20:00.780 --> 02:20:05.820
ships top-heavy and prone to capsizing

02:20:03.600 --> 02:20:08.040
in stormy conditions.

02:20:05.820 --> 02:20:10.620
After this disaster, there are no

02:20:08.040 --> 02:20:14.420
mentions of the corvus ever being used

02:20:10.620 --> 02:20:14.420
again on Roman ships.

02:20:14.580 --> 02:20:20.340
The war would drag on for another 14

02:20:17.700 --> 02:20:23.939
years, with most of the fighting taking

02:20:20.340 --> 02:20:27.720
place in Sicily and the surrounding seas,

02:20:23.939 --> 02:20:29.280
but by the year 241 BC, Carthage was

02:20:27.720 --> 02:20:31.560
spent.

02:20:29.280 --> 02:20:34.260
The Carthaginian senate ordered their

02:20:31.560 --> 02:20:36.899
general in Sicily to sign whatever peace

02:20:34.260 --> 02:20:38.460
treaty the Romans demanded, no matter how

02:20:36.899 --> 02:20:41.000
punishing.

02:20:38.460 --> 02:20:45.680
This general was a man named Hamilcar

02:20:41.000 --> 02:20:48.420
Barca. He was proud, a competent general,

02:20:45.680 --> 02:20:51.300
and he had been winning some of his

02:20:48.420 --> 02:20:53.520
battles in Sicily. He believed that

02:20:51.300 --> 02:20:56.880
signing such a punishing treaty was

02:20:53.520 --> 02:20:58.500
madness, and so, he refused the order to

02:20:56.880 --> 02:21:01.020
negotiate.

02:20:58.500 --> 02:21:05.960
In his place, the senate sent a more

02:21:01.020 --> 02:21:05.960
junior commander to capitulate to Rome.

02:21:08.359 --> 02:21:17.160
The First Punic War ended in the year

02:21:11.700 --> 02:21:21.380
241 BC, 23 years after it had begun, with

02:21:17.160 --> 02:21:21.380
the signing of the Treaty of Lutatius.

02:21:21.479 --> 02:21:26.100
It was one of the longest continuous

02:21:23.640 --> 02:21:27.060
wars to ever take place in the ancient

02:21:26.100 --> 02:21:29.880
world.

02:21:27.060 --> 02:21:32.040
It had exhausted both Rome and Carthage,

02:21:29.880 --> 02:21:33.540
and driven them both to the brink of

02:21:32.040 --> 02:21:36.420
bankruptcy.

02:21:33.540 --> 02:21:38.760
But Rome, as the victor, had at least

02:21:36.420 --> 02:21:40.920
gained something from all the years of

02:21:38.760 --> 02:21:43.439
carnage.

02:21:40.920 --> 02:21:45.840
Under the terms of the treaty, Carthage

02:21:43.439 --> 02:21:48.960
was forced to give up all its remaining

02:21:45.840 --> 02:21:51.000
territory in Sicily to Rome, and possibly

02:21:48.960 --> 02:21:53.460
the island of Corsica, too.

02:21:51.000 --> 02:21:56.100
Carthage was forced to release all Roman

02:21:53.460 --> 02:21:57.899
prisoners without ransom, while hefty

02:21:56.100 --> 02:22:00.720
ransoms were charged for any

02:21:57.899 --> 02:22:03.479
Carthaginian held by Rome,

02:22:00.720 --> 02:22:07.020
and they were forced to pay a staggering

02:22:03.479 --> 02:22:10.380
82 tons of silver in reparations to Rome

02:22:07.020 --> 02:22:13.380
over the next ten years.

02:22:10.380 --> 02:22:16.380
All of this meant that Carthage could no

02:22:13.380 --> 02:22:18.660
longer afford to pay its armies.

02:22:16.380 --> 02:22:21.359
Many of these were foreign mercenaries

02:22:18.660 --> 02:22:24.000
that it was already in debt to, and in

02:22:21.359 --> 02:22:26.220
the same year as the treaty was signed, a

02:22:24.000 --> 02:22:28.979
large band of these mercenaries, around

02:22:26.220 --> 02:22:31.740
20,000 men or so, camped outside

02:22:28.979 --> 02:22:34.280
the city itself and refused to budge

02:22:31.740 --> 02:22:38.460
until they got paid.

02:22:34.280 --> 02:22:40.859
But the state was all but bankrupt.

02:22:38.460 --> 02:22:43.260
When the Carthaginian senate delayed in

02:22:40.859 --> 02:22:47.340
paying them, they mutinied and began

02:22:43.260 --> 02:22:49.979
looting and burning the countryside.

02:22:47.340 --> 02:22:52.800
While the two decades of war had been

02:22:49.979 --> 02:22:55.140
tough on the citizens of Carthage, it had

02:22:52.800 --> 02:22:57.840
been even tougher on the rural regions

02:22:55.140 --> 02:23:00.899
of Africa it ruled over.

02:22:57.840 --> 02:23:03.600
Carthaginian provinces like Libya had

02:23:00.899 --> 02:23:06.600
sent huge numbers of men to fight for

02:23:03.600 --> 02:23:09.600
Carthage, and they were subjected to

02:23:06.600 --> 02:23:12.120
punishing taxes to pay for it all.

02:23:09.600 --> 02:23:15.800
Their resentment had been slowly

02:23:12.120 --> 02:23:18.960
building, and now it boiled over.

02:23:15.800 --> 02:23:21.060
When news of this army of rioting

02:23:18.960 --> 02:23:23.280
mercenaries reached some of these

02:23:21.060 --> 02:23:26.160
discontented cities, they saw their

02:23:23.280 --> 02:23:28.319
chance to free themselves of the rule of

02:23:26.160 --> 02:23:31.319
Carthage entirely.

02:23:28.319 --> 02:23:34.560
Many of them rebelled, and soon Carthage

02:23:31.319 --> 02:23:37.020
was engulfed in a civil war.

02:23:34.560 --> 02:23:39.720
It looked for the first time like the

02:23:37.020 --> 02:23:44.420
entire empire might come apart at the

02:23:39.720 --> 02:23:44.420
seams, as Polybius writes.

02:23:44.520 --> 02:23:49.560
For three years and about four months

02:23:47.399 --> 02:23:52.020
did the Mercenaries maintain a war

02:23:49.560 --> 02:23:54.479
against the Carthaginians, which far

02:23:52.020 --> 02:23:57.000
surpassed any that I have heard of for

02:23:54.479 --> 02:23:59.280
cruelty and inhumanity.

02:23:57.000 --> 02:24:02.100
The many battles in which they have been

02:23:59.280 --> 02:24:04.740
engaged at sea have naturally left them

02:24:02.100 --> 02:24:07.319
ill-supplied with arms, sailors, and

02:24:04.740 --> 02:24:10.800
vessels. They had no store of provisions

02:24:07.319 --> 02:24:12.960
ready and no expectation whatever of

02:24:10.800 --> 02:24:14.100
external assistance from friends or

02:24:12.960 --> 02:24:16.800
allies.

02:24:14.100 --> 02:24:18.660
They were indeed now thoroughly taught

02:24:16.800 --> 02:24:21.479
the difference between a foreign war

02:24:18.660 --> 02:24:24.800
carried on beyond the seas and the

02:24:21.479 --> 02:24:24.800
domestic insurrection.

02:24:25.140 --> 02:24:30.540
The civil war that followed, which would

02:24:27.780 --> 02:24:34.080
become known as the Mercenary War, would

02:24:30.540 --> 02:24:36.720
unfold with unparalleled brutality.

02:24:34.080 --> 02:24:38.939
The bodies of crucified rebels would

02:24:36.720 --> 02:24:42.120
have become a regular sight along the

02:24:38.939 --> 02:24:44.880
roads. The instability caused a famine,

02:24:42.120 --> 02:24:47.520
and Carthage was forced to raise an army

02:24:44.880 --> 02:24:50.460
from its citizens, forcing ordinary

02:24:47.520 --> 02:24:52.800
people in the capital to fight.

02:24:50.460 --> 02:24:55.200
The man tasked by the Carthaginian

02:24:52.800 --> 02:24:58.200
senate with carrying out this civil war

02:24:55.200 --> 02:25:00.600
was the proud general Hamilcar Barca,

02:24:58.200 --> 02:25:02.580
the man who had refused to sign the

02:25:00.600 --> 02:25:05.040
treaty with Rome.

02:25:02.580 --> 02:25:07.620
Throughout these years of violence, he

02:25:05.040 --> 02:25:10.800
would have seen his homeland burning, his

02:25:07.620 --> 02:25:14.220
people starving and dying, and all this

02:25:10.800 --> 02:25:16.760
time, he nursed his hatred for his Roman

02:25:14.220 --> 02:25:16.760
enemies.

02:25:21.680 --> 02:25:28.260
At enormous cost, Hamilcar Barca would

02:25:25.680 --> 02:25:31.140
eventually crush the rebels, and he

02:25:28.260 --> 02:25:34.020
sometimes did this quite literally.

02:25:31.140 --> 02:25:37.080
Many insurgents captured in the later

02:25:34.020 --> 02:25:39.899
years of the war were executed beneath

02:25:37.080 --> 02:25:42.720
the feet of Carthage's elephants, the

02:25:39.899 --> 02:25:44.640
ultimate living symbol of the empire's

02:25:42.720 --> 02:25:47.819
power.

02:25:44.640 --> 02:25:49.920
After four years of civil war, some

02:25:47.819 --> 02:25:52.680
measure of order returned to the

02:25:49.920 --> 02:25:56.160
scorched countryside.

02:25:52.680 --> 02:25:58.020
The empire of Carthage had survived, but

02:25:56.160 --> 02:25:59.640
they were now in an even worse state

02:25:58.020 --> 02:26:02.040
than before.

02:25:59.640 --> 02:26:04.979
Meanwhile, the Romans had spent four

02:26:02.040 --> 02:26:08.640
years recovering and drawing wealth from

02:26:04.979 --> 02:26:11.939
their new lands in Sicily and Corsica. At

02:26:08.640 --> 02:26:14.399
Carthage's time of weakness, Rome moved

02:26:11.939 --> 02:26:17.040
to capture the island of Sardinia, too,

02:26:14.399 --> 02:26:18.899
which had escaped its grasp during the

02:26:17.040 --> 02:26:21.899
war and was now rebelling against

02:26:18.899 --> 02:26:24.420
Carthage's weakened rule.

02:26:21.899 --> 02:26:28.800
The Carthaginians could do nothing to

02:26:24.420 --> 02:26:31.140
stop them, as Polybius recalls.

02:26:28.800 --> 02:26:33.420
When the Carthaginians expressed

02:26:31.140 --> 02:26:36.000
indignation of this on the ground that

02:26:33.420 --> 02:26:38.939
the lordship over Sardinia more properly

02:26:36.000 --> 02:26:40.979
belonged to them, the Romans voted to

02:26:38.939 --> 02:26:43.800
declare war against them. The

02:26:40.979 --> 02:26:45.720
Carthaginians, however, having just had an

02:26:43.800 --> 02:26:47.819
almost miraculous escape from

02:26:45.720 --> 02:26:50.580
annihilation in the recent civil war,

02:26:47.819 --> 02:26:53.939
yielded to the necessities of the hour

02:26:50.580 --> 02:26:56.580
and not only abandoned Sardinia, but they

02:26:53.939 --> 02:26:58.859
paid the Romans 1,200 talents into the

02:26:56.580 --> 02:27:01.800
bargain that they might not be obliged

02:26:58.859 --> 02:27:03.420
to undertake the war for the present. The

02:27:01.800 --> 02:27:06.960
new balance of power in the

02:27:03.420 --> 02:27:10.380
Mediterranean was clear. Carthage was now

02:27:06.960 --> 02:27:13.020
a hollowed-out husk.

02:27:10.380 --> 02:27:15.180
If they were to reclaim any of the power

02:27:13.020 --> 02:27:17.220
that they had once held, the next

02:27:15.180 --> 02:27:19.680
generation of Carthaginian military

02:27:17.220 --> 02:27:22.620
leaders would need to produce a general

02:27:19.680 --> 02:27:24.780
of such genius that he could turn around

02:27:22.620 --> 02:27:26.760
the hopes and fortunes of this

02:27:24.780 --> 02:27:29.160
floundering empire,

02:27:26.760 --> 02:27:32.760
a general that would conduct a campaign

02:27:29.160 --> 02:27:35.700
so daring that it is still studied in

02:27:32.760 --> 02:27:38.819
military academies to this day.

02:27:35.700 --> 02:27:41.960
That man would bear a name that in

02:27:38.819 --> 02:27:46.580
Phoenician meant ëby the grace of Baalí.

02:27:41.960 --> 02:27:46.580
His name was Hannibal.

02:27:47.760 --> 02:27:50.760
Hannibal

02:28:08.479 --> 02:28:13.439
was the son of the general Hamilcar

02:28:11.399 --> 02:28:16.560
Barca.

02:28:13.439 --> 02:28:19.020
When the First Punic War ended, he was a

02:28:16.560 --> 02:28:21.000
boy of only six years old, and he would

02:28:19.020 --> 02:28:23.939
have watched with the formative mind of

02:28:21.000 --> 02:28:26.040
a child as the world he knew was torn

02:28:23.939 --> 02:28:29.340
apart by violence, and his father

02:28:26.040 --> 02:28:31.740
struggled to end the rebellions.

02:28:29.340 --> 02:28:34.620
When Rome had snatched away the island

02:28:31.740 --> 02:28:36.600
of Sardinia, Carthage lost the last of

02:28:34.620 --> 02:28:39.540
its profitable central Mediterranean

02:28:36.600 --> 02:28:42.660
islands, and with the empire so weakened,

02:28:39.540 --> 02:28:45.120
its economy was in freefall.

02:28:42.660 --> 02:28:48.020
If it was to right itself, Carthage would

02:28:45.120 --> 02:28:50.760
need to find vast resources of minerals,

02:28:48.020 --> 02:28:53.280
metals, and people,

02:28:50.760 --> 02:28:55.380
and Hannibal's father knew that the only

02:28:53.280 --> 02:28:57.780
way these could be found was by

02:28:55.380 --> 02:28:59.819
expanding Carthage's last remaining

02:28:57.780 --> 02:29:03.540
overseas territories.

02:28:59.819 --> 02:29:06.319
These were in southern Spain, as Polybius

02:29:03.540 --> 02:29:06.319
writes. Hamilcar,

02:29:06.620 --> 02:29:12.540
with the anger felt by all his

02:29:09.180 --> 02:29:14.819
compatriots at this last outrage, as soon

02:29:12.540 --> 02:29:17.340
as he had finally crushed the mutiny of

02:29:14.819 --> 02:29:20.040
mercenaries and secured the safety of

02:29:17.340 --> 02:29:24.319
his country, at once threw all his

02:29:20.040 --> 02:29:24.319
efforts into the conquest of Spain.

02:29:24.660 --> 02:29:30.479
Hamilcar gathered an army and set out for

02:29:28.200 --> 02:29:34.020
the Spanish colonies.

02:29:30.479 --> 02:29:36.540
Rome now ruled the seas, and Carthage's

02:29:34.020 --> 02:29:39.200
navy was so weakened that he was unable

02:29:36.540 --> 02:29:41.640
to travel the whole way to Spain by ship.

02:29:39.200 --> 02:29:44.580
Instead, he had to march all the way

02:29:41.640 --> 02:29:46.920
across North Africa and ferry his army

02:29:44.580 --> 02:29:49.580
across the sea at the narrow Straits of

02:29:46.920 --> 02:29:49.580
Gibraltar.

02:29:49.620 --> 02:29:53.520
When he left,

02:29:51.120 --> 02:29:56.880
he took his own young son Hannibal with

02:29:53.520 --> 02:29:59.880
him to teach the boy the art of war and

02:29:56.880 --> 02:30:02.280
to ensure that he passed on his burning

02:29:59.880 --> 02:30:05.100
hatred for Rome.

02:30:02.280 --> 02:30:08.160
At the time, when his father was about to

02:30:05.100 --> 02:30:11.160
start with his army on his expedition to

02:30:08.160 --> 02:30:13.920
Spain, Hannibal, then nine years of age,

02:30:11.160 --> 02:30:17.220
were standing by the altar while

02:30:13.920 --> 02:30:20.160
Hamilcar was sacrificing to Zeus.

02:30:17.220 --> 02:30:23.100
His father took him by the hand, led him

02:30:20.160 --> 02:30:26.580
up to the altar, and bade him lay his

02:30:23.100 --> 02:30:29.640
hand on the victim and swear never to be

02:30:26.580 --> 02:30:33.180
the friend of the Romans. He made his own

02:30:29.640 --> 02:30:36.540
son Hannibal such an enemy of Rome that

02:30:33.180 --> 02:30:39.380
none could be more bitter.

02:30:36.540 --> 02:30:42.000
Despite the weakened state of Carthage,

02:30:39.380 --> 02:30:45.060
Hamilcar succeeded in conquering the

02:30:42.000 --> 02:30:47.760
Celtic tribes of Spain. He built a new

02:30:45.060 --> 02:30:50.580
city there that became known as New

02:30:47.760 --> 02:30:53.160
Carthage, now the southern Spanish city

02:30:50.580 --> 02:30:56.100
of Cartagena.

02:30:53.160 --> 02:30:58.380
While the young boy Hannibal grew up in

02:30:56.100 --> 02:31:02.100
Spain, he would have likely visited the

02:30:58.380 --> 02:31:04.680
Temple of Melqart or Hercules in Gades,

02:31:02.100 --> 02:31:06.300
that temple with the golden olive tree

02:31:04.680 --> 02:31:08.220
at its center.

02:31:06.300 --> 02:31:11.040
He would have heard stories about

02:31:08.220 --> 02:31:13.979
Hercules and his legendary journey over

02:31:11.040 --> 02:31:15.120
the Alps, herding the cattle of Geryon,

02:31:13.979 --> 02:31:16.800
the giant.

02:31:15.120 --> 02:31:19.439
Perhaps he would have even learned the

02:31:16.800 --> 02:31:21.960
history of the Greek, Agathocles, and

02:31:19.439 --> 02:31:25.140
his daring strike right at the heart of

02:31:21.960 --> 02:31:27.420
his stronger enemy. All this while, he

02:31:25.140 --> 02:31:30.800
would have dreamed of one day making his

02:31:27.420 --> 02:31:30.800
own mark on history.

02:31:32.880 --> 02:31:38.760
When his father Hamilcar died and his

02:31:36.300 --> 02:31:41.220
successor was assassinated, it would soon

02:31:38.760 --> 02:31:44.280
fall to the young Hannibal to lead the

02:31:41.220 --> 02:31:46.740
Carthaginian armies in Spain.

02:31:44.280 --> 02:31:49.260
He continued his father's work of

02:31:46.740 --> 02:31:51.780
expanding their territories, pushing back

02:31:49.260 --> 02:31:54.720
the local Celtic tribes who opposed him,

02:31:51.780 --> 02:31:56.160
and it's clear he developed a flare for

02:31:54.720 --> 02:31:58.920
warfare.

02:31:56.160 --> 02:32:01.260
By the time he was 27, Hannibal

02:31:58.920 --> 02:32:04.140
controlled more than half of the Iberian

02:32:01.260 --> 02:32:06.180
Peninsula, a vast and wealthy territory

02:32:04.140 --> 02:32:07.859
of nearly a quarter-million square

02:32:06.180 --> 02:32:10.560
kilometers.

02:32:07.859 --> 02:32:13.200
From his father, he had inherited an army

02:32:10.560 --> 02:32:16.740
of 60,000 battle-hardened troops,

02:32:13.200 --> 02:32:19.319
the best in the empire, and a stable of

02:32:16.740 --> 02:32:22.020
200 war elephants.

02:32:19.319 --> 02:32:25.020
He had also forged alliances with a

02:32:22.020 --> 02:32:28.260
number of Celtic tribes in Spain that he

02:32:25.020 --> 02:32:30.899
knew would come to his aid if needed.

02:32:28.260 --> 02:32:35.540
He was now at the head of the wealthiest

02:32:30.899 --> 02:32:35.540
and most powerful province of the empire.

02:32:35.700 --> 02:32:41.640
Hannibal and his father's success in

02:32:38.580 --> 02:32:44.760
Spain restored the lifeblood of Carthage,

02:32:41.640 --> 02:32:45.660
and silver once again flowed through the

02:32:44.760 --> 02:32:48.359
empire.

02:32:45.660 --> 02:32:51.060
It's said that just one Spanish mine in

02:32:48.359 --> 02:32:52.859
the region of Baebelo, with its shafts

02:32:51.060 --> 02:32:55.500
running more than two kilometers into

02:32:52.859 --> 02:32:57.720
the mountainside, was producing nearly a

02:32:55.500 --> 02:32:59.640
thousand kilograms of silver each week

02:32:57.720 --> 02:33:02.040
for Hannibal's treasury.

02:32:59.640 --> 02:33:04.740
Analysis shows that the coins being

02:33:02.040 --> 02:33:06.600
minted in Spain at this time were of an

02:33:04.740 --> 02:33:09.060
exceptionally high content of silver,

02:33:06.600 --> 02:33:11.640
while those being minted back in

02:33:09.060 --> 02:33:14.600
Carthage were still watered down with

02:33:11.640 --> 02:33:14.600
cheaper metals.

02:33:15.479 --> 02:33:20.100
All of this meant that Hannibal was

02:33:18.120 --> 02:33:22.680
beginning to feel increasingly confident

02:33:20.100 --> 02:33:25.200
about testing the bounds of what he

02:33:22.680 --> 02:33:28.020
could get away with, both with the Senate

02:33:25.200 --> 02:33:31.399
back in Carthage and with his sworn

02:33:28.020 --> 02:33:31.399
enemy of Rome.

02:33:33.359 --> 02:33:39.840
The Roman poet Silius Italicus gives one

02:33:36.840 --> 02:33:43.260
description of his character.

02:33:39.840 --> 02:33:46.859
He was one, by nature, eager for action,

02:33:43.260 --> 02:33:50.939
yet an oath-breaker, cunning beyond all,

02:33:46.859 --> 02:33:53.580
though of questionable fairness. Armed, he

02:33:50.939 --> 02:33:56.880
was no respecter of the gods; bold to do

02:33:53.580 --> 02:33:59.640
wrong, scorning the virtues of peace, and

02:33:56.880 --> 02:34:03.060
with a thirst for human blood alive in

02:33:59.640 --> 02:34:05.880
his deepest marrow. Above all, in the

02:34:03.060 --> 02:34:09.359
flower of his youth, he longed to erase

02:34:05.880 --> 02:34:13.020
that defeat, a generation's shame, and

02:34:09.359 --> 02:34:15.979
drown their peace treaty deep in the

02:34:13.020 --> 02:34:15.979
Sicilian Sea.

02:34:16.620 --> 02:34:22.020
The location for the flashpoint that

02:34:19.020 --> 02:34:24.540
would spark the Second Punic War was the

02:34:22.020 --> 02:34:27.620
town of Saguntum, just north of what is

02:34:24.540 --> 02:34:31.380
today Valencia in southern Spain.

02:34:27.620 --> 02:34:33.660
Saguntum was a Roman ally, and Rome had

02:34:31.380 --> 02:34:36.600
been watching with concern as Carthage's

02:34:33.660 --> 02:34:39.359
Spanish borders edged ever closer.

02:34:36.600 --> 02:34:41.640
Rome had made it very clear that they

02:34:39.359 --> 02:34:44.580
would not tolerate a Carthaginian attack

02:34:41.640 --> 02:34:47.100
on the city of Saguntum,

02:34:44.580 --> 02:34:48.899
but Hannibal was willing to call their

02:34:47.100 --> 02:34:53.220
bluff.

02:34:48.899 --> 02:34:55.800
In the year 219 BC, at the age of 28, he

02:34:53.220 --> 02:34:57.720
led his army against the city and put it

02:34:55.800 --> 02:35:00.840
under siege.

02:34:57.720 --> 02:35:03.180
The fighting didn't go smoothly; the

02:35:00.840 --> 02:35:05.760
people of Saguntum put up a fierce

02:35:03.180 --> 02:35:07.740
defense from their walls, and Hannibal

02:35:05.760 --> 02:35:10.260
was even wounded in the thigh by a

02:35:07.740 --> 02:35:12.840
javelin, but his move to take the city

02:35:10.260 --> 02:35:14.399
was a clear spit in the eye of the

02:35:12.840 --> 02:35:16.140
Romans.

02:35:14.399 --> 02:35:19.380
When they heard about what was happening,

02:35:16.140 --> 02:35:21.600
Rome dispatched some envoys who turned

02:35:19.380 --> 02:35:23.880
up at Hannibal's siege camp at Saguntum

02:35:21.600 --> 02:35:26.700
and demanded to speak with him.

02:35:23.880 --> 02:35:28.680
He had his man send them away, telling

02:35:26.700 --> 02:35:29.700
them that he was too busy to talk to

02:35:28.680 --> 02:35:32.340
them.

02:35:29.700 --> 02:35:34.680
The Romans must have left seething with

02:35:32.340 --> 02:35:37.319
rage.

02:35:34.680 --> 02:35:39.720
Back in Carthage, news of Hannibal's

02:35:37.319 --> 02:35:43.080
actions were likely met with excitement

02:35:39.720 --> 02:35:45.840
by his supporters and with a frenzy of

02:35:43.080 --> 02:35:48.960
dismay by others.

02:35:45.840 --> 02:35:51.359
One of his great opponents, a man named

02:35:48.960 --> 02:35:53.460
Hanno, is supposed to have delivered a

02:35:51.359 --> 02:35:56.100
blistering speech against him in the

02:35:53.460 --> 02:36:01.399
Carthaginian senate, the words of which

02:35:56.100 --> 02:36:01.399
the later Roman historian Livy imagines.

02:36:01.740 --> 02:36:06.479
As long as any single representative of

02:36:04.319 --> 02:36:09.359
the blood and name of Barca survives,

02:36:06.479 --> 02:36:12.359
our treaty with Rome will never remain

02:36:09.359 --> 02:36:14.640
unimperilled. You have sent to the army, as

02:36:12.359 --> 02:36:16.859
though supplying fuel to fire, a young

02:36:14.640 --> 02:36:19.260
man who is consumed with a passion for

02:36:16.859 --> 02:36:21.840
sovereign power, and who recognizes that

02:36:19.260 --> 02:36:24.540
the only way to it lies in passing his

02:36:21.840 --> 02:36:27.359
life surrounded by armed legions and

02:36:24.540 --> 02:36:29.760
perpetually stirring up fresh wars. It is

02:36:27.359 --> 02:36:32.220
against Carthage that Hannibal is now

02:36:29.760 --> 02:36:34.140
bringing up his towers. It is Carthage

02:36:32.220 --> 02:36:37.140
whose walls he is shaking with his

02:36:34.140 --> 02:36:39.960
battering rams. The ruins of Saguntum

02:36:37.140 --> 02:36:42.120
will fall on our heads, and the war which

02:36:39.960 --> 02:36:45.060
has begun with Saguntum will have to be

02:36:42.120 --> 02:36:47.460
carried on with Rome.

02:36:45.060 --> 02:36:49.680
But Hannibal also had plenty of

02:36:47.460 --> 02:36:52.020
supporters, and even his strongest

02:36:49.680 --> 02:36:54.479
opponents in the senate found themselves

02:36:52.020 --> 02:36:56.880
in something of a bind.

02:36:54.479 --> 02:36:59.280
Many would have likely preferred to have

02:36:56.880 --> 02:37:02.040
Hannibal arrested and his armies given

02:36:59.280 --> 02:37:05.160
to some more predictable general, but in

02:37:02.040 --> 02:37:07.920
truth, they had no idea how to do this.

02:37:05.160 --> 02:37:10.260
Hannibalís soldiers were loyal to him, and

02:37:07.920 --> 02:37:13.319
any move against him would cause a civil

02:37:10.260 --> 02:37:15.720
war that could lose Carthage all of the

02:37:13.319 --> 02:37:19.020
wealthy Spanish provinces on which their

02:37:15.720 --> 02:37:21.540
entire economy now rested.

02:37:19.020 --> 02:37:24.479
But the Romans, too, were paralyzed by

02:37:21.540 --> 02:37:27.600
indecision. For the eight months of the

02:37:24.479 --> 02:37:29.660
siege of Saguntum, Rome did nothing but

02:37:27.600 --> 02:37:33.300
complain.

02:37:29.660 --> 02:37:35.939
When Hannibal finally took the city, the

02:37:33.300 --> 02:37:40.080
Romans sent a delegation of ambassadors

02:37:35.939 --> 02:37:42.600
to Africa to demand an explanation.

02:37:40.080 --> 02:37:46.399
The clouds of war were once again

02:37:42.600 --> 02:37:46.399
gathering over the sea.

02:37:46.560 --> 02:37:52.439
When these men arrived, they spoke before

02:37:49.740 --> 02:37:54.060
the Carthaginian senate and demanded to

02:37:52.439 --> 02:37:56.280
know whether Hannibal's capture of

02:37:54.060 --> 02:37:59.220
Saguntum was the official policy of

02:37:56.280 --> 02:38:00.479
Carthage or just the work of one rogue

02:37:59.220 --> 02:38:03.060
general.

02:38:00.479 --> 02:38:05.760
If he had acted alone, they demanded that

02:38:03.060 --> 02:38:09.060
Hannibal be arrested and handed over for

02:38:05.760 --> 02:38:12.000
punishment. If Carthage failed to do that,

02:38:09.060 --> 02:38:14.640
Rome would declare war.

02:38:12.000 --> 02:38:17.399
The historian Appian described this

02:38:14.640 --> 02:38:19.280
moment as the Carthaginian senate made

02:38:17.399 --> 02:38:21.899
its choice.

02:38:19.280 --> 02:38:23.580
The Romans now sent ambassadors to

02:38:21.899 --> 02:38:25.380
Carthage to demand that Hannibal should

02:38:23.580 --> 02:38:27.960
be delivered up to them as a violator of

02:38:25.380 --> 02:38:30.899
the treaty. If they would not give him up,

02:38:27.960 --> 02:38:33.180
war was to be declared forthwith.

02:38:30.899 --> 02:38:36.380
The chief of the embassy pointed to the

02:38:33.180 --> 02:38:39.359
fold of his toga and, smiling, said, ëHere,

02:38:36.380 --> 02:38:42.420
Carthaginians, I bring you peace or war.

02:38:39.359 --> 02:38:44.880
You may take whichever you choose.í The

02:38:42.420 --> 02:38:46.260
latter replied, ëYou may give us whichever

02:38:44.880 --> 02:38:48.600
you like.í

02:38:46.260 --> 02:38:52.460
When the Romans offered war, they all

02:38:48.600 --> 02:38:56.520
cried out, ëWe accept it.í

02:38:52.460 --> 02:38:59.100
The poet Silius Italicus, writing some

02:38:56.520 --> 02:39:02.100
centuries after the conflict, gives an

02:38:59.100 --> 02:39:05.340
even more florid rendition.

02:39:02.100 --> 02:39:08.220
He gestured to them that he carried war

02:39:05.340 --> 02:39:11.340
and peace in his hands, demanding they

02:39:08.220 --> 02:39:14.100
choose, and when the senators refused to

02:39:11.340 --> 02:39:16.680
accept either, he replied, shaking his

02:39:14.100 --> 02:39:20.520
robes as if pouring out battle and ruin

02:39:16.680 --> 02:39:24.979
from his arms; ëTake war, unhappy Libya,

02:39:20.520 --> 02:39:24.979
with an outcome like the first.í

02:39:25.140 --> 02:39:30.720
The Roman historian Livy describes the

02:39:28.020 --> 02:39:32.100
conflict that ensued in the following

02:39:30.720 --> 02:39:34.920
terms.

02:39:32.100 --> 02:39:38.580
The most memorable of all wars ever

02:39:34.920 --> 02:39:41.100
waged, the war that is, which, under the

02:39:38.580 --> 02:39:43.920
leadership of Hannibal, the Carthaginians

02:39:41.100 --> 02:39:45.899
waged with the Roman people, for neither

02:39:43.920 --> 02:39:48.060
have states or nations met in arms

02:39:45.899 --> 02:39:50.819
possessed of ample resources,

02:39:48.060 --> 02:39:53.840
nor was their own might and power ever

02:39:50.819 --> 02:39:53.840
so great.

02:39:54.600 --> 02:40:00.180
Growing up among the fires of civil war,

02:39:57.479 --> 02:40:03.300
Hannibal had learned never to let your

02:40:00.180 --> 02:40:05.880
homeland become a battlefield. He knew

02:40:03.300 --> 02:40:08.160
that if he waited in Spain, his lands

02:40:05.880 --> 02:40:11.939
would soon become host to a Roman

02:40:08.160 --> 02:40:14.700
invasion force. His fields would burn. His

02:40:11.939 --> 02:40:16.319
silver mines would dry up, and his people

02:40:14.700 --> 02:40:19.800
would suffer.

02:40:16.319 --> 02:40:22.100
So, he decided to take his war to

02:40:19.800 --> 02:40:22.100
Rome.

02:40:22.740 --> 02:40:28.140
He withdrew to his capital of New

02:40:25.200 --> 02:40:31.740
Carthage for the winter, to prepare and

02:40:28.140 --> 02:40:35.399
plan, and here, Livy describes him giving

02:40:31.740 --> 02:40:37.859
the following speech to his soldiers.

02:40:35.399 --> 02:40:40.319
You are on the eve of an expedition that

02:40:37.859 --> 02:40:42.120
will carry you far afield, and it is

02:40:40.319 --> 02:40:45.000
uncertain when you will see again your

02:40:42.120 --> 02:40:48.060
homes. With the first signs of spring,

02:40:45.000 --> 02:40:50.220
with Heavenís good help, we may begin a

02:40:48.060 --> 02:40:52.080
war that shall bring us vast renown and

02:40:50.220 --> 02:40:55.260
treasure.

02:40:52.080 --> 02:40:58.979
The journey from New Carthage to Italy

02:40:55.260 --> 02:41:01.380
was one of about 1,500 kilometers, so

02:40:58.979 --> 02:41:03.720
Hannibal knew that a long and dangerous

02:41:01.380 --> 02:41:05.040
march awaited him once the spring

02:41:03.720 --> 02:41:07.500
arrived,

02:41:05.040 --> 02:41:10.260
and at the end of this journey, a

02:41:07.500 --> 02:41:12.660
monumental problem loomed ahead of him.

02:41:10.260 --> 02:41:15.840
That's because the geography of the

02:41:12.660 --> 02:41:18.800
Italian Peninsula made it something of a

02:41:15.840 --> 02:41:18.800
natural fortress.

02:41:19.340 --> 02:41:24.840
Beginning in the Cretaceous Period

02:41:21.840 --> 02:41:26.760
around 100 million years ago, the steady

02:41:24.840 --> 02:41:29.460
northward movement of the African

02:41:26.760 --> 02:41:32.100
continental plate crushing beneath the

02:41:29.460 --> 02:41:35.399
Eurasian plate in the region of Sicily

02:41:32.100 --> 02:41:38.640
had caused the Earth's crust to bend and

02:41:35.399 --> 02:41:41.580
pleat, driving up a dramatic series of

02:41:38.640 --> 02:41:44.340
mountains that form a sheer wall between

02:41:41.580 --> 02:41:47.939
the Italian Peninsula and Celtic Western

02:41:44.340 --> 02:41:51.479
Europe, which the Romans called Gaul.

02:41:47.939 --> 02:41:54.000
These mountains, known as the Alps, can

02:41:51.479 --> 02:41:57.000
tower up to five kilometers from sea

02:41:54.000 --> 02:42:00.540
level, with permanent snow-capped peaks

02:41:57.000 --> 02:42:03.120
choked with icy glaciers, and with only a

02:42:00.540 --> 02:42:06.120
few narrow crossing points.

02:42:03.120 --> 02:42:08.819
The Roman writer Ammianus Marcellinus

02:42:06.120 --> 02:42:11.300
describes the appearance of the Alps at

02:42:08.819 --> 02:42:11.300
this time.

02:42:11.399 --> 02:42:16.439
This country of Gaul, because of its

02:42:14.160 --> 02:42:19.439
lofty chains of mountains always covered

02:42:16.439 --> 02:42:21.359
with formidable snows, was formerly all

02:42:19.439 --> 02:42:23.460
but unknown to the inhabitants of the

02:42:21.359 --> 02:42:26.399
rest of the globe, except where it

02:42:23.460 --> 02:42:28.640
borders on the coast; and mountain

02:42:26.399 --> 02:42:31.680
bulwarks enclose it on every side,

02:42:28.640 --> 02:42:33.899
surrounding it naturally, as if by the

02:42:31.680 --> 02:42:36.720
art of man.

02:42:33.899 --> 02:42:39.060
The most commonly-used roads were the

02:42:36.720 --> 02:42:41.700
ones that went around this natural wall,

02:42:39.060 --> 02:42:44.100
the narrow corridor that follows the

02:42:41.700 --> 02:42:46.140
coastline past what is now the French

02:42:44.100 --> 02:42:48.540
port town of Nice.

02:42:46.140 --> 02:42:51.660
But as the only way into and out of

02:42:48.540 --> 02:42:54.720
Italy, these roads were heavily defended

02:42:51.660 --> 02:42:56.580
and lined with forts stacked with Roman

02:42:54.720 --> 02:42:59.160
legionaries.

02:42:56.580 --> 02:43:01.560
Here, the Romans could have staged a

02:42:59.160 --> 02:43:04.380
fearsome defense.

02:43:01.560 --> 02:43:06.720
Faced with this problem, Hannibal would

02:43:04.380 --> 02:43:09.000
need a daring solution,

02:43:06.720 --> 02:43:11.280
and it's here that those stories may

02:43:09.000 --> 02:43:14.100
have come back to him, stories he must

02:43:11.280 --> 02:43:17.100
have heard as a child of the great hero

02:43:14.100 --> 02:43:20.460
Hercules leading his herd of cattle

02:43:17.100 --> 02:43:22.319
directly over the Alps.

02:43:20.460 --> 02:43:24.600
The Romans believed that it was

02:43:22.319 --> 02:43:27.960
impossible to cross the Alps with an

02:43:24.600 --> 02:43:31.620
army weighed down with supplies, with

02:43:27.960 --> 02:43:32.939
horses, oxen, and with a herd of 37

02:43:31.620 --> 02:43:35.640
elephants.

02:43:32.939 --> 02:43:38.640
It would be madness to even attempt it,

02:43:35.640 --> 02:43:43.220
and for that reason, it was the last

02:43:38.640 --> 02:43:43.220
thing they would ever have expected.

02:43:49.800 --> 02:43:55.260
When spring came and the Romans heard of

02:43:52.920 --> 02:43:58.080
the Carthaginian army beginning its

02:43:55.260 --> 02:44:00.979
march, they sent ambassadors along the

02:43:58.080 --> 02:44:04.140
coastal roads and into what they called

02:44:00.979 --> 02:44:06.660
Transalpine Gaul. There were Celtic

02:44:04.140 --> 02:44:08.939
tribes of Gauls living on both the

02:44:06.660 --> 02:44:11.580
Italian and the northern side of the

02:44:08.939 --> 02:44:15.180
Alps, and so, the Romans used the Latin

02:44:11.580 --> 02:44:17.580
word cis, meaning ëon this sideí and trans,

02:44:15.180 --> 02:44:20.160
meaning ëon the other sideí, to

02:44:17.580 --> 02:44:22.439
differentiate between them. The Roman

02:44:20.160 --> 02:44:25.620
ambassadors approached the leaders of

02:44:22.439 --> 02:44:28.140
these Transalpine Gauls, and informed

02:44:25.620 --> 02:44:30.660
them of the Carthaginian army then

02:44:28.140 --> 02:44:33.420
making its way towards them.

02:44:30.660 --> 02:44:36.300
They asked these Gauls to bar the way

02:44:33.420 --> 02:44:38.580
to Hannibal and his troops, but they

02:44:36.300 --> 02:44:42.660
didn't get the reception they'd hoped

02:44:38.580 --> 02:44:45.540
for, as Livy describes.

02:44:42.660 --> 02:44:47.939
When the envoys, boasting of the renown

02:44:45.540 --> 02:44:50.280
and valor of the Roman people and the

02:44:47.939 --> 02:44:52.260
extent of their dominion, requested the

02:44:50.280 --> 02:44:54.300
Gauls to deny the Phoenician a passage

02:44:52.260 --> 02:44:55.800
through their lands and cities, if he

02:44:54.300 --> 02:44:59.040
should attempt to carry the war into

02:44:55.800 --> 02:45:01.680
Italy, it is said that they burst out

02:44:59.040 --> 02:45:03.540
into such peals of laughter that the

02:45:01.680 --> 02:45:05.760
magistrates and elders could scarce

02:45:03.540 --> 02:45:08.520
reduce the younger men to order.

02:45:05.760 --> 02:45:10.979
So stupid and impudent a thing, it seemed,

02:45:08.520 --> 02:45:13.560
to propose that the Gauls should bring

02:45:10.979 --> 02:45:16.140
down the war on their own heads and

02:45:13.560 --> 02:45:19.040
offer their own fields to be pillaged in

02:45:16.140 --> 02:45:19.040
place of other men's.

02:45:19.200 --> 02:45:25.020
This was perhaps the first sign that

02:45:22.140 --> 02:45:28.200
things weren't going to go as the Romans

02:45:25.020 --> 02:45:30.899
might have wished.

02:45:28.200 --> 02:45:33.600
But on his march south, Hannibal did

02:45:30.899 --> 02:45:36.479
encounter significant resistance from

02:45:33.600 --> 02:45:38.399
local peoples who didn't welcome the

02:45:36.479 --> 02:45:41.100
presence of his army,

02:45:38.399 --> 02:45:44.040
and in France, it was only through the

02:45:41.100 --> 02:45:48.680
excessive distribution of gifts that the

02:45:44.040 --> 02:45:48.680
Gauls allowed him and his men to pass.

02:45:48.780 --> 02:45:57.080
The first true obstacle was the river

02:45:51.720 --> 02:45:57.080
Rhone, one of France's largest rivers.

02:45:57.240 --> 02:46:03.420
Here, Hannibal's army crossed with

02:46:00.000 --> 02:46:05.819
difficulty, building rafts to ferry his

02:46:03.420 --> 02:46:08.460
men and equipment across,

02:46:05.819 --> 02:46:10.380
but the elephants here posed a

02:46:08.460 --> 02:46:13.200
significant challenge.

02:46:10.380 --> 02:46:15.720
These animals were terrified of water,

02:46:13.200 --> 02:46:18.660
and so, to get them across, the

02:46:15.720 --> 02:46:20.880
Carthaginians built enormous rafts built

02:46:18.660 --> 02:46:23.100
from whole tree trunks and covered them

02:46:20.880 --> 02:46:24.840
with earth and turf so that the

02:46:23.100 --> 02:46:27.420
elephants would believe they were still

02:46:24.840 --> 02:46:30.060
standing on dry land.

02:46:27.420 --> 02:46:33.060
In that way, they were able to coax two

02:46:30.060 --> 02:46:34.080
of the females onto the rafts and across

02:46:33.060 --> 02:46:36.780
the river,

02:46:34.080 --> 02:46:39.600
and from there, the rest of the herd were

02:46:36.780 --> 02:46:42.120
ferried across.

02:46:39.600 --> 02:46:45.420
Hannibal then followed the river road

02:46:42.120 --> 02:46:47.580
north and found a tribe of Gauls who

02:46:45.420 --> 02:46:49.080
agreed to help him achieve his

02:46:47.580 --> 02:46:52.319
impossible plan;

02:46:49.080 --> 02:46:54.359
to cross the vast natural barrier of the

02:46:52.319 --> 02:46:57.060
Alps.

02:46:54.359 --> 02:46:59.880
These Gauls gave Hannibal and his men

02:46:57.060 --> 02:47:02.880
supplies and warm clothing for the

02:46:59.880 --> 02:47:04.680
mountain crossing, but the task ahead was

02:47:02.880 --> 02:47:08.340
still staggering.

02:47:04.680 --> 02:47:10.920
By this time, it was October. Winter was

02:47:08.340 --> 02:47:14.040
closing in, and the passes of the Alps

02:47:10.920 --> 02:47:16.500
were choked with ice and snow.

02:47:14.040 --> 02:47:19.560
The later Roman writer Ammianus

02:47:16.500 --> 02:47:22.560
Marcellinus writes one account of these

02:47:19.560 --> 02:47:25.439
treacherous alpine passes.

02:47:22.560 --> 02:47:27.660
In these Alps, there rises a lofty

02:47:25.439 --> 02:47:29.220
ridge which scarcely anyone can cross

02:47:27.660 --> 02:47:32.220
without danger,

02:47:29.220 --> 02:47:34.260
for as one comes from Gaul, it falls off

02:47:32.220 --> 02:47:36.359
with sheer incline,

02:47:34.260 --> 02:47:39.120
terrible to look upon because of

02:47:36.359 --> 02:47:41.640
overhanging cliffs on either side;

02:47:39.120 --> 02:47:44.160
then over precipitous ravines on either

02:47:41.640 --> 02:47:46.800
side and chasms rendered treacherous

02:47:44.160 --> 02:47:49.140
through the accumulation of ice, men and

02:47:46.800 --> 02:47:52.380
animals descending with hesitating steps

02:47:49.140 --> 02:47:56.220
slide forward, and wagons as well.

02:47:52.380 --> 02:47:58.020
In winter, the ground, caked with ice, and

02:47:56.220 --> 02:48:00.899
as if it were polished and therefore

02:47:58.020 --> 02:48:03.840
slippery, drives men headlong in their

02:48:00.899 --> 02:48:06.840
gait, and the spreading valleys, made

02:48:03.840 --> 02:48:09.319
treacherous by ice, sometimes swallow up

02:48:06.840 --> 02:48:09.319
the traveler.

02:48:10.319 --> 02:48:15.600
The march to the top of the pass took

02:48:12.780 --> 02:48:18.479
nine days, and we can only imagine the

02:48:15.600 --> 02:48:21.479
hardship that these men, their horses and

02:48:18.479 --> 02:48:23.100
oxen, and elephants all endured during

02:48:21.479 --> 02:48:25.439
those days,

02:48:23.100 --> 02:48:26.520
but on the ninth day, they reached the

02:48:25.439 --> 02:48:29.100
top,

02:48:26.520 --> 02:48:32.280
and now gazed down through the Alpine

02:48:29.100 --> 02:48:34.859
pass into the green lowlands of Italy

02:48:32.280 --> 02:48:37.080
stretching out below them.

02:48:34.859 --> 02:48:39.120
But the descent from the mountains would

02:48:37.080 --> 02:48:40.439
prove to be even more treacherous than

02:48:39.120 --> 02:48:42.780
the climb.

02:48:40.439 --> 02:48:45.240
On their way down, they found that a

02:48:42.780 --> 02:48:47.819
recent landslide had turned what was

02:48:45.240 --> 02:48:49.800
already a difficult road into an

02:48:47.819 --> 02:48:52.080
unpassable precipice.

02:48:49.800 --> 02:48:54.899
The historian Livy describes the

02:48:52.080 --> 02:48:57.540
obstacle that faced them.

02:48:54.899 --> 02:49:00.600
The result was a horrible struggle, the

02:48:57.540 --> 02:49:02.819
ice affording no foothold in any case, at

02:49:00.600 --> 02:49:05.040
least of all on a steep slope.

02:49:02.819 --> 02:49:07.800
When a man tried by hands or knees to

02:49:05.040 --> 02:49:09.840
get on his feet again, even those useless

02:49:07.800 --> 02:49:11.160
supports slipped from under him and let

02:49:09.840 --> 02:49:13.260
him down.

02:49:11.160 --> 02:49:15.240
There were no stumps or roots anywhere

02:49:13.260 --> 02:49:18.720
to afford a purchase to either hand or

02:49:15.240 --> 02:49:21.120
foot; in short, there was nothing for it

02:49:18.720 --> 02:49:24.560
but to roll and slither on the smooth

02:49:21.120 --> 02:49:24.560
ice and melting snow.

02:49:25.020 --> 02:49:31.680
The decision was made to cut a stepped

02:49:28.560 --> 02:49:34.380
path into this sheer wall, and the episode

02:49:31.680 --> 02:49:36.899
has become one of the most famous in the

02:49:34.380 --> 02:49:39.899
mythical retelling of these events that

02:49:36.899 --> 02:49:42.540
would take place over the next centuries.

02:49:39.899 --> 02:49:45.660
The story goes that Hannibal ordered his

02:49:42.540 --> 02:49:47.880
men to gather large amounts of wood and

02:49:45.660 --> 02:49:50.040
build a great fire against the rock of

02:49:47.880 --> 02:49:52.979
the precipice.

02:49:50.040 --> 02:49:56.280
As the fire blazed and the flames licked

02:49:52.979 --> 02:49:58.620
at the icy stone, the rock heated up,

02:49:56.280 --> 02:50:01.140
then the soldiers would pour their

02:49:58.620 --> 02:50:03.840
rations of sour wine against the heated

02:50:01.140 --> 02:50:07.680
rock, causing its temperature to rapidly

02:50:03.840 --> 02:50:10.200
drop and the rock to crack. With iron

02:50:07.680 --> 02:50:13.200
tools, they then worked away at these

02:50:10.200 --> 02:50:16.680
fissures until after four days of labor,

02:50:13.200 --> 02:50:19.260
steps were cut into the rock, as Livy

02:50:16.680 --> 02:50:21.420
recounts.

02:50:19.260 --> 02:50:23.939
After thus heating the crag with fire,

02:50:21.420 --> 02:50:26.100
they opened a way in it with iron tools

02:50:23.939 --> 02:50:28.740
and relieved the steepness of the slope

02:50:26.100 --> 02:50:30.960
with zigzags of an easy gradient,

02:50:28.740 --> 02:50:33.420
so that not only the baggage animals but

02:50:30.960 --> 02:50:36.000
even the elephants could be led down.

02:50:33.420 --> 02:50:37.439
Four days were consumed at the cliff, and

02:50:36.000 --> 02:50:38.460
the animals nearly perished of

02:50:37.439 --> 02:50:40.500
starvation,

02:50:38.460 --> 02:50:43.560
for the mountaintops are all

02:50:40.500 --> 02:50:47.600
practically bare, and such grass as does

02:50:43.560 --> 02:50:47.600
grow is buried under snow.

02:50:48.180 --> 02:50:53.280
Whether this episode unfolded quite in

02:50:50.819 --> 02:50:55.859
this manner or not, from the perspective

02:50:53.280 --> 02:50:59.340
of Hannibal's followers, the purpose of

02:50:55.859 --> 02:51:02.280
telling this story was clear; here was a

02:50:59.340 --> 02:51:04.080
new Hercules, it said, a man who has

02:51:02.280 --> 02:51:06.899
crossed the Alps with his herd of

02:51:04.080 --> 02:51:10.380
elephants, a man who achieves great

02:51:06.899 --> 02:51:13.080
labors wherever he goes, a man for whom

02:51:10.380 --> 02:51:16.100
the very rock of the mountain presents

02:51:13.080 --> 02:51:16.100
no obstacle.

02:51:16.920 --> 02:51:22.080
Climbing down into the foothills, the men

02:51:19.800 --> 02:51:24.960
must have felt the lowland warmth wash

02:51:22.080 --> 02:51:28.020
over their skin for the first time with

02:51:24.960 --> 02:51:30.740
a sense of enormous relief, as Livy

02:51:28.020 --> 02:51:30.740
recounts.

02:51:30.780 --> 02:51:35.580
Lower down one comes to valleys and

02:51:33.060 --> 02:51:37.740
sunny slopes and rivulets, and near them

02:51:35.580 --> 02:51:40.319
woods and places that begin to be fitted

02:51:37.740 --> 02:51:42.479
for man's habitation. There the beasts

02:51:40.319 --> 02:51:45.240
were turned out to graze, and the men,

02:51:42.479 --> 02:51:48.020
exhausted with toiling at the road, were

02:51:45.240 --> 02:51:48.020
allowed to rest.

02:51:48.780 --> 02:51:53.640
But the audacity of Hannibal's plan had

02:51:52.200 --> 02:51:56.520
come at a cost,

02:51:53.640 --> 02:51:59.160
as Polybius writes.

02:51:56.520 --> 02:52:02.580
When Hannibal crossed the Rhone, he had

02:51:59.160 --> 02:52:05.819
38,000 infantry and more than 8,000

02:52:02.580 --> 02:52:09.420
cavalry. He lost nearly half in the pass;

02:52:05.819 --> 02:52:11.899
while the survivors had, by these long

02:52:09.420 --> 02:52:16.380
continued sufferings, become almost

02:52:11.899 --> 02:52:19.620
savage in look and general appearance.

02:52:16.380 --> 02:52:22.439
Nevertheless, Hannibal and his men now

02:52:19.620 --> 02:52:24.240
stood and looked out over the lands of

02:52:22.439 --> 02:52:27.240
Italy below.

02:52:24.240 --> 02:52:29.660
They had caught the Romans completely by

02:52:27.240 --> 02:52:29.660
surprise.

02:52:32.600 --> 02:52:38.939
At the outbreak of war with Carthage,

02:52:35.840 --> 02:52:40.260
Rome knew that Hannibal's army was on

02:52:38.939 --> 02:52:42.779
the move.

02:52:40.260 --> 02:52:45.180
They sent out messengers to find out any

02:52:42.779 --> 02:52:48.120
word about the location of his forces,

02:52:45.180 --> 02:52:49.920
but recently they had been coming back

02:52:48.120 --> 02:52:52.260
empty-handed.

02:52:49.920 --> 02:52:55.319
After crossing the river Rhone, the

02:52:52.260 --> 02:52:59.100
Carthaginian general had disappeared.

02:52:55.319 --> 02:53:01.260
He wasn't in Gaul. He wasn't in Spain. For

02:52:59.100 --> 02:53:05.180
the Romans, the situation must have been

02:53:01.260 --> 02:53:08.100
puzzling and a little concerning.

02:53:05.180 --> 02:53:11.160
When news came to them of what Hannibal

02:53:08.100 --> 02:53:12.420
had done, the first note of panic began

02:53:11.160 --> 02:53:15.359
to set in.

02:53:12.420 --> 02:53:17.700
Polybius recounted the reaction of one

02:53:15.359 --> 02:53:20.340
Roman general.

02:53:17.700 --> 02:53:23.100
Publius had not expected that Hannibal would

02:53:20.340 --> 02:53:25.080
even attempt the passage of the Alps, or

02:53:23.100 --> 02:53:28.319
if he did attempt it, that he could

02:53:25.080 --> 02:53:30.420
escape utter destruction.

02:53:28.319 --> 02:53:32.880
He was immensely astonished at his courage

02:53:30.420 --> 02:53:35.279
and adventurous daring when he heard that he

02:53:32.880 --> 02:53:37.319
had not only got safe across, but was

02:53:35.279 --> 02:53:39.000
actually besieging certain towns in

02:53:37.319 --> 02:53:42.000
Italy.

02:53:39.000 --> 02:53:44.220
The Roman government was typically slow-

02:53:42.000 --> 02:53:47.220
-moving, and the speed of Hannibal's

02:53:44.220 --> 02:53:49.740
attack had stunned them.

02:53:47.220 --> 02:53:52.260
Scarcely had the last rumor about the

02:53:49.740 --> 02:53:55.439
taking of Saguntum by the Carthaginians

02:53:52.260 --> 02:53:57.960
ceased to attract attention, then news came

02:53:55.439 --> 02:53:59.279
that Hannibal had arrived in Italy with

02:53:57.960 --> 02:54:01.500
his army.

02:53:59.279 --> 02:54:03.960
What made matters worse was that

02:54:01.500 --> 02:54:06.779
Hannibal was now recruiting allies from

02:54:03.960 --> 02:54:09.300
the Cisalpine Gauls in the foothills of

02:54:06.779 --> 02:54:12.000
the Alps, Celtic tribes on the Italian

02:54:09.300 --> 02:54:14.819
side of the mountains who had fought with

02:54:12.000 --> 02:54:18.359
the Romans before.

02:54:14.819 --> 02:54:20.520
The Roman senate went into a panic. They

02:54:18.359 --> 02:54:22.920
brought up reinforcements from Sicily,

02:54:20.520 --> 02:54:25.620
from an army that at that moment had

02:54:22.920 --> 02:54:28.920
been preparing to invade Africa.

02:54:25.620 --> 02:54:31.620
The general Sempronius Longus led this

02:54:28.920 --> 02:54:34.740
army of more than 40,000 to intercept

02:54:31.620 --> 02:54:37.560
Hannibal's forces in northern Italy. They

02:54:34.740 --> 02:54:40.020
met at the battle of Trebia in December

02:54:37.560 --> 02:54:42.600
of the year 218 BC.

02:54:40.020 --> 02:54:45.300
Here, Hannibal's powerful and

02:54:42.600 --> 02:54:48.359
determined forces utterly smashed the

02:54:45.300 --> 02:54:50.460
Roman army, killing at least 20,000

02:54:48.359 --> 02:54:53.340
soldiers.

02:54:50.460 --> 02:54:56.100
When news of this defeat reached Rome,

02:54:53.340 --> 02:54:57.600
the mood in the senate must have been

02:54:56.100 --> 02:55:00.600
bleak.

02:54:57.600 --> 02:55:03.359
Hannibal marched south and crossed the

02:55:00.600 --> 02:55:05.520
Apennine mountains that run down the

02:55:03.359 --> 02:55:07.500
center of Italy, and crushed another

02:55:05.520 --> 02:55:11.060
Roman army on the shore of Lake

02:55:07.500 --> 02:55:14.880
Trasimene, killing another 15,000 Romans

02:55:11.060 --> 02:55:17.399
and capturing 10,000 prisoners.

02:55:14.880 --> 02:55:20.040
From there, his march seemed to be

02:55:17.399 --> 02:55:23.160
unstoppable.

02:55:20.040 --> 02:55:26.040
Hannibal would rampage across Italy for

02:55:23.160 --> 02:55:28.920
a total of fifteen years.

02:55:26.040 --> 02:55:31.800
Chastened by their defeats, the Romans

02:55:28.920 --> 02:55:34.859
now avoided any battles with him, trying

02:55:31.800 --> 02:55:36.479
instead to suffocate his army and cut

02:55:34.859 --> 02:55:39.120
off his supplies.

02:55:36.479 --> 02:55:41.819
They even resorted to a scorched-earth

02:55:39.120 --> 02:55:44.880
campaign in which they burned their own

02:55:41.819 --> 02:55:47.640
countryside in a desperate attempt to

02:55:44.880 --> 02:55:50.359
starve Hannibal's troops.

02:55:47.640 --> 02:55:52.740
Hannibal's strategy was to march south,

02:55:50.359 --> 02:55:55.560
hoping that the conquered Greek cities

02:55:52.740 --> 02:55:57.779
of southern Italy would greet him as a

02:55:55.560 --> 02:56:00.899
liberator and throw off the rule of

02:55:57.779 --> 02:56:03.960
their Roman masters, but the journey was

02:56:00.899 --> 02:56:06.660
hard. On his way, all but the largest of

02:56:03.960 --> 02:56:09.120
his elephants would die as a result of

02:56:06.660 --> 02:56:10.920
the harsh Italian winter, and while

02:56:09.120 --> 02:56:13.560
riding through the marshes of central

02:56:10.920 --> 02:56:16.200
Italy, Hannibal himself caught an

02:56:13.560 --> 02:56:18.180
infection that caused the loss of one of

02:56:16.200 --> 02:56:20.939
his eyes.

02:56:18.180 --> 02:56:23.640
When he reached southern Italy, he seized

02:56:20.939 --> 02:56:26.460
a vast supply depot at the town of Cannae,

02:56:23.640 --> 02:56:28.439
and the Roman senate realized their

02:56:26.460 --> 02:56:30.359
strategy of suffocating him wouldn't

02:56:28.439 --> 02:56:33.180
work.

02:56:30.359 --> 02:56:37.140
They ordered a vast army to be drawn up,

02:56:33.180 --> 02:56:39.899
86,000 soldiers, the largest that had

02:56:37.140 --> 02:56:42.240
ever been raised in Roman history, and

02:56:39.899 --> 02:56:45.120
with this force, they sent the best and

02:56:42.240 --> 02:56:48.720
brightest of Roman society to march

02:56:45.120 --> 02:56:51.420
south to meet Hannibal at Cannae.

02:56:48.720 --> 02:56:53.880
Hannibal, now frustrated with these

02:56:51.420 --> 02:56:56.460
months without a battle, was all too

02:56:53.880 --> 02:56:59.520
eager to accept.

02:56:56.460 --> 02:57:02.939
Once again, the Roman army was utterly

02:56:59.520 --> 02:57:05.880
smashed, and the defeat was so total that

02:57:02.939 --> 02:57:07.920
even high members of Roman society were

02:57:05.880 --> 02:57:11.340
slaughtered on the battlefield.

02:57:07.920 --> 02:57:13.520
Livy describes the aftermath.

02:57:11.340 --> 02:57:19.260
It is said that 45,500

02:57:13.520 --> 02:57:21.420
foot and 2,700 horse was slain, in an

02:57:19.260 --> 02:57:22.439
almost equal proportion of citizens and

02:57:21.420 --> 02:57:25.020
allies.

02:57:22.439 --> 02:57:29.580
In the number were the quaestors of both

02:57:25.020 --> 02:57:32.939
consuls and 29 military tribunes, some

02:57:29.580 --> 02:57:35.520
of consular rank, some of praetorian; and

02:57:32.939 --> 02:57:37.500
besides these, 80 senators, all men who had

02:57:35.520 --> 02:57:38.939
held offices which would have given

02:57:37.500 --> 02:57:41.220
them the right to be elected to the

02:57:38.939 --> 02:57:43.740
senate, but had volunteered to serve as

02:57:41.220 --> 02:57:45.600
soldiers in the legions. The prisoners

02:57:43.740 --> 02:57:48.300
taken in this battle are said to have

02:57:45.600 --> 02:57:51.600
numbered 3,000 foot soldiers

02:57:48.300 --> 02:57:54.180
and 1,500 horsemen.

02:57:51.600 --> 02:57:59.540
When news of this staggering defeat

02:57:54.180 --> 02:57:59.540
reached Rome, the city went into a panic.

02:57:59.939 --> 02:58:05.760
The people of Rome began seeing evil

02:58:02.640 --> 02:58:08.520
omens and portents everywhere. One

02:58:05.760 --> 02:58:11.040
senator was dispatched to Greece to

02:58:08.520 --> 02:58:13.800
consult the oracle at Delphi,

02:58:11.040 --> 02:58:17.040
and as the Carthaginians had once done

02:58:13.800 --> 02:58:19.740
under threat by Agathocles, the Romans

02:58:17.040 --> 02:58:23.580
resorted to rituals of human sacrifice

02:58:19.740 --> 02:58:26.160
to appease their angry gods, as Livy

02:58:23.580 --> 02:58:29.160
describes.

02:58:26.160 --> 02:58:32.580
By the direction of the Books of Fate,

02:58:29.160 --> 02:58:34.920
some unusual sacrifices were offered;

02:58:32.580 --> 02:58:36.720
amongst others, a Gaulish man and woman

02:58:34.920 --> 02:58:39.420
and a Greek man and woman were buried

02:58:36.720 --> 02:58:42.180
alive in the cattle market, in a place

02:58:39.420 --> 02:58:44.220
walled in with stone, which even before

02:58:42.180 --> 02:58:45.359
this time had been defiled with human

02:58:44.220 --> 02:58:47.939
victims,

02:58:45.359 --> 02:58:50.180
a sacrifice wholly alien to the Roman

02:58:47.939 --> 02:58:50.180
spirit.

02:58:50.760 --> 02:58:56.340
To raise a new army, the Romans reduced

02:58:54.120 --> 02:58:59.520
the age of boys that were allowed to

02:58:56.340 --> 02:59:02.220
serve in the military to 17, and began

02:58:59.520 --> 02:59:04.859
enlisting criminals, those with crushing

02:59:02.220 --> 02:59:08.399
debts, and even slaves.

02:59:04.859 --> 02:59:11.460
But their situation looked bleak.

02:59:08.399 --> 02:59:14.040
After the battle of Cannae, many of the old

02:59:11.460 --> 02:59:17.420
Greek cities of southern Italy began to

02:59:14.040 --> 02:59:19.740
join Hannibal and rebel against Rome.

02:59:17.420 --> 02:59:23.640
Sicily looked like it could break free,

02:59:19.740 --> 02:59:26.939
too, and for the next 11 years, war would

02:59:23.640 --> 02:59:30.779
rage all over southern Italy.

02:59:26.939 --> 02:59:34.080
In the year 211 BC, Hannibal even marched

02:59:30.779 --> 02:59:35.279
against Rome itself, causing great panic

02:59:34.080 --> 02:59:38.399
in the city,

02:59:35.279 --> 02:59:41.760
but like the Greek king Pyrrhus before him,

02:59:38.399 --> 02:59:45.600
Hannibal saw no hope of breaching the

02:59:41.760 --> 02:59:48.240
city's imposing Servian walls.

02:59:45.600 --> 02:59:51.060
The Carthaginian senate made several

02:59:48.240 --> 02:59:53.880
attempts to open up a new front in this

02:59:51.060 --> 02:59:56.939
war and capitalize on Hannibal's

02:59:53.880 --> 02:59:59.520
stunning success. They sent armies into

02:59:56.939 --> 03:00:01.859
northern Italy and Sicily, hoping to

02:59:59.520 --> 03:00:05.279
regain some of their former territories,

03:00:01.859 --> 03:00:08.220
but none of their other generals had the

03:00:05.279 --> 03:00:11.340
same ability, and these attempts all

03:00:08.220 --> 03:00:14.520
ended in defeat.

03:00:11.340 --> 03:00:16.740
Rome now realized that trying to stop

03:00:14.520 --> 03:00:18.600
Hannibal was useless,

03:00:16.740 --> 03:00:21.359
and the only way they could turn the

03:00:18.600 --> 03:00:23.640
tide of this war was to attack Carthage

03:00:21.359 --> 03:00:27.000
in return.

03:00:23.640 --> 03:00:29.880
They sent one army into Spain, led by a

03:00:27.000 --> 03:00:32.700
general named Publius Cornelius Scipio,

03:00:29.880 --> 03:00:36.060
who had been among the few survivors of

03:00:32.700 --> 03:00:37.859
the battle of Cannae, and he was remarkably

03:00:36.060 --> 03:00:42.240
successful.

03:00:37.859 --> 03:00:44.819
In the year 209 BC, in a devastating blow,

03:00:42.240 --> 03:00:47.819
Scipio managed to capture the Spanish

03:00:44.819 --> 03:00:50.399
capital of New Carthage.

03:00:47.819 --> 03:00:53.520
Three years later, he defeated the last

03:00:50.399 --> 03:00:56.040
remaining Carthaginian army in Spain,

03:00:53.520 --> 03:01:00.000
essentially seizing the entire province

03:00:56.040 --> 03:01:02.399
and its abundant silver mines for Rome.

03:01:00.000 --> 03:01:05.460
Despite everything Hannibal had achieved,

03:01:02.399 --> 03:01:06.840
the war was starting to turn in Rome's

03:01:05.460 --> 03:01:10.740
favor.

03:01:06.840 --> 03:01:13.620
Four years later in 205 BC, with Hannibal

03:01:10.740 --> 03:01:16.859
still rampaging in Italy, the Romans gave

03:01:13.620 --> 03:01:20.160
Scipio command of the armies of Sicily

03:01:16.859 --> 03:01:22.800
and ordered him to set sail for Africa,

03:01:20.160 --> 03:01:25.880
to bring this war to the gates of

03:01:22.800 --> 03:01:25.880
Carthage itself.

03:01:26.220 --> 03:01:34.319
After a year of preparation,

03:01:29.040 --> 03:01:36.899
Scipio set sail in 204 BC.

03:01:34.319 --> 03:01:40.140
Faced with this invasion that could

03:01:36.899 --> 03:01:42.899
behead his entire society, Hannibal was

03:01:40.140 --> 03:01:45.779
forced to take his army and leave Italy,

03:01:42.899 --> 03:01:49.439
to hurry back to Carthage and defend the

03:01:45.779 --> 03:01:52.260
city, as the Roman poet Silius Italicus

03:01:49.439 --> 03:01:56.220
renders it.

03:01:52.260 --> 03:01:59.340
Carthage, with all her limbs severed, now

03:01:56.220 --> 03:02:01.500
depended upon a single man; only the

03:01:59.340 --> 03:02:04.740
name of Hannibal prevented her great

03:02:01.500 --> 03:02:08.040
realm from sliding into utter ruin.

03:02:04.740 --> 03:02:10.740
Envoys promptly set sail, crossing the

03:02:08.040 --> 03:02:13.260
sea to recall him, with a plea from his

03:02:10.740 --> 03:02:16.500
country warning that should he choose to

03:02:13.260 --> 03:02:18.720
linger, the city of Carthage might exist

03:02:16.500 --> 03:02:21.899
no more.

03:02:18.720 --> 03:02:25.380
Hannibal marshaled all the forces of

03:02:21.899 --> 03:02:30.300
Carthage and met Publius Scipio in North

03:02:25.380 --> 03:02:33.920
Africa in October of the year 202 BC, at

03:02:30.300 --> 03:02:33.920
a place called Zama.

03:02:34.500 --> 03:02:39.840
Here, on the eve of battle,

03:02:37.020 --> 03:02:42.840
Scipio and Hannibal finally met for the

03:02:39.840 --> 03:02:46.859
first time, and Hannibal seems to have

03:02:42.840 --> 03:02:49.859
presented a dejected, weary face, as

03:02:46.859 --> 03:02:52.859
Polybius writes.

03:02:49.859 --> 03:02:55.380
The next day, both commanders advanced

03:02:52.859 --> 03:02:57.960
from their camps, attended by a few

03:02:55.380 --> 03:03:00.540
horsemen. Presently, they left these

03:02:57.960 --> 03:03:03.240
escorts and met in the intervening space

03:03:00.540 --> 03:03:05.700
by themselves, each accompanied by an

03:03:03.240 --> 03:03:06.600
interpreter. Hannibal was the first to

03:03:05.700 --> 03:03:09.779
speak.

03:03:06.600 --> 03:03:12.120
After the usual salutation, he said that

03:03:09.779 --> 03:03:15.479
he wished that the Romans had never

03:03:12.120 --> 03:03:19.560
coveted any possession outside Italy, nor

03:03:15.479 --> 03:03:22.020
the Carthaginians outside Libya.

03:03:19.560 --> 03:03:25.680
To this battle, Hannibal brought 80

03:03:22.020 --> 03:03:29.040
elephants from the stables of Carthage.

03:03:25.680 --> 03:03:32.279
But recently, one of Carthage's most

03:03:29.040 --> 03:03:34.800
important allies, the kingdom of Numidia

03:03:32.279 --> 03:03:38.580
to their west, had seen the writing on

03:03:34.800 --> 03:03:40.020
the wall and had switched sides, declaring

03:03:38.580 --> 03:03:42.600
for Rome.

03:03:40.020 --> 03:03:45.720
For centuries, Numidia had provided

03:03:42.600 --> 03:03:48.899
Carthage with its crucial cavalry, and

03:03:45.720 --> 03:03:50.700
now Carthage found itself facing these

03:03:48.899 --> 03:03:52.140
same Numidian horsemen on the

03:03:50.700 --> 03:03:54.540
battlefield.

03:03:52.140 --> 03:03:57.240
On top of this, the Romans had developed

03:03:54.540 --> 03:03:59.700
new tactics to neutralize Carthage's

03:03:57.240 --> 03:04:01.620
great strength, the fearsome war

03:03:59.700 --> 03:04:04.140
elephants.

03:04:01.620 --> 03:04:07.020
When the battle began, the elephants of

03:04:04.140 --> 03:04:09.779
Carthage charged, but the Roman lines

03:04:07.020 --> 03:04:12.060
opened up to swallow them, containing

03:04:09.779 --> 03:04:15.840
them with spears and pelting them with

03:04:12.060 --> 03:04:18.240
javelins. These animals panicked and

03:04:15.840 --> 03:04:19.560
stampeded back through the Carthaginian

03:04:18.240 --> 03:04:22.680
lines.

03:04:19.560 --> 03:04:25.380
In the chaos, the Numidian cavalry, now

03:04:22.680 --> 03:04:28.080
fighting with the Romans, swung into the

03:04:25.380 --> 03:04:30.420
rear of the Carthaginian ranks, and

03:04:28.080 --> 03:04:31.800
Hannibal's army was driven from the

03:04:30.420 --> 03:04:36.000
field. He

03:04:31.800 --> 03:04:40.319
only narrowly escaped with his life.

03:04:36.000 --> 03:04:44.540
after 17 long years of war, Carthage was

03:04:40.319 --> 03:04:44.540
once again decisively defeated.

03:04:51.740 --> 03:04:58.140
After the years of the destruction that

03:04:54.899 --> 03:05:01.859
Hannibal had wrought in Italy, Rome was

03:04:58.140 --> 03:05:04.680
in no mood to be lenient.

03:05:01.859 --> 03:05:06.840
They forced Carthage to sign an even

03:05:04.680 --> 03:05:07.680
more crushing peace treaty than the

03:05:06.840 --> 03:05:11.100
first.

03:05:07.680 --> 03:05:13.920
All of its overseas territories in Spain

03:05:11.100 --> 03:05:16.380
and elsewhere were stripped away from it,

03:05:13.920 --> 03:05:19.620
and many of its lands in North Africa

03:05:16.380 --> 03:05:21.899
were handed over to the Numidians,

03:05:19.620 --> 03:05:25.859
and Carthage was ordered to pay more

03:05:21.899 --> 03:05:28.620
than 370 tons of silver, nearly five

03:05:25.859 --> 03:05:30.840
times the amount they had paid after the

03:05:28.620 --> 03:05:33.420
First Punic War.

03:05:30.840 --> 03:05:36.120
The treaty also aimed to destroy

03:05:33.420 --> 03:05:36.899
Carthage's ability to wage war in the

03:05:36.120 --> 03:05:39.359
future.

03:05:36.899 --> 03:05:42.000
It banned them from keeping any war

03:05:39.359 --> 03:05:44.760
elephants, all of which were handed over

03:05:42.000 --> 03:05:48.120
to the Romans, and restricted the size of

03:05:44.760 --> 03:05:51.240
their fleet to only ten ships, barely

03:05:48.120 --> 03:05:53.939
enough to even protect them from pirates.

03:05:51.240 --> 03:05:56.160
The rest of the Carthaginian navy was

03:05:53.939 --> 03:05:59.700
burned in its port.

03:05:56.160 --> 03:06:01.380
The Roman poet Silius Italicus describes

03:05:59.700 --> 03:06:04.319
the scene.

03:06:01.380 --> 03:06:08.220
Then Carthage witnessed a dreadful sight,

03:06:04.319 --> 03:06:10.460
her fleet being set ablaze, the waves

03:06:08.220 --> 03:06:15.000
aglow with the sudden conflagration,

03:06:10.460 --> 03:06:17.640
while Nereus, lord of the ocean, trembled

03:06:15.000 --> 03:06:20.460
at the glare.

03:06:17.640 --> 03:06:23.340
The Carthaginians were restricted from

03:06:20.460 --> 03:06:26.279
declaring war anywhere outside of Africa,

03:06:23.340 --> 03:06:28.560
and only in Africa if they got the

03:06:26.279 --> 03:06:31.979
permission of Rome first.

03:06:28.560 --> 03:06:35.640
The new political situation was clear;

03:06:31.979 --> 03:06:38.000
Carthage was now entirely subservient to

03:06:35.640 --> 03:06:38.000
Rome.

03:06:40.319 --> 03:06:46.380
Hannibal would live for another 20 years

03:06:43.439 --> 03:06:49.560
after the battle of Zama, although he

03:06:46.380 --> 03:06:53.160
would go into exile in the East, retiring

03:06:49.560 --> 03:06:57.600
to Tyre, the mother city of Carthage, and

03:06:53.160 --> 03:07:01.020
then to the Selucid Empire and Armenia.

03:06:57.600 --> 03:07:03.479
The writer Pausanius claims that he died

03:07:01.020 --> 03:07:06.660
when he cut his finger on his drawn

03:07:03.479 --> 03:07:07.800
sword and developed septicemia from the

03:07:06.660 --> 03:07:10.859
wound.

03:07:07.800 --> 03:07:13.560
Other more dramatic stories describe him

03:07:10.859 --> 03:07:16.200
taking poison when he finds his dwelling

03:07:13.560 --> 03:07:19.380
place surrounded by soldiers loyal to

03:07:16.200 --> 03:07:23.420
the Romans, come to capture him and take

03:07:19.380 --> 03:07:23.420
him back to Rome in chains.

03:07:35.899 --> 03:07:42.899
The Second Punic War was over, and once

03:07:40.260 --> 03:07:45.060
more, peace returned to that part of the

03:07:42.899 --> 03:07:47.340
Mediterranean that would last for

03:07:45.060 --> 03:07:50.819
another 50 years.

03:07:47.340 --> 03:07:54.960
During this time, despite its diminished

03:07:50.819 --> 03:07:58.080
situation, Carthage continued to flourish.

03:07:54.960 --> 03:08:00.180
Ironically, it seemed to do them good to

03:07:58.080 --> 03:08:02.460
be freed from the responsibilities of

03:08:00.180 --> 03:08:04.560
defending far-flung colonies and

03:08:02.460 --> 03:08:07.859
territories that for centuries had

03:08:04.560 --> 03:08:10.560
drained their treasury. Nothing about the

03:08:07.859 --> 03:08:13.040
war had changed the city's central role

03:08:10.560 --> 03:08:15.899
in the network of Mediterranean trade.

03:08:13.040 --> 03:08:19.020
Money still flowed into it from all

03:08:15.899 --> 03:08:21.300
corners of the sea, so much so that the

03:08:19.020 --> 03:08:23.760
Carthaginians offered to pay off the

03:08:21.300 --> 03:08:26.580
entirety of the reparations they owed to

03:08:23.760 --> 03:08:29.160
Rome just ten years after the end of the

03:08:26.580 --> 03:08:31.800
war, when the treaty had given them fifty

03:08:29.160 --> 03:08:33.960
years to pay it.

03:08:31.800 --> 03:08:36.479
Some of the largest and grandest

03:08:33.960 --> 03:08:39.000
buildings in Carthage were constructed

03:08:36.479 --> 03:08:40.859
during these decades after the Second

03:08:39.000 --> 03:08:42.600
Punic War.

03:08:40.859 --> 03:08:45.000
For the people of the city,

03:08:42.600 --> 03:08:48.600
it must have been a time of renewed hope,

03:08:45.000 --> 03:08:51.080
as the wounds of the long conflict began

03:08:48.600 --> 03:08:51.080
to heal.

03:08:51.600 --> 03:08:58.580
But their diminished political situation

03:08:54.420 --> 03:08:58.580
did have its downsides.

03:09:04.100 --> 03:09:09.660
Banned from declaring war without Roman

03:09:07.380 --> 03:09:12.479
permission, Carthage repeatedly found

03:09:09.660 --> 03:09:15.120
itself defenseless against ambitious

03:09:12.479 --> 03:09:18.120
rivals in North Africa,

03:09:15.120 --> 03:09:23.939
and one of these was the new Roman ally

03:09:18.120 --> 03:09:23.939
and King of Numidia, named Massinissa.

03:09:27.319 --> 03:09:32.279
Massinissa was the king who had betrayed

03:09:29.760 --> 03:09:35.700
the Carthaginians before the battle of Zama,

03:09:32.279 --> 03:09:37.680
sending his powerful Numidian cavalry to

03:09:35.700 --> 03:09:40.800
fight for the Romans, and possibly

03:09:37.680 --> 03:09:43.560
tipping the entire battle in their favor.

03:09:40.800 --> 03:09:45.540
As a result, he had lived a long and

03:09:43.560 --> 03:09:49.500
prosperous life.

03:09:45.540 --> 03:09:52.020
He was now at the age of 86, and his long

03:09:49.500 --> 03:09:54.779
reign had seen Numidia break free of

03:09:52.020 --> 03:09:57.840
Carthage and become a North African

03:09:54.779 --> 03:09:59.700
power in its own right, and a loyal ally

03:09:57.840 --> 03:10:02.580
of Rome.

03:09:59.700 --> 03:10:05.700
But Massinissa wasn't content with this,

03:10:02.580 --> 03:10:07.439
and he always coveted more land for his

03:10:05.700 --> 03:10:09.899
growing kingdom.

03:10:07.439 --> 03:10:12.840
With the power of Rome now backing him

03:10:09.899 --> 03:10:15.540
and Carthage's hands tied behind its

03:10:12.840 --> 03:10:18.300
back, he repeatedly moved to seize

03:10:15.540 --> 03:10:20.520
wealthy pieces of land from the weakened

03:10:18.300 --> 03:10:23.520
former empire.

03:10:20.520 --> 03:10:26.160
The Carthaginians, bound by their treaty,

03:10:23.520 --> 03:10:29.160
had to appeal to the Romans to allow

03:10:26.160 --> 03:10:32.399
them to defend themselves, but Rome

03:10:29.160 --> 03:10:35.939
considered Massinissa a crucial ally, and

03:10:32.399 --> 03:10:39.540
they always ruled in his favor.

03:10:35.939 --> 03:10:44.340
Carthage was like a great stricken whale

03:10:39.540 --> 03:10:48.300
slowly being eaten alive by sharks.

03:10:44.340 --> 03:10:51.060
In the year 152 BC, half a century after

03:10:48.300 --> 03:10:54.240
the end of the Second Punic War, the

03:10:51.060 --> 03:10:57.120
Numidian King Massinissa seized a

03:10:54.240 --> 03:10:59.640
particularly rich tract of farmland that

03:10:57.120 --> 03:11:01.260
had belonged to Carthage for centuries,

03:10:59.640 --> 03:11:04.020
and the Carthaginians were

03:11:01.260 --> 03:11:07.500
understandably upset, as the Roman

03:11:04.020 --> 03:11:10.560
historian Appian writes.

03:11:07.500 --> 03:11:12.899
Not long afterward, Massinissa raised a

03:11:10.560 --> 03:11:15.600
dispute about the land known as the ëbig

03:11:12.899 --> 03:11:19.560
fieldsí and the country belonging to 50

03:11:15.600 --> 03:11:22.260
towns, which is called Tysca. Again, the

03:11:19.560 --> 03:11:25.080
Carthaginians had recourse to the Romans.

03:11:22.260 --> 03:11:27.720
Again, the latter promised to send envoys

03:11:25.080 --> 03:11:30.000
to arbitrate the matter, but they delayed

03:11:27.720 --> 03:11:32.100
until it seemed probable that the

03:11:30.000 --> 03:11:34.560
Carthaginian interests would be utterly

03:11:32.100 --> 03:11:37.620
ruined.

03:11:34.560 --> 03:11:41.819
Rome finally agreed to send a delegation

03:11:37.620 --> 03:11:43.920
to Carthage to mediate this dispute.

03:11:41.819 --> 03:11:46.560
One of the men sent as part of this

03:11:43.920 --> 03:11:50.460
delegation was an irascible Roman

03:11:46.560 --> 03:11:54.120
senator by the name of Cato the Elder.

03:11:50.460 --> 03:11:55.680
Cato at this time was 81 years old, and

03:11:54.120 --> 03:11:58.439
had spent much of his time in the

03:11:55.680 --> 03:12:01.080
senate railing against what he perceived

03:11:58.439 --> 03:12:03.000
as the increasingly loose morals of

03:12:01.080 --> 03:12:05.700
Roman society.

03:12:03.000 --> 03:12:08.580
As a young man, he had fought against the

03:12:05.700 --> 03:12:11.040
armies of Hannibal in Italy, and as a

03:12:08.580 --> 03:12:13.560
result, he had grown to utterly detest

03:12:11.040 --> 03:12:15.420
the Carthaginians and everything they

03:12:13.560 --> 03:12:18.540
stood for.

03:12:15.420 --> 03:12:21.180
When he arrived in Carthage, Cato

03:12:18.540 --> 03:12:24.240
expected to find the city a barbarian

03:12:21.180 --> 03:12:27.660
backwater, impoverished by its two

03:12:24.240 --> 03:12:30.960
subsequent defeats at the hands of Rome,

03:12:27.660 --> 03:12:34.439
but what he found horrified him.

03:12:30.960 --> 03:12:37.560
Carthage was a booming city that seemed

03:12:34.439 --> 03:12:39.960
to be doing better than ever, and to his

03:12:37.560 --> 03:12:44.460
shock, the visible wealth of the city

03:12:39.960 --> 03:12:47.760
seemed to outdo that of Rome itself.

03:12:44.460 --> 03:12:51.020
In Plutarch's biography of Cato, he

03:12:47.760 --> 03:12:54.300
describes the old senator's reaction.

03:12:51.020 --> 03:12:57.060
The city was by no means in a poor or lowly

03:12:54.300 --> 03:12:59.660
state as the Romans supposed, but rather

03:12:57.060 --> 03:13:02.520
teeming with vigorous fighting men,

03:12:59.660 --> 03:13:04.560
overflowing with enormous wealth, filled

03:13:02.520 --> 03:13:08.460
with arms of every sort and with

03:13:04.560 --> 03:13:12.140
military supplies, and more than a

03:13:08.460 --> 03:13:12.140
little emboldened by all this.

03:13:13.080 --> 03:13:19.020
The writer Appian records another

03:13:16.020 --> 03:13:21.479
version of this moment, as the senators

03:13:19.020 --> 03:13:24.680
rode through the wealthy landscape

03:13:21.479 --> 03:13:24.680
outside the city.

03:13:24.960 --> 03:13:30.660
They carefully observed the country; they

03:13:28.020 --> 03:13:33.359
saw how diligently it was cultivated and

03:13:30.660 --> 03:13:35.880
what great estates it possessed. They

03:13:33.359 --> 03:13:37.439
entered the city and saw how greatly it

03:13:35.880 --> 03:13:40.439
had increased in wealth and population

03:13:37.439 --> 03:13:41.880
since its overthrow by Scipio not long

03:13:40.439 --> 03:13:44.399
before.

03:13:41.880 --> 03:13:46.620
When they returned to Rome, they declared

03:13:44.399 --> 03:13:49.620
that Carthage was to them an object of

03:13:46.620 --> 03:13:52.500
apprehension rather than of jealousy, the

03:13:49.620 --> 03:13:56.460
city being so ill-affected, so near to

03:13:52.500 --> 03:13:59.939
them, and growing so rapidly.

03:13:56.460 --> 03:14:01.560
The old senator Cato was shaken by his

03:13:59.939 --> 03:14:03.840
experience.

03:14:01.560 --> 03:14:07.740
From then, he would dedicate the final

03:14:03.840 --> 03:14:11.340
years of his life to a single cause.

03:14:07.740 --> 03:14:13.500
Now at every debate in the senate, Cato

03:14:11.340 --> 03:14:15.840
would end every one of his statements,

03:14:13.500 --> 03:14:18.120
whether on the price of grain or the

03:14:15.840 --> 03:14:21.540
wars in Gaul, whether on the appointment

03:14:18.120 --> 03:14:26.240
of new consuls or the response to a

03:14:21.540 --> 03:14:26.240
flood in the south, with a single

03:14:26.600 --> 03:14:33.840
phrase; ceterum, censeo Carthago delenda est.

03:14:30.020 --> 03:14:35.220
Furthermore, I believe Carthage must be

03:14:33.840 --> 03:14:38.040
destroyed.

03:14:35.220 --> 03:14:41.300
Many in the Roman senate were starting

03:14:38.040 --> 03:14:41.300
to agree with him.

03:14:46.620 --> 03:14:52.500
Finally, a year after Cato's visit to

03:14:49.979 --> 03:14:55.380
Carthage, the Carthaginians had had

03:14:52.500 --> 03:14:58.560
enough of the Numidian king Massinissa

03:14:55.380 --> 03:15:02.279
taking advantage of their situation.

03:14:58.560 --> 03:15:04.680
They sent an army of 50,000 men to seize

03:15:02.279 --> 03:15:05.760
back some of the farmland that he had

03:15:04.680 --> 03:15:08.460
taken. 

03:15:05.760 --> 03:15:11.120
But their army was decisively defeated

03:15:08.460 --> 03:15:14.279
by the Numidians.

03:15:11.120 --> 03:15:17.760
Carthage's last attempt to defend itself

03:15:14.279 --> 03:15:21.060
had been a failure, but to the Romans, it

03:15:17.760 --> 03:15:24.120
was also a breach of their treaty, and it

03:15:21.060 --> 03:15:27.540
was enough of a pretext to go to war one

03:15:24.120 --> 03:15:30.260
final time to destroy their old rival

03:15:27.540 --> 03:15:30.260
for good.

03:15:30.840 --> 03:15:38.399
In the year 149 BC, the old Phoenician

03:15:34.920 --> 03:15:40.080
city of Utica seems to have felt the

03:15:38.399 --> 03:15:43.560
change in the winds.

03:15:40.080 --> 03:15:46.260
They also changed allegiances, declaring

03:15:43.560 --> 03:15:49.500
their loyalty to Rome, and in the same

03:15:46.260 --> 03:15:52.380
year, a large Roman army used the port of

03:15:49.500 --> 03:15:54.420
Utica to land in North Africa, and

03:15:52.380 --> 03:15:56.220
prepared to march on the city of

03:15:54.420 --> 03:15:59.100
Carthage.

03:15:56.220 --> 03:16:02.160
At news of this army landing, the

03:15:59.100 --> 03:16:05.160
Carthaginians were distraught.

03:16:02.160 --> 03:16:07.319
They sent envoys to meet the Romans, and

03:16:05.160 --> 03:16:09.140
when they arrived, the Romans demanded

03:16:07.319 --> 03:16:12.420
that the city be completely

03:16:09.140 --> 03:16:14.160
demilitarized and hand over all of their

03:16:12.420 --> 03:16:17.220
military equipment.

03:16:14.160 --> 03:16:19.920
The Carthaginians complied.

03:16:17.220 --> 03:16:22.680
They came back with every piece of armor

03:16:19.920 --> 03:16:24.540
and weaponry they could find, offering

03:16:22.680 --> 03:16:27.120
their total surrender,

03:16:24.540 --> 03:16:29.700
and with the Roman general sitting over

03:16:27.120 --> 03:16:33.680
them on his high seat, they pleaded with

03:16:29.700 --> 03:16:33.680
the Romans not to go to war.

03:16:33.840 --> 03:16:39.840
Carthage was now completely disarmed, and

03:16:37.620 --> 03:16:44.220
in response, the Romans offered them

03:16:39.840 --> 03:16:47.399
peace on one condition, but it was a

03:16:44.220 --> 03:16:50.819
condition so absurd that even they must

03:16:47.399 --> 03:16:52.800
have known it would be rejected.

03:16:50.819 --> 03:16:55.560
They demanded that the Carthaginians

03:16:52.800 --> 03:16:59.160
abandoned their city so that it could be

03:16:55.560 --> 03:17:02.520
demolished in its entirety and moved 16

03:16:59.160 --> 03:17:04.020
kilometers or so inland and away from

03:17:02.520 --> 03:17:09.080
the sea.

03:17:04.020 --> 03:17:09.080
Appian recounts these Roman demands.

03:17:09.300 --> 03:17:16.319
Censorinus rose, and with a stern

03:17:12.660 --> 03:17:18.600
countenance, spoke; ëYield Carthage to us,

03:17:16.319 --> 03:17:21.060
and betake yourselves where you like

03:17:18.600 --> 03:17:24.180
within your own territory, at a distance

03:17:21.060 --> 03:17:27.180
of at least ten miles from the sea, for we

03:17:24.180 --> 03:17:29.420
are resolved to raze your city to the

03:17:27.180 --> 03:17:29.420
ground.í

03:17:29.939 --> 03:17:34.439
Such a task would be virtually

03:17:32.160 --> 03:17:37.080
impossible, and of course for the

03:17:34.439 --> 03:17:39.540
sea-going Phoenicians of Carthage, would

03:17:37.080 --> 03:17:40.979
have essentially ended their livelihoods

03:17:39.540 --> 03:17:43.140
for good.

03:17:40.979 --> 03:17:45.720
Moving the city would have meant

03:17:43.140 --> 03:17:48.300
abandoning their temples, the cemeteries

03:17:45.720 --> 03:17:51.479
where their ancestors were buried, every

03:17:48.300 --> 03:17:54.359
street and corner that they knew.

03:17:51.479 --> 03:17:57.420
Appian records the outpouring of grief

03:17:54.359 --> 03:18:00.439
as the Carthaginians were informed of

03:17:57.420 --> 03:18:00.439
the Roman plans.

03:18:01.439 --> 03:18:06.660
While he was yet speaking,

03:18:04.080 --> 03:18:10.380
the Carthaginians lifted their hands

03:18:06.660 --> 03:18:12.000
toward heaven with loud cries and called

03:18:10.380 --> 03:18:14.460
on the gods.

03:18:12.000 --> 03:18:16.800
They flung themselves on the ground and

03:18:14.460 --> 03:18:19.020
beat it with their hands and heads. Some

03:18:16.800 --> 03:18:21.180
of them even tore their clothes and

03:18:19.020 --> 03:18:24.979
lacerated their flesh, as though they

03:18:21.180 --> 03:18:27.779
were absolutely bereft of their senses.

03:18:24.979 --> 03:18:30.840
After the first frenzy was past, there

03:18:27.779 --> 03:18:32.760
was great silence and prostration, as of

03:18:30.840 --> 03:18:35.640
men lying dead.

03:18:32.760 --> 03:18:37.680
So pitiable was this mingling together

03:18:35.640 --> 03:18:42.380
of public and private grief that it

03:18:37.680 --> 03:18:42.380
drew tears from the Romans themselves.

03:18:42.840 --> 03:18:47.899
The Carthaginians withdrew to their city,

03:18:45.479 --> 03:18:52.500
and the entire civilian population

03:18:47.899 --> 03:18:55.560
prepared to withstand their attackers.

03:18:52.500 --> 03:18:58.319
The historian Appian summarizes the dire

03:18:55.560 --> 03:19:00.540
situation that the citizens of Carthage

03:18:58.319 --> 03:19:02.520
faced.

03:19:00.540 --> 03:19:04.920
They reflected that their city was

03:19:02.520 --> 03:19:07.859
without arms, that it was empty of

03:19:04.920 --> 03:19:11.340
defenders, that it had not a ship, not a

03:19:07.859 --> 03:19:13.680
catapult, not a javelin, not a sword, nor a

03:19:11.340 --> 03:19:16.080
sufficient number of fighting men.

03:19:13.680 --> 03:19:20.340
They had neither mercenaries, nor friends,

03:19:16.080 --> 03:19:21.960
nor allies, nor time to procure any. Their

03:19:20.340 --> 03:19:24.260
enemies were in possession of their

03:19:21.960 --> 03:19:27.479
children, their arms, and their territory.

03:19:24.260 --> 03:19:30.660
Their city was besieged by foes provided

03:19:27.479 --> 03:19:33.479
with ships, infantry, cavalry, and engines,

03:19:30.660 --> 03:19:36.260
while Massinissa, their other enemy, was

03:19:33.479 --> 03:19:36.260
on their flank.

03:19:36.720 --> 03:19:42.660
But the city was still a formidable

03:19:39.359 --> 03:19:45.840
fortress. Its triple line of defensive

03:19:42.660 --> 03:19:48.899
walls could withstand any assault,

03:19:45.840 --> 03:19:51.500
and it had complex systems for gathering

03:19:48.899 --> 03:19:54.540
rainwater and storing it in vast

03:19:51.500 --> 03:19:56.460
cisterns, allowing it to maintain a

03:19:54.540 --> 03:19:57.479
continuous supply of fresh drinking

03:19:56.460 --> 03:20:00.479
water.

03:19:57.479 --> 03:20:02.580
The Romans settled in for a siege, but

03:20:00.479 --> 03:20:05.279
soon found it to be much more difficult

03:20:02.580 --> 03:20:07.800
than they had expected.

03:20:05.279 --> 03:20:10.620
They controlled the seas, but swift

03:20:07.800 --> 03:20:13.200
Carthaginian sailors were still able to

03:20:10.620 --> 03:20:15.180
smuggle food into the city's harbor at

03:20:13.200 --> 03:20:17.880
night.

03:20:15.180 --> 03:20:20.640
The Romans tried again and again to

03:20:17.880 --> 03:20:23.460
storm the city walls, but each time, they

03:20:20.640 --> 03:20:25.500
were fought back by the citizens, now

03:20:23.460 --> 03:20:28.680
fighting tooth and nail for their

03:20:25.500 --> 03:20:31.439
survival with every tool and improvised

03:20:28.680 --> 03:20:33.660
weapon they could find, as Appian

03:20:31.439 --> 03:20:36.960
recounts.

03:20:33.660 --> 03:20:39.720
All the sacred places, the temples and

03:20:36.960 --> 03:20:41.819
every other unoccupied space, were turned

03:20:39.720 --> 03:20:43.859
into workshops where men and women

03:20:41.819 --> 03:20:46.859
worked together day and night without

03:20:43.859 --> 03:20:49.439
pause, taking their food by turns on a

03:20:46.859 --> 03:20:52.680
fixed schedule. Each day, they made a

03:20:49.439 --> 03:20:55.859
hundred shields, 300 swords, a thousand

03:20:52.680 --> 03:20:58.500
missiles for catapults, 500 darts and

03:20:55.859 --> 03:21:01.260
javelins, and as many catapults as they

03:20:58.500 --> 03:21:03.120
could. For strings to bend them, the women

03:21:01.260 --> 03:21:04.979
cut off their hair for want of other

03:21:03.120 --> 03:21:08.220
fibers.

03:21:04.979 --> 03:21:10.020
The siege of Carthage went on for three

03:21:08.220 --> 03:21:13.920
years.

03:21:10.020 --> 03:21:17.100
In the year 147, command of the besieging

03:21:13.920 --> 03:21:20.160
army was given to a new consul, in fact,

03:21:17.100 --> 03:21:22.680
the 36-year-old adopted grandson of the

03:21:20.160 --> 03:21:25.439
great Publius Scipio, who had beat

03:21:22.680 --> 03:21:28.439
Hannibal at the battle of Zama some 50

03:21:25.439 --> 03:21:30.779
years earlier, a man named Scipio

03:21:28.439 --> 03:21:33.899
Aemilianus.

03:21:30.779 --> 03:21:35.939
With him came his personal friend and

03:21:33.899 --> 03:21:39.600
official documenter of the expedition,

03:21:35.939 --> 03:21:41.640
the Greek historian Polybius, who writes

03:21:39.600 --> 03:21:43.520
this part of his history as an

03:21:41.640 --> 03:21:46.319
eyewitness.

03:21:43.520 --> 03:21:49.200
Infuriated at the smugglers still

03:21:46.319 --> 03:21:51.840
supplying the besieged city, the Roman

03:21:49.200 --> 03:21:54.479
general Scipio ordered a vast stone

03:21:51.840 --> 03:21:57.420
barrier to be built in the mouth of

03:21:54.479 --> 03:21:59.700
Carthage's harbor, blocking any further

03:21:57.420 --> 03:22:02.880
attempts to resupply it.

03:21:59.700 --> 03:22:06.840
Food became scarce in the city,

03:22:02.880 --> 03:22:11.520
but still the defenders struggled on.

03:22:06.840 --> 03:22:13.800
But in the spring of the year 146 BC, the

03:22:11.520 --> 03:22:17.520
spirit of the Carthaginians was

03:22:13.800 --> 03:22:20.340
exhausted. Scipio launched a full-scale

03:22:17.520 --> 03:22:22.920
assault of the city from the area of the

03:22:20.340 --> 03:22:25.800
harbor, and the great walls of Carthage

03:22:22.920 --> 03:22:28.500
were finally breached.

03:22:25.800 --> 03:22:32.040
The Roman legions poured into the city

03:22:28.500 --> 03:22:34.020
and began to massacre every person they

03:22:32.040 --> 03:22:36.720
could find.

03:22:34.020 --> 03:22:39.260
Appian described the scenes that

03:22:36.720 --> 03:22:39.260
followed.

03:22:39.779 --> 03:22:45.359
Then came new scenes of horror as the

03:22:43.140 --> 03:22:48.060
fire spread and carried everything down.

03:22:45.359 --> 03:22:50.700
The soldiers did not wait to destroy the

03:22:48.060 --> 03:22:53.939
buildings little by little, but all in a

03:22:50.700 --> 03:22:56.220
heap. So, the crashing grew louder and

03:22:53.939 --> 03:22:59.120
many corpses fell with the stones into

03:22:56.220 --> 03:23:01.620
the midst. Others were seen still living,

03:22:59.120 --> 03:23:03.960
especially old men, women, and young

03:23:01.620 --> 03:23:06.660
children, who had hidden in the inmost

03:23:03.960 --> 03:23:10.020
nooks of the houses, some of them wounded,

03:23:06.660 --> 03:23:12.000
some more or less burned, and uttering

03:23:10.020 --> 03:23:15.239
piteous cries.

03:23:12.000 --> 03:23:17.220
Still others, thrust out and falling from

03:23:15.239 --> 03:23:20.399
such a height with the stones, timbers,

03:23:17.220 --> 03:23:23.760
and fire, were torn asunder in all shapes

03:23:20.399 --> 03:23:27.180
of horror, crushed and mangled. Trenches

03:23:23.760 --> 03:23:30.120
were filled with men. The tug of war, the

03:23:27.180 --> 03:23:32.640
glory of approaching victory, the rush of

03:23:30.120 --> 03:23:36.000
the soldiery, the orders of the officers,

03:23:32.640 --> 03:23:38.399
the blast of the trumpets, tribunes and

03:23:36.000 --> 03:23:39.420
centurions marching their cohorts hither

03:23:38.399 --> 03:23:42.600
and thither --

03:23:39.420 --> 03:23:44.580
all together made everybody frantic and

03:23:42.600 --> 03:23:46.680
heedless of the spectacles under their

03:23:44.580 --> 03:23:49.140
eyes.

03:23:46.680 --> 03:23:52.979
The slaughter of Carthage's citizens

03:23:49.140 --> 03:23:55.620
went on for six days, during which it's

03:23:52.979 --> 03:23:58.200
thought that an estimated 60,000 people

03:23:55.620 --> 03:24:01.080
were put to the sword.

03:23:58.200 --> 03:24:04.319
The Roman general Scipio set his

03:24:01.080 --> 03:24:06.899
soldiers to work in shifts so that they

03:24:04.319 --> 03:24:09.479
would not become tired of the killing,

03:24:06.899 --> 03:24:12.899
and on the seventh day, Scipio ordered

03:24:09.479 --> 03:24:15.859
his soldiers to begin taking prisoners.

03:24:12.899 --> 03:24:18.479
From this point, a further 50,000

03:24:15.859 --> 03:24:20.279
Carthaginians were rounded up and sold

03:24:18.479 --> 03:24:22.800
into slavery.

03:24:20.279 --> 03:24:25.500
From there, they would be sold and

03:24:22.800 --> 03:24:27.359
dispersed to all corners of the Roman

03:24:25.500 --> 03:24:30.779
republic.

03:24:27.359 --> 03:24:33.420
Carthage was burned to the ground and

03:24:30.779 --> 03:24:36.479
demolished brick by brick.

03:24:33.420 --> 03:24:39.540
Some Carthaginians held out for some

03:24:36.479 --> 03:24:41.880
time in the citadel of Byrsa, the

03:24:39.540 --> 03:24:44.760
fortified hill on which legend has it

03:24:41.880 --> 03:24:47.279
that Elishaya once cut apart her ox hide

03:24:44.760 --> 03:24:49.319
at the city's founding.

03:24:47.279 --> 03:24:52.260
According to Appian, when the

03:24:49.319 --> 03:24:55.439
Carthaginian general Hasdrubal finally

03:24:52.260 --> 03:24:58.979
surrendered, his wife set fire to the

03:24:55.439 --> 03:25:01.620
main temple and climbed upon its roof.

03:24:58.979 --> 03:25:04.739
Just like the mythical figure of

03:25:01.620 --> 03:25:07.920
Elishaya, she then cast herself and her

03:25:04.739 --> 03:25:10.319
children into the flames.

03:25:07.920 --> 03:25:13.319
It is said that as the fire was lighted,

03:25:10.319 --> 03:25:15.899
the wife of Hasdrubal, in full view of

03:25:13.319 --> 03:25:18.960
Scipio, arrayed in the best attire

03:25:15.899 --> 03:25:21.600
possible under such circumstances,

03:25:18.960 --> 03:25:23.880
and with her children by her side,

03:25:21.600 --> 03:25:27.479
said in Scipio's hearing;

03:25:23.880 --> 03:25:28.680
ëFor you, Roman, the gods have no cause of

03:25:27.479 --> 03:25:31.560
indignation,

03:25:28.680 --> 03:25:34.979
since you exercise the right of war.

03:25:31.560 --> 03:25:38.399
Upon this, Hasdrubal, betrayer of his

03:25:34.979 --> 03:25:40.800
country and her temples, of me and his

03:25:38.399 --> 03:25:42.120
children, may the gods of Carthage take

03:25:40.800 --> 03:25:45.359
vengeance,

03:25:42.120 --> 03:25:48.540
and you be their instrument.í

03:25:45.359 --> 03:25:50.760
Having reproached him thus, she slew her

03:25:48.540 --> 03:25:52.800
children, flung them into the fire, and

03:25:50.760 --> 03:25:55.920
plunged in after them.

03:25:52.800 --> 03:25:59.660
Such they say was the death

03:25:55.920 --> 03:25:59.660
of the wife of Hasdrubal.

03:26:00.660 --> 03:26:05.880
The historian Polybius, who accompanied

03:26:03.420 --> 03:26:08.279
Scipio throughout the entire siege,

03:26:05.880 --> 03:26:11.100
writes with little detail about what

03:26:08.279 --> 03:26:13.620
unfolded, but he does note that in the

03:26:11.100 --> 03:26:17.399
moment of his victory, the Roman general

03:26:13.620 --> 03:26:20.460
turned to him and said something strange.

03:26:17.399 --> 03:26:23.700
In the burning ruins of Carthage, Scipio

03:26:20.460 --> 03:26:26.700
Ammianus seems to have felt a spark of

03:26:23.700 --> 03:26:29.640
apprehension, a sudden fear or

03:26:26.700 --> 03:26:34.859
realization that one day the same fate

03:26:29.640 --> 03:26:37.260
might befall his own great city of Rome.

03:26:34.859 --> 03:26:40.140
Turning around to me at once and

03:26:37.260 --> 03:26:42.899
grasping my hand, Scipio said,

03:26:40.140 --> 03:26:45.120
ëA glorious moment, Polybius,

03:26:42.899 --> 03:26:48.000
but I have a dread foreboding that

03:26:45.120 --> 03:26:49.920
someday the same doom will be pronounced

03:26:48.000 --> 03:26:52.620
on my own country.í

03:26:49.920 --> 03:26:55.260
It would be difficult to mention an

03:26:52.620 --> 03:26:56.399
assurance more statesmanlike and more

03:26:55.260 --> 03:26:58.859
profound.

03:26:56.399 --> 03:27:02.460
At the moment of our greatest triumph

03:26:58.859 --> 03:27:05.340
and of disaster to our enemies -- to bear

03:27:02.460 --> 03:27:08.880
in mind at the season of success the

03:27:05.340 --> 03:27:11.939
mutability of fortune.

03:27:08.880 --> 03:27:14.160
Appian records that Scipio is said to

03:27:11.939 --> 03:27:17.279
have wept at the sight of Carthage

03:27:14.160 --> 03:27:20.460
burning, and that he recited a line from

03:27:17.279 --> 03:27:23.760
Homer's great epic The Iliad, in which

03:27:20.460 --> 03:27:28.220
Andromache, the wife of Hector, laments

03:27:23.760 --> 03:27:28.220
the coming destruction of Troy.

03:27:29.040 --> 03:27:34.800
Scipio, beholding this city, which had

03:27:32.340 --> 03:27:38.040
flourished 700 years from its foundation

03:27:34.800 --> 03:27:41.060
and had ruled over so many lands, islands,

03:27:38.040 --> 03:27:44.040
and seas, rich with arms and fleets,

03:27:41.060 --> 03:27:46.380
elephants and money, equal to the

03:27:44.040 --> 03:27:49.739
mightiest monarchies but far surpassing

03:27:46.380 --> 03:27:53.279
them in bravery and high spirit, now come

03:27:49.739 --> 03:27:56.340
to its end in total destruction.

03:27:53.279 --> 03:27:59.160
Scipio, beholding this spectacle, is said

03:27:56.340 --> 03:28:01.319
to have shed tears and publicly lamented

03:27:59.160 --> 03:28:03.960
the fortune of the enemy. After

03:28:01.319 --> 03:28:05.819
meditating by himself a long time and

03:28:03.960 --> 03:28:08.880
reflecting on the rise and fall of

03:28:05.819 --> 03:28:11.640
cities, nations, and empires, as well as of

03:28:08.880 --> 03:28:14.160
individuals upon the fate of Troy, that

03:28:11.640 --> 03:28:17.160
once proud city, upon that of the

03:28:14.160 --> 03:28:20.160
Assyrians, the Medes, and the Persians,

03:28:17.160 --> 03:28:23.160
greatest of all, and later the splendid

03:28:20.160 --> 03:28:25.560
Macedonian Empire, either voluntarily or

03:28:23.160 --> 03:28:26.760
otherwise, the words of the poet escaped

03:28:25.560 --> 03:28:29.160
his lips;

03:28:26.760 --> 03:28:32.040
ëThe day shall come in which our sacred Troy

03:28:29.160 --> 03:28:36.899
and Priam, and the people over whom spear-

03:28:32.040 --> 03:28:40.200
-bearing Priam rules, shall perish all.í

03:28:36.899 --> 03:28:43.260
But back in Rome, there was no such sense

03:28:40.200 --> 03:28:45.779
of foreboding. The city exploded in

03:28:43.260 --> 03:28:48.439
celebration at the news.

03:28:45.779 --> 03:28:48.439
When the people of Rome

03:28:49.040 --> 03:28:54.540
heard of the victory early in the

03:28:51.600 --> 03:28:57.180
evening, they poured into the streets and

03:28:54.540 --> 03:28:59.819
spent the whole night congratulating and

03:28:57.180 --> 03:29:02.640
embracing each other like people just

03:28:59.819 --> 03:29:04.439
now delivered from some great fear, just

03:29:02.640 --> 03:29:07.319
now confirmed in their worldwide

03:29:04.439 --> 03:29:10.020
supremacy, just now assured of the

03:29:07.319 --> 03:29:12.779
permanence of their own city, and winners

03:29:10.020 --> 03:29:14.760
of such a victory as never before.

03:29:12.779 --> 03:29:17.399
They talked about the height of the

03:29:14.760 --> 03:29:19.620
walls and the size of the stones.

03:29:17.399 --> 03:29:22.080
They pictured to each other the whole

03:29:19.620 --> 03:29:25.460
war as though it were just taking place

03:29:22.080 --> 03:29:25.460
under their own eyes.

03:29:27.380 --> 03:29:33.540
In the days that followed, ash would have

03:29:30.840 --> 03:29:35.700
settled over the charred ruins of

03:29:33.540 --> 03:29:38.960
Carthage.

03:29:35.700 --> 03:29:42.300
From its final victory in the Punic Wars,

03:29:38.960 --> 03:29:44.700
Rome would emerge as the only superpower

03:29:42.300 --> 03:29:46.800
left in the Mediterranean.

03:29:44.700 --> 03:29:49.739
The scattered Greek kingdoms that

03:29:46.800 --> 03:29:52.500
remained were one by one absorbed by it,

03:29:49.739 --> 03:29:54.960
and in the coming centuries, it would

03:29:52.500 --> 03:29:57.420
grow to encompass the entire shore of

03:29:54.960 --> 03:30:00.000
that sea, cover all but the farthest

03:29:57.420 --> 03:30:03.660
stretches of Western Europe, and shape

03:30:00.000 --> 03:30:07.800
the entire course of European history.

03:30:03.660 --> 03:30:10.979
But Carthage would become just a name, a

03:30:07.800 --> 03:30:16.040
coin that had lost its value, an emblem

03:30:10.979 --> 03:30:16.040
of an age that had passed into nothing.

03:30:19.979 --> 03:30:25.500
After the carnage of the siege, the

03:30:22.979 --> 03:30:27.840
blackened ruins of the city were emptied

03:30:25.500 --> 03:30:30.600
of all life.

03:30:27.840 --> 03:30:31.920
But for the Romans, this still wasn't

03:30:30.600 --> 03:30:34.319
enough.

03:30:31.920 --> 03:30:37.260
In the years that followed, they sent

03:30:34.319 --> 03:30:39.899
further delegations to the city to

03:30:37.260 --> 03:30:43.380
systematically take it apart piece by

03:30:39.899 --> 03:30:47.160
piece to ensure that no population crept

03:30:43.380 --> 03:30:50.100
back to repopulate its ruins, that never

03:30:47.160 --> 03:30:53.040
again would their great rival resurface

03:30:50.100 --> 03:30:55.920
in North Africa.

03:30:53.040 --> 03:30:58.380
Some of the libraries and archives of

03:30:55.920 --> 03:30:59.279
Carthage survived the burning of the

03:30:58.380 --> 03:31:01.439
city.

03:30:59.279 --> 03:31:04.739
In these were kept the books of

03:31:01.439 --> 03:31:08.399
Carthaginian history, perhaps poetry and

03:31:04.739 --> 03:31:10.739
mythology, science and medicine, documents

03:31:08.399 --> 03:31:13.020
of the Phoenician voyages of discovery

03:31:10.739 --> 03:31:15.420
to the edges of the world,

03:31:13.020 --> 03:31:19.080
but all of these were taken by the

03:31:15.420 --> 03:31:21.779
Romans. Some were simply burned, while

03:31:19.080 --> 03:31:23.640
others were distributed among the Romanís

03:31:21.779 --> 03:31:26.819
African allies.

03:31:23.640 --> 03:31:29.520
As a result, not a single one of these

03:31:26.819 --> 03:31:32.760
works has survived.

03:31:29.520 --> 03:31:35.700
Today, scarcely a few documents written

03:31:32.760 --> 03:31:38.700
by a Carthaginian can be read, and no

03:31:35.700 --> 03:31:40.100
works of literature or history have come

03:31:38.700 --> 03:31:43.260
down to us.

03:31:40.100 --> 03:31:47.340
So, for the next two thousand years,

03:31:43.260 --> 03:31:50.520
their story would be told by others.

03:31:47.340 --> 03:31:55.620
Their voices and their memory, just like

03:31:50.520 --> 03:31:55.620
their city, were completely erased.

03:31:56.939 --> 03:32:02.580
The territory of Carthage was absorbed

03:31:59.939 --> 03:32:05.220
into the new Roman province of Africa,

03:32:02.580 --> 03:32:08.040
and for the next hundred years, what

03:32:05.220 --> 03:32:11.340
remained of the ruins of Carthage were

03:32:08.040 --> 03:32:12.560
left to crumble into the sands, home to

03:32:11.340 --> 03:32:16.319
wild dogs,

03:32:12.560 --> 03:32:19.580
overgrown with scrub and weeds and marram

03:32:16.319 --> 03:32:24.739
grass, washed with salt from the sea air,

03:32:19.580 --> 03:32:24.739
the roost of gulls and crows.

03:32:25.380 --> 03:32:30.060
More than a century later,

03:32:27.660 --> 03:32:32.819
Rome would send a party of

03:32:30.060 --> 03:32:35.580
3,000 colonists to the ruins of the

03:32:32.819 --> 03:32:37.859
shattered city, and they founded a Roman

03:32:35.580 --> 03:32:40.979
colony on the rubble.

03:32:37.859 --> 03:32:43.380
As they settled the area, the ruins of

03:32:40.979 --> 03:32:45.899
Carthage were themselves buried beneath

03:32:43.380 --> 03:32:48.300
a new Roman town that shared almost

03:32:45.899 --> 03:32:52.020
nothing of the city that had once stood

03:32:48.300 --> 03:32:55.319
there except its name, and even the ruins

03:32:52.020 --> 03:32:58.640
of the city as it had once been would

03:32:55.319 --> 03:32:58.640
soon be forgotten.

03:33:00.779 --> 03:33:07.260
Around the year 1835, the British

03:33:04.439 --> 03:33:09.840
statesman Sir Grenville Temple visited

03:33:07.260 --> 03:33:11.640
the ruins of Carthage, and wrote the

03:33:09.840 --> 03:33:14.399
following description of his

03:33:11.640 --> 03:33:19.100
disappointment upon finding how little

03:33:14.399 --> 03:33:19.100
remained of that once great city.

03:33:19.140 --> 03:33:25.380
Early on the morning following, I walked

03:33:22.920 --> 03:33:27.899
to the site of the great Carthage, of

03:33:25.380 --> 03:33:30.720
that town at the sound of whose name

03:33:27.899 --> 03:33:31.920
mighty Rome herself had so often

03:33:30.720 --> 03:33:34.920
trembled.

03:33:31.920 --> 03:33:36.899
I was prepared to see but few vestiges

03:33:34.920 --> 03:33:39.720
of its former grandeur,

03:33:36.899 --> 03:33:42.779
but my heart sunk within me when

03:33:39.720 --> 03:33:45.660
ascending one of its hills, for I beheld

03:33:42.779 --> 03:33:48.380
nothing more than a few scattered and

03:33:45.660 --> 03:33:52.080
shapeless masses of masonry.

03:33:48.380 --> 03:33:53.819
Its very name is now unknown to the

03:33:52.080 --> 03:33:57.359
present inhabitants.

03:33:53.819 --> 03:33:59.520
Buried in the silence of the grave, no

03:33:57.359 --> 03:34:01.739
living soul appearing, except

03:33:59.520 --> 03:34:04.739
occasionally a soldier going or

03:34:01.739 --> 03:34:06.899
returning from the fort, or the solitary

03:34:04.739 --> 03:34:09.300
and motionless figure of an Arab,

03:34:06.899 --> 03:34:11.640
watching his flocks from the summit of

03:34:09.300 --> 03:34:15.180
the fragment of some former palace or

03:34:11.640 --> 03:34:18.180
temple. Solitude and silence hold sway

03:34:15.180 --> 03:34:20.340
over the whole scene, a scene which

03:34:18.180 --> 03:34:21.899
impresses on the mind a feeling of

03:34:20.340 --> 03:34:26.300
melancholy,

03:34:21.899 --> 03:34:26.300
which I found difficult to shake off.

03:34:29.939 --> 03:34:35.700
Another person who visited these ruins

03:34:32.640 --> 03:34:38.580
was the English poet Letitia Elizabeth

03:34:35.700 --> 03:34:43.200
Landon, and I'd like to end the episode

03:34:38.580 --> 03:34:45.840
with her poem, entitled Carthage.

03:34:43.200 --> 03:34:48.660
As you listen, imagine what it would feel

03:34:45.840 --> 03:34:52.380
like to watch the streets and temples of

03:34:48.660 --> 03:34:55.739
that city crumble and burn, as 800 years

03:34:52.380 --> 03:34:57.060
of history is buried beneath ash and

03:34:55.739 --> 03:34:59.700
soot.

03:34:57.060 --> 03:35:01.399
Imagine every book that has ever been

03:34:59.700 --> 03:35:05.580
written in your native language

03:35:01.399 --> 03:35:08.460
destroyed, and your people enslaved and

03:35:05.580 --> 03:35:10.920
scattered about the face of the Earth.

03:35:08.460 --> 03:35:14.040
Imagine what it would feel like to see

03:35:10.920 --> 03:35:16.739
your own hometown disappear, emptied of

03:35:14.040 --> 03:35:20.640
all life and demolished brick by brick,

03:35:16.739 --> 03:35:24.359
then left empty, until only a scattering

03:35:20.640 --> 03:35:24.359
of ruins remains.

03:35:26.540 --> 03:35:34.620
Low it lieth -- earth to earth --

03:35:30.720 --> 03:35:38.700
all to which that earth gave birth --

03:35:34.620 --> 03:35:42.359
palace, market street, and fane;

03:35:38.700 --> 03:35:45.960
dust that never asks in vain,

03:35:42.359 --> 03:35:47.460
hath reclaimíd its own again.

03:35:45.960 --> 03:35:49.800
Dust,

03:35:47.460 --> 03:35:53.340
the wide worldís king.

03:35:49.800 --> 03:35:56.460
Where are now the glorious hours of a

03:35:53.340 --> 03:35:59.460
nationís gatheríd powers?

03:35:56.460 --> 03:36:01.319
Like the setting of a star in the

03:35:59.460 --> 03:36:02.520
fathomless afar,

03:36:01.319 --> 03:36:03.779
timeís

03:36:02.520 --> 03:36:07.380
eternal wing

03:36:03.779 --> 03:36:10.080
hath around those ruins cast the dark

03:36:07.380 --> 03:36:13.560
presence of the past.

03:36:10.080 --> 03:36:16.859
Thou dost build thy home on sand,

03:36:13.560 --> 03:36:20.460
and the palace-girdled strand

03:36:16.859 --> 03:36:23.939
fadeth like a dream.

03:36:20.460 --> 03:36:28.220
Thy great victories only show

03:36:23.939 --> 03:36:28.220
all is nothingness below.

03:36:32.420 --> 03:36:38.700
Thank you once again for listening to

03:36:35.580 --> 03:36:40.739
the Fall of Civilizations Podcast.

